<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Titans Release Kick Returner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The Tennessee Titans, needing some depth  
at tight end, released kick returner Roell Preston on Wednesday, 
two weeks after signing the Pro Bowler as an unrestricted free 
agent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Titans signed rookie tight end Larry Brown off the practice  
squad to replace Preston, and defensive end Keith Embray was added 
to the practice squad. Brown was signed to give the Titans a third 
tight end with Jackie Harris out indefinitely with a severe 
hamstring strain. 
</P>
<P>
	Wide receiver Derrick Mason replaces Preston as the Titans'  
primary returner on punts and kickoffs. Mason had the job until he 
had arthroscopic knee surgery on Sept. 11. For his career, the 1997 
fourth-round draft pick has averaged 20.7 yards on kickoff returns 
and 7.3 yards on punt returns. 
</P>
<P>
	In two games with Tennessee, Preston averaged 23.8 yards on  
kickoff returns and 7.4 yards on punt returns, ranking him seventh 
and ninth, respectively, in the AFC. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was the only option we had that we felt was workable,''  
coach Jeff Fisher said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mason is healthy again and can handle the returns. We couldn't  
go into a game with just two tight ends. It's not that we think 
Roell Preston cannot still be a productive returner in this league, 
but he hadn't had a training camp -- and we were forced to make a 
decision.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
