<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 01:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ramirez: Indians RBI Man-ny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Home run hoopla has baseball fans too busy  
watching Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire to realize what kind of show 
Manny Ramirez has put on this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has been unbelievable,'' Indians catcher Sandy Alomar said.  
``An RBI machine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quietly. That's how Ramirez goes about his business. No muss, no  
fuss. Just grab the bat and hit the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez, with little commotion, is having one of the most  
productive seasons in baseball history. But as fans again focus on 
the home run exploits of Sosa and McGwire, Ramirez's dizzying 
numbers are practically unnoticed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians right fielder has 160 RBIs.  
</P>
<P>
	That's 160 RBIs. No player in 61 years has done that.  
</P>
<P>
	``Manny is absolutely amazing,'' said Cleveland manager Mike  
Hargrove, a pretty fair hitter who never drove in more than 85 in a 
season. ``One hundred sixty RBIs? If you drive in 70 runs in a 
year, people talk about that as a good offensive year. And here 
Manny has more than doubled that. What he's done in two years is a 
career for most people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez has knocked in more runs in a season since Jimmie Foxx  
had 175 RBIs in 1938. And consider the season-high RBI totals for 
these Hall of Famers: Hank Aaron, 132; Willie Mays, 141; Ty Cobb, 
144; Ted Williams, 159; and Joe DiMaggio, 155. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez has 305 RBIs the past two seasons. He is one of only  
eight AL players ever to reach 160 RBIs in a year, and with six 
games remaining, he'll probably break Hal Trosky's club record of 
162 (1936). 
</P>
<P>
	If he can pick up 10 RBIs in Cleveland's final five games -- not  
an impossible task given he got eight Friday night and 12 last 
weekend -- Ramirez would be just the seventh player to reach 170. 
</P>
<P>
	``My goal is to get 90 or 100 RBI a season, and if I get more  
than that, I'm even more happy,'' said Ramirez, who went 2-for-3 
Tuesday night, but failed to drive in a run in Cleveland's 2-1 win 
at Kansas City. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the prospect of joining the company of the 170 club --  
Foxx, Hack Wilson, Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Hank Greenberg and Chuck 
Klein -- doesn't faze Ramirez. He just does his job, batting cleanup 
for baseball's best hitting team. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland needs 15 runs in its last six games to become seventh  
team to score 1,000 runs in a season, and the first since the 
Boston Red Sox in 1950. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just getting the right hits at the right time,'' he said.  
``Kenny Lofton, Omar Vizquel and Robbie Alomar are getting on base 
and doing an awesome job, but I also have to get the hits. They can 
get on base, but if I don't get the hits at the right time, they're 
not going to come home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez's RBI total would be higher still if he hadn't missed  
three games because of a suspension for charging the mound or six 
because of injuries. The missed games cooled him off to the point 
where he looked lost at the plate for long stretches. 
</P>
<P>
	In most years, Ramirez's stats would make him the front-runner  
for MVP. Not in 1999. In fact, Ramirez might not even be the 
Indians' MVP. 
</P>
<P>
	Pedro Martinez, Nomar Garciaparra, Derek Jeter and Rafael  
Palmeiro are all having outstanding years, as is Indians second 
baseman Roberto Alomar. 
</P>
<P>
	Lofton knows who gets his vote.  
</P>
<P>
	``Manny is MVP. If people don't vote for him it's a shame,'' he  
said. ``Guys need to write about him. He deserves MVP and that's 
the bottom line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What might hurt Ramirez is that he often draws attention with a  
bonehead defensive play or a baserunning mistake. 
</P>
<P>
	The 27-year-old outfielder hasn't made as many mental mistakes  
this season. But last Thursday night in Detroit, he loafed after a 
foul ball down the line and was promptly yanked by Hargrove. The 
manager reportedly chased him through the tunnel behind the dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez insisted his hamstring tightened, but Hargrove said  
Ramirez never told him that. Ramirez took care of any lingering 
controversy the next day by hitting a grand slam, a three-run homer 
and driving in a career-high eight runs in an 18-4 rout. 
</P>
<P>
	``Manny has done it all year long,'' Sandy Alomar said. ``He has  
been unreal.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
