<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 16:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Harding To Make Pro Skating Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) -- Two dozen people lined up to buy  
tickets Wednesday to Tonya Harding's return to the ice, a 
professional competition she says will give her a chance to show 
she can still skate. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years after receiving a lifetime ban from amateur  
competition for her role in the knee-bashing of chief rival Nancy 
Kerrigan, Harding will compete as a professional for the first time 
Oct. 18-19 in Huntington. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a little nervous because I haven't skated in front of an  
audience for some time,'' Harding said Wednesday from Portland, 
Ore. ``I'm sure there's going to be skeptics out there, but I'm 
sure the skeptical people would even like to see me skate. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was an amateur, I skated for myself. As a professional,  
I will do it for the fans. This is the way I can thank them and 
show them that I can still skate great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The event is expected to be a sellout, and fans who bought  
tickets at the 5,780-seat Huntington Civic Arena were excited about 
seeing her. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see anything wrong with it,'' Bob Berry said. ``We  
should be a forgiving people and understanding. Nancy Kerrigan's 
forgiven her. We should be tolerant enough to do the same thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think she's got guts,'' said Edna Holland, a self-described  
skating fanatic. ``She's had all these problems and she's still 
coming back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 28-year-old Harding says she has been training for seven  
months and can hit all her triple jumps except the triple axel. She 
is the only American woman to land that difficult jump in 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Harding announced her intentions in February, but it took a  
while for a promoter to bite. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been calling every professional event there is and it was  
just a question of who would have the guts to take her,'' Harding's 
adviser, Michael Rosenberg, said. ``Everybody was nervous to be the 
first one to put her in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kerrigan was whacked with a baton as she left the ice during  
practice at the 1994 U.S. championships in Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Harding's ex-husband, Jeff Stone, and two other men served time  
for planning and carrying out the attack. Harding avoided jail time 
despite her guilty plea to covering up the attack. She received a 
lifetime ban by the U.S. Figure Skating Association and apologized 
in person to Kerrigan. 
</P>
<P>
	Harding said fans won't see her and Kerrigan compete against  
each other again. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's happy and she has her baby. I've gone on with my life,''  
Harding said. ``I know everyone's going to associate with us being 
together, but we've moved on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kerrigan was skeptical about Harding's return to competition.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's been said before, so who knows? We'll see,'' Kerrigan  
said in Nashville, Tenn., where she was promoting a Nov. 23 skating 
exhibition. 
</P>
<P>
	The pair had appeared together for a network television  
interview last year. Kerrigan said she hasn't had contact with 
Harding since. 
</P>
<P>
	``What for?'' she said, laughing.  
</P>
<P>
	Harding has stayed busy as a skating coach, along with other  
ventures, including a low-budget movie as a waitress. She turned 
down an offer to wrestle in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	In February 1997, the same month she claims she was abducted by  
someone outside her Portland, Ore., home, Harding skated in a 
two-minute exhibition at a hockey game in Reno, Nev. 
</P>
<P>
	Next month will mark her debut in a pro competition. The USFSA  
has no jurisdiction over the event, which will be televised by ESPN 
on Oct. 25, Nov. 1 and Nov. 8. Others entered in the West Virginia 
competition are Elizabeth Manley, Surya Bonaly, Tonia Kwiatkowski 
and Pasha Grischuk. 
</P>
<P>
	For Kwiatkowski, who had said she would never skate again with  
Harding, time apparently has healed old wounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't care one way or another, I guess,'' Kwiatkowski  
said from Lakewood, Ohio. ``I guess you need to give her a chance. 
I look at her as being another competitor.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
