<HEADLINE> Black Leaders Enraged by Plea Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A coalition of black leaders have criticized a  
pending plea agreement that would give a 12-year prison sentence to 
a reputed mob hit man who has admitted taking part in 20 killings. 
</P>
<P>
	John Martorano has agreed to confess to the killings and, in  
doing so, implicate other gangsters, attorneys said. In exchange, 
he would receive a 12 1/2-year sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Black leaders upset over the deal pointed to comments in a  
newspaper column last year by a retired police officer that 
Martorano ``practically used black people for target practice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four of the 20 victims Martorano has acknowledged were black.  
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot allow this serial killer to kill people and then  
just walk,'' the Rev. Bruce Wall said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall was among a group of ministers, elected officials and  
community activists who contend Martorano may be behind more 
killings. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, they called for an investigation by the Boston  
police, Suffolk County prosecutors and the U.S. Attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Suffolk County District Attorney Ralph Martin, who participated  
in the deal, insisted there was no evidence that Martorano had 
committed any murders beyond the 20 to which he confessed. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston Police spokeswoman Margot Hill said Police Commissioner  
Paul Evans would discuss the request for an investigation with the 
district attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any information that comes to us outside the scope of the plea  
agreement, we will vigorously pursue with the district attorney,'' 
Hill said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall urged prosecutors to rescind the deal, which is scheduled  
to go before a federal judge later this week. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
