<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 09:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doctor Faces Murder Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FARMINGTON, Utah (AP) -- Autopsies on three elderly patients who  
died while in a doctor's care show they had lethal doses of 
morphine in their system, a prosecutor said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know each victim was given morphine in sufficient quantities  
to cause their death,'' Davis County Attorney Mel Wilson said after 
Dr. Robert Allan Weitzel's initial court appearance on charges that 
he killed five patients. 
</P>
<P>
	All five died between Dec. 30, 1995, and Jan. 14, 1996.  
Prosecutors say he prescribed massive doses of morphine for then 
while he was director of a geriatric-psychiatric unit run by 
Houston-based Horizons Mental Health Management Inc. at the Davis 
Hospital and Medical Center in Layton. 
</P>
<P>
	According police, none of the five had ailments that might have  
caused death or required morphine. 
</P>
<P>
	Three patients were exhumed and the Utah Medical Examiner  
performed autopsies. Investigators don't plan to exhume the two 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson said the medical examiner will testify that, in at least  
one of the three autopsied cases, the death was a homicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the first-degree felony murder charges carries a  
sentence of five years to life. A preliminary hearing has been set 
for January. 
</P>
<P>
	Weitzel, 43, sat quietly throughout Wednesday's hearing.  
</P>
<P>
	He remains free on $100,000 bail. He was arrested last week at  
Bay City, Texas, and returned to Utah voluntarily. 
</P>
<P>
	Weitzel also was charged in federal court with 22 counts of  
fraudulently obtaining prescription pain killers. In July, the Drug 
Enforcement Administration sought to have Weitzel's license to 
prescribe drugs revoked. A DEA affidavit alleged that he used 
illegally obtained drugs for himself. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 08:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Serbs Block Main East-West Highway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serbs blocked Kosovo's main  
east-west highway for a second day today, demanding better security 
following a grenade attack in an outdoor market that killed three 
Serbs and injured dozens. 
</P>
<P>
	Four people, two ethnic Albanians and two others who were  
unidentified, were detained in the attack, which occurred Tuesday 
in the Serb-populated town of Kosovo Polje, NATO spokesman Maj. Ole 
Irgens said. 
</P>
<P>
	But U.N. spokeswoman Daniela Rozgorova said the two ethnic  
Albanians were questioned and released. 
</P>
<P>
	Rozgorova also said three U.N. workers reported missing since  
Monday in northwest Kosovo had been arrested by Yugoslav police and 
taken to the Yugoslav town of Kraljevo. It was not known why they 
were detained. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, two workers of the World Food Program were  
detained by Serb police in northern Kosovo. They were freed later. 
</P>
<P>
	Tensions between NATO peacekeepers and Kosovo's Serb minority  
rose after the grenade attack, which Serb community leader Dusan 
Ristic blamed on the officially disbanded Kosovo Liberation Army. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to the attack, Serbs blocked Kosovo's main highway  
on Tuesday, backing up hundreds of vehicles for miles on the road 
from the provincial capital of Pristina to Pec. British soldiers 
prevented civilian traffic from reaching the roadblock. 
</P>
<P>
	Up to 30 Serbs were still manning a barricade today and not  
letting anyone pass. There was no sign of KFOR, the international 
peacekeeping force. Russian soldiers were seen about a half-mile 
away. 
</P>
<P>
	Rozgorova said today 47 people were injured in the grenade  
attack and treated in the Kosovo Polje hospital Tuesday. Head nurse 
Jasmina Brocic said today that one of three people evacuated to Nis 
died last night, bringing the death toll to three. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. chief administrator Bernard Kouchner strongly condemned the  
grenade attack and said it undermines efforts to transform Kosovo 
into a multiethnic society. 
</P>
<P>
	``This outrageous act against innocent civilians puts in danger  
all efforts at democracy in Kosovo,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The political leader of the officially disbanded Kosovo  
Liberation Army, Hashim Thaci, also condemned the ``inhuman'' 
attack ``no matter who committed it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other violence, one man was shot and killed and another was  
wounded after a quarrel in a bar in Decani on Tuesday, peacekeeper 
spokesman Irgens said today. Four Albanians were arrested Tuesday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on Tuesday, an Albanian girl was killed in an explosion,  
Irgens said. It was not clear if a mine or a grenade exploded. 
Irgens also said that two Serb teachers were missing in the town of 
Urosevac. 
</P>
<P>
	In Belgrade, the Yugoslav government blamed the grenade attack  
on NATO and U.N. for transforming the former rebel KLA into the 
Kosovo Protection Corps. NATO and the United Nations say the new 
corps is a civilian organization, but Yugoslavia said the attack 
proves the KLA has not demilitarized. 
</P>
<P>
	``The KLA may recently have changed its name and undergone  
cosmetic alterations, but it continues to spread terror and thus 
prevails in Kosovo,'' said Stanimir Vukicevic, Yugoslavia's liaison 
with NATO and the United Nations, according to the state Tanjug 
news agency. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 07:40:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Actor Seeks Parkinson's Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Actor Michael J. Fox told a Senate hearing  
Tuesday that he had hidden his Parkinson's disease for eight years 
``through increasing amounts of medication, through surgery, and by 
employing the hundreds of little tricks and techniques a person 
with Parkinson's learns to mask his or her condition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Fox, urging Congress to increase funding into the causes of  
the incurable ailment, said his days of quietly ``soldiering on'' 
were over. ``The war against Parkinson's is a winnable war, and I 
am resolved to play a role in that victory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke before a crowded hearing of a Senate Appropriations  
subcommittee chaired by Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox joined other Parkinson's advocates urging Congress to  
increase research funding for the disease by $75 million. In 1997, 
Congress authorized the National Institutes of Health to use $100 
million to study the disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox, 38, last year made public that he had been suffering from  
Parkinson's disease since 1991. He said he first noticed a twitch 
in his left little finger while on the set of the film ``Doc 
Hollywood.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parkinson's disease is a degenerative neurological disorder that  
destroys brain cells that produce dopamine, a chemical important 
for movement. Symptoms include muscle stiffening, tremors and 
difficulty moving. 
</P>
<P>
	The disease affects about 1 million Americans, including former  
heavyweight boxing champion Muhammad Ali and Attorney General Janet 
Reno. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox is the current star of the ABC sitcom ``Spin City.'' He has  
also had starring roles in the ``Back to the Future'' movies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 10:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Wary of Islamic Rebel Ploys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- While Russian jets bombed Chechnya again  
today, officials said Islamic militants might stage new attacks in 
Russia by slipping across the border among refugees fleeing the 
airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 60,000 people have abandoned their homes since Russian jets  
began bombing the Chechen capital of Grozny and nearby regions a 
week ago. The airstrikes today again hit communications centers, 
ammunition depots, and oil and industrial facilities, the Russian 
Defense Ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chechen officials claimed 10 people were killed during today's  
raids. The Russian Defense Ministry said all the casualties were 
militants. The Chechens say 300 civilians have died in strikes so 
far. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscow says the strikes are aimed against Chechnya-based Islamic  
rebels who twice invaded the neighboring republic of Dagestan in 
August and September. The militants have also been blamed for a 
series of apartment explosions in Russia that killed some 300 
people in recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The raids have fueled fears that Moscow is planning a major  
ground operation in Chechnya, which could mean a repeat of the 
disastrous 1994-96 war with Chechen separatists. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials have denied they plan to send in ground troops. But  
the Interfax news agency today quoted an unidentified Defense 
Ministry source as saying preparations for a ground operation have 
entered their final stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the airstrikes began, Russia said up to 2,000 militants  
were gathered along the border of Dagestan in preparation for a new 
invasion. Russian commanders said the militants' supply lines and 
bases must be destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian Defense Ministry spokesman Sergei Pryganov said today  
that around 2,000 refugees have fled east from Chechnya toward 
Dagestan. 
</P>
<P>
	That has made the situation at the border chaotic, he said,  
because the refugees were trying to enter Dagestan at crossings 
where the militants were gathered. The guerrillas could try to 
infiltrate the border posing as refugees, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities were letting some refugees across, but only after  
strict document checks. The refugees were being accommodated in 
tent camps in Dagestan, Pryganov said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of those fleeing Chechnya have fled west into the  
neighboring Russian region of Ingushetia, and several regional 
leaders have warned of an impending humanitarian crisis because of 
the refugee influx. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin urged  
negotiations with Chechnya, saying the republic's leaders must 
``show a constructive approach and the willingness to free their 
territory of bandit gangs,'' Interfax reported. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 20:16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  UN To Proceed With E. Timor Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United Nations will go ahead with a  
human rights inquiry into atrocities committed in East Timor 
despite Indonesia's rejection of the probe, the U.N. spokesman said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. investigators would like to have the cooperation of  
Indonesia's own human rights organization and access to Indonesia's 
military, but neither is required for the inquiry to go forward, 
spokesman Fred Eckhard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia's Justice Minister Muladi said Wednesday that the  
Indonesian government rejected the inquiry and would issue a 
government decree saying so. Indonesia has said it should be 
allowed to investigate the reports that its army and army-supported 
militias were involved in widespread killings and pillaging 
following a vote on East Timor's independence Aug. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia's foreign minister said Wednesday that some violence  
was inevitable and that the United Nations had to go ahead with the 
ballot or risk the world's condemnation for having denied East 
Timor's people the right to choose their future. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia might also never again have agreed to allow the East  
Timorese to decide whether they wanted to remain part of the 
country or become independent, Alexander Downer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Could it have ever been resolved in an environment of perfect  
harmony and peace? The answer to that is `no', it couldn't have 
been,'' Downer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Passions were too high and East Timor's history too violent to  
have allowed for an easy vote or an easy transition to either 
independence or special autonomy within the country, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But that didn't mean it should never be resolved. And those  
who say the ballot shouldn't have taken place are people who say 
the East Timor situation shouldn't be resolved,'' he told reporters 
after speaking before the U.N. General Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	As he spoke, the United Nations moved ahead with plans to start  
taking over some civilian control of East Timor to try to get the 
territory's water, sanitation, transport and communications systems 
going again. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas met Wednesday with senior  
U.N. officials to discuss what the United Nations could do in the 
month before Indonesia formally hands the territory over to a 
transitional U.N. authority, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Portuguese Ambassador Antonio Monteiro said the U.N. Security  
Council should expand the mandate of the mission currently in East 
Timor to allow it to start rebuilding the territory. But U.N. 
officials said that might not be necessary and could embarrass 
Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	In Geneva, the U.N. refugee agency said Wednesday that efforts  
to reach thousands of refugees in makeshift camps across the border 
in West Timor are going slowly. There have been reports of 
pro-Indonesian militias there harassing people in the camps, some 
of whom were shipped there against their will. 
</P>
<P>
	One member of a U.N.-led mission to West Timor set out on  
Wednesday for the border town of Atambua, which reportedly holds up 
to 100,000 people under militia control, the statement from U.N. 
High Commissioner for Refugees said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the provincial capital, Kupang, authorities were insisting on  
24 hours' advance notice to police from U.N. staff planning to 
visit the refugee camps. 
</P>
<P>
	UNHCR staff who went to a sports stadium in the city were  
accompanied by six policemen armed with automatic rifles and 
sticks. It held some 700 East Timorese, and another 300 were 
sheltering under tarpaulins around the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was enough food, water and sanitation facilities and no  
visible military or police presence in the area,'' UNHCR said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0023 </DOCNO>
