<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 09:10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Up on Export Hopes / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures pushed higher in early  
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade after Russia requested 
5 million tons of food aid from the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's appeal is for a variety of grains and commodities. It  
includes 1.5 million tons of corn, 1.5 million tons of feed wheat, 
1 million tons of milling wheat, 500,000 tons of soybeans, 500,000 
tons of soy meal and 100,000 tons of soy oil. 
</P>
<P>
	Talks between the two countries on the prospective donations  
will take place in October, and investors appear optimistic they 
will take place. Corn, wheat, soybean and oat futures all opened 
higher on the news. 
</P>
<P>
	Continued rainy weather in the Midwest that is delaying the corn  
and soybean harvests also helped nudge prices upward. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 2 cents to $2.87 3/4 a bushel;  
December corn rose 1/2 cent to $2.14 1/4 a bushel; December oats rose 1 
cent to $1.16 1/4 a bushel; November soybeans rose 3/4 cent to $4.91 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and pork futures both inched higher in early trading on the  
Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	October cattle rose .20 cent to 67.15 cents a pound; October  
feeder cattle rose .27 cent to 80.07 cents a pound; October lean 
hogs rose .13 cent to 48.55 cents a pound; February frozen pork 
bellies rose .08 cent to 63.65 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thomas Jefferson's Scrapbooks Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) -- Scholars believe four scrapbooks  
uncovered by a history professor were put together by Thomas 
Jefferson and offer further insight into the life of the nation's 
third president. 
</P>
<P>
	The red leather-bound books contain thousands of newspaper  
articles from all over the East Coast dating to Jefferson's 
presidency, from 1801-08. They indicate that Jefferson was more 
sentimental that scholars have thought. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers once believed the scrapbooks were put together by  
Jefferson's granddaughters but recently discovered that some 
notations on the clippings match Jefferson's handwriting. Some 
clippings are pasted on envelopes with Jefferson's address. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are confident these books were compiled by Jefferson  
himself,'' said James Horn, director of the International Center 
for Jefferson Studies in Charlottesville. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert M.S. McDonald, a professor at the U.S. Military Academy  
at West Point, N.Y., found the 6-by-9-inch books this summer at the 
University of Virginia's Alderman Library while doing research. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was stunned,'' McDonald said. ``I realized that they not  
only belonged to Jefferson, but also that they were Jefferson's 
creation. It is not every day that new Jefferson materials come to 
light. And these are a treasure trove of information.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McDonald found an oak leaf pressed into one book between an  
article on friendship and a poem titled ``Scenes from My Youth.'' 
Jefferson and his boyhood friend, Dabney Carr, played together on 
Monticello and used to study under an oak tree. 
</P>
<P>
	The two promised each other the survivor would bury the other  
under that tree. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was the genesis of the Monticello family graveyard,''  
McDonald said. Carr was the first buried where the oak tree was 
believed to have been. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers say one of the scrapbooks was given to the library  
in 1851. The three others were donated in 1951 by Jefferson family 
members. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 22:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Makes Fla. Bomb Case a Priority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- FBI agents tracking a bomber suspected  
of twice hitting Florida A&AMP;M University say the case is the 
bureau's No. 1 priority in northern Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Two pipe bombs exploded at the predominantly black university  
Aug. 31 and Sept. 22, one in an administration building restroom 
and the other in a restroom surrounded by classrooms and offices. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither explosion caused any injuries, and the damage was  
slight. But many of the school's 12,000 students and its 
administrators fear they may be dealing with a serial bomber out to 
send a message. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have my pledge, until this case is solved, no stone will  
go unturned,'' Tom Kneir, head of the FBI's office in northern 
Florida, told students Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of city and county police officers have descended on the  
campus, patrolling streets and checking everyone's identification 
24 hours a day. 
</P>
<P>
	Surveillance cameras paid for by the state were being installed  
across campus Wednesday. And all buildings are being checked for 
suspicious items every morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Tallahassee Police Chief Walt McNeil assured students that they  
would be safe at Saturday's home football game against Morgan 
State. ``We're going to go into that stadium and comb it from head 
to toe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Jeb Bush said he has asked Attorney General Janet Reno for  
$388,000 to cover the cost of the extra security patrols until 
whoever is responsible for the bombings is caught. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 16:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patriots Kicker Shrugs Off Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- Pressure is Bill Parcells hinting your job  
is at stake if you miss a kick. Pressure is Justin Leonard hovering 
over a 45-foot putt with the Ryder Cup on the line. 
</P>
<P>
	There's little pressure, says Adam Vinatieri, in contemplating a  
field goal attempt that could win a game in the final minute. Not, 
as in Vinatieri's case, if you haven't missed all season. 
</P>
<P>
	The kicker for the unbeaten New England Patriots has made his  
last nine attempts -- seven this season -- and doesn't flinch in 
tight situations when his teammates are counting on him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just loving the opportunity to be out on the field,'' he  
said. ``I'd much rather be the one that's kicking it than the guy 
standing on the sideline watching their kicker kick it and hoping 
that he misses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vinatieri kicked at South Dakota State, then played for  
Amsterdam of the World League in 1996. He signed with the Patriots 
as a free agent before the 1996 season, with no guarantee of 
long-term employment. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the fourth game that season, Parcells, then the Patriots  
coach, discussed his rookie kicker with reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Probably the most pressure I've felt so far was probably the  
overtime kick against Jacksonville,'' Vinatieri said. ``The week 
before, Parcells said I was game-to-game, so you all know what that 
means.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he came through with five field goals, including a 40-yarder  
that gave New England a 28-25 overtime victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went, `He'll be happy with me today. We'll see about  
tomorrow,''' Vinatieri said. 
</P>
<P>
	This season, his field goals with three seconds and 35 seconds  
left won the Patriots' first two games. They won their third game 
16-14 over the New York Giants with his three second-half field 
goals last Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	That same day, Leonard sank a pressure putt on the 17th green  
that clinched the Ryder Cup for the United States over Europe at 
The Country Club in nearby Brookline. 
</P>
<P>
	``Leonard's putt was as big a game-winner, a 55-yarder in the  
Super Bowl-type thing,'' said Vinatieri, who just missed seeing it 
on television because he had to leave for his game. ``You can feel 
kind of what he's feeling and the pressures that he's feeling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vinatieri rarely seems flustered, even when fans are screaming  
for him to miss. He's made 90-of-110 field-goal attempts as a 
Patriot and last Sunday tied Gino Cappelletti's team record by 
making his 105th straight extra point. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's pretty much Mr. Automatic. You get down in his range and  
you know you're getting some points,'' wide receiver Shawn 
Jefferson said. ``If he had to make a 70-yarder, I'd bet money that 
he'd make it. That's the type of pressure player he is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We can just about ask him to do anything at the end of these  
games,'' coach Pete Carroll said. ``He feels very good about his 
work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vinatieri's longest field goal is a 58-yarder with three seconds  
left in the final exhibition game at Carolina. But the Patriots 
lost 23-20 on John Kasay's 61-yard field goal with no time left. 
Both connected with the harder footballs kickers are using compared 
to last season. 
</P>
<P>
	The 58-yarder ``gave me some confidence with the new balls,''  
Vinatieri said. ``I know a lot of the guys were concerned about how 
much distance it was going to'' cut from the kicks. 
</P>
<P>
	With quarterback Drew Bledsoe's ability to move the offense into  
scoring position, Vinatieri expects to get plenty of chances to add 
to his field-goal totals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I consider myself very fortunate to be on a team that scores a  
lot of points,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	His teammates consider themselves fortunate to have him.  
</P>
<P>
	``Adam is one of the best kickers in the game,'' Jefferson said.  
``The league knows that. We know that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 05:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fired Museum Guide Gets Job Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A museum guide who was fired because of the  
way she explained an explicit sculpture to a group of fifth-grade 
girls has been offered her job back. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art told Stephanie  
Riseley they regret the circumstances that led to her dismissal in 
May and congratulated her on the ``high quality'' of her job 
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	``We appreciate the strength of your commitment to public access  
and education,'' said Priscilla Gibbs, chairwoman of the museum's 
Docent Council, in a Sept. 14 letter. 
</P>
<P>
	Riseley was fired after she guided a tour from Hurley Elementary  
School past an Edward Kienholz sculpture entitled ``Back Seat Dodge 
'38,'' which featured life-size figures of a couple in a drunken 
embrace. 
</P>
<P>
	Riseley explained that the sculpture was an expression of an  
artist's first sexual experience and suggested Kienholz was telling 
viewers ``you only get one first sexual experience, so think before 
you act.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tour guide's explanation stunned the girls' chaperones and  
teacher. The school's principal complained to museum officials, who 
then fired Riseley. 
</P>
<P>
	The firing prompted complaints from some museum members and led  
to the threat of a defamation and freedom of speech lawsuit from 
the former docent. 
</P>
<P>
	Riseley said she was pleased to have her job back and ``my good  
name restored to me.'' But she said she didn't know when she would 
resume her tour work. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 12:20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Theories on Waco Siege </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For all the recent furor over the FBI's use of  
potentially incendiary tear gas canisters on the final day of the 
Waco siege, a lawyer suing the government on behalf of Branch 
Davidian survivors and relatives contends the inferno may have been 
triggered by other causes. 
</P>
<P>
	Cult leader David Koresh and some 80 followers perished during  
the fiery climax to the siege on April 19, 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Caddell, the lead lawyer in a wrongful-death lawsuit  
against the government, is wary of tying his legal case to the 
military canisters lobbed by federal agents. Alternate theories 
under examination include the possibility that the fire was caused 
by contact between exhaust from military tanks used in the assault 
and the flimsy wooden walls of the Davidians' compound, he said, 
adding that the exhaust could have reached 1,200 degrees 
Fahrenheit. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a number of possible explanations and I don't want  
to get sucked in too much into the whole pyrotechnic issue,'' 
Caddell said in a recent interview. ``It may turn out to be a red 
herring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal officials have always said the fire was set by the  
Davidians, not agents -- a position maintained after the FBI 
acknowledged last month that its agents fired a few pyrotechnic 
tear-gas projectiles on the siege's final day. There's no evidence 
those canisters, lobbed several hours before the fire, ignited the 
flames, they say. 
</P>
<P>
	That view is shared by an arson expert on the team that  
investigated the tragedy as part of the Justice Department's 1993 
Waco probe. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still say what we came to the conclusion on at the end of  
our investigation down there still holds today, regardless of what 
they are saying about these pyrotechnic devices,'' said Thomas 
Hitchings, chief deputy fire marshal in Allegheny County, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	Caddell and others who accuse the government of a cover-up are  
examining theories that: 
</P>
<P>
	--Military tanks that punched holes into the building to insert  
non-burning tear gas knocked over lanterns the Davidians relied on 
after the FBI cut off electricity. 
</P>
<P>
	--Flash-bang devices used by federal agents ignited the building.  
Filmmaker Michael McNulty, who has espoused that theory, claims 
such devices were found near the fire's origins. The government 
disputes his assertions. 
</P>
<P>
	--Heat from the tanks' exhaust could have ignited the dwelling's  
wooden walls, which were reinforced with makeshift barricades of 
hay bales. 
</P>
<P>
	Caddell said a special forces operative told him of once trying  
to warm his gloved hands beneath the exhaust from such tanks, only 
to see his leather gloves ignite. 
</P>
<P>
	But a spokesman for General Dynamics Land Division, which  
manufactured the M728 Combat Engineer Vehicles used at Waco, said 
the tanks' diesel engines produce heat that ``does not get hot 
enough to start a fire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Janet Reno insists the fire was set by the  
Davidians. But stung by the FBI's recent disclosure, she named 
former Republican Sen. John Danforth of Missouri to investigate 
whether there was a cover-up or other wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI officials declined to address the scenarios suggested by  
Caddell and other skeptics, saying the fire's genesis has been 
extensively reviewed. And Danforth's inquiry ``would preclude us 
from making any comment,'' FBI spokesman Bill Carter said. 
</P>
<P>
	The independent arson investigators who combed the Waco ruins  
concluded the fire resulted from ``an intentional act'' by people 
inside the compound and that accelerants were used to speed the 
flames. 
</P>
<P>
	Fires were set in three locations, the team concluded. The fire  
began on the second floor's southeast corner, moments after a tank 
disengaged from that section's ground floor. Flames then were 
detected on the first floor's midsection and east side. 
</P>
<P>
	But former Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms arson  
investigator Richard L. Sherrow, hired by the plaintiffs, concluded 
the fire started in only one location, most likely when the tank 
rammed the southeast corner. 
</P>
<P>
	David Thibodeau, one of nine Davidians who survived the final  
assault, said he does not believe agents intentionally set the 
fire. But he blames the government for the conditions leading up to 
the tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although neither we nor the feds deliberately set Mount Carmel  
ablaze, the FBI must have been aware that the toxic brew they 
injected into our building in such enormous quantities would create 
a highly flammable condition that windy day,'' he writes in his new 
book. 
</P>
<P>
	For Caddell, the debate over who triggered the inferno  
ultimately may prove academic in a lawsuit that accuses the 
government of using excessive force throughout the operation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not have to prove how the fire started to win our  
lawsuit,'' he said. ``But I think we will prove that the 
government's actions on April 19 contributed to the spread of the 
fire ... and the deaths of Davidians as a result of the fire.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
