<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Makes Fla. Bomb Case a Priority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- FBI agents tracking a bomber suspected  
of twice hitting Florida A&AMP;M University told students and Gov. Jeb 
Bush on Wednesday that the case is the bureau's No. 1 priority in 
northern Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Two pipe bombs exploded at the predominantly black university  
Aug. 31 and Sept. 22, one in an administration building restroom 
and the other in a restroom surrounded by classrooms and offices. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither explosion caused any injuries, and the damage was  
slight. But many of the school's 12,000 students and its 
administrators fear they may be dealing with a serial bomber out to 
send a message. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have my pledge, until this case is solved, no stone will  
go unturned,'' Tom Kneir, head of the FBI's office in northern 
Florida, told students Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of city and county police officers have descended on the  
hilltop campus, patrolling streets and checking everyone's 
identification 24 hours a day. 
</P>
<P>
	Surveillance cameras paid for by the state were being installed  
across campus Wednesday. And all buildings are being checked for 
suspicious items every morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Tallahassee Police Chief Walt McNeil assured students that they  
would be safe at Saturday's home football game against Morgan 
State. ``We're going to go into that stadium and comb it from head 
to toe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said he had asked Attorney General Janet Reno for $388,000  
to cover the cost of the extra security patrols until whoever is 
responsible for the bombings is caught. The governor said Reno had 
not committed, although he said she expressed sympathy and general 
support when he met with her in Washington last week. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
