<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU OKs Funding for BBC News Channel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- European Union regulators Wednesday  
ruled that public funding for the British Broadcasting Corp.'s 
24-hour television news channel does not breach EU rules on 
government subsidies. 
</P>
<P>
	In approving state funding for BBC News 24, the European  
Commission rejected a complaint from the channel's main competitor, 
Rupert Murdoch's Sky television. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commission ruled that the BBC's funding by license fees  
levied on all British television owners did constitute state aid, 
but it also ruled that subsidies for public service broadcasting 
could be exempt from EU restrictions on government handouts. 
</P>
<P>
	BBC News 24 was launched in 1997 and is delivered free of charge  
to cable and satellite operators in Britain. It is also shown on 
the terrestrial channel BBC1, in early morning hours after normal 
network programming ends. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
