<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Unmistakably' Mackie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bob Mackie has seen his life flash in front of  
his eyes: It's a purple, aqua and magenta cape decorated with a 
roulette wheel and draped over a white sequined wedding gown. 
</P>
<P>
	The Las Vegas wedding outfit, with its battery-operated blinking  
lights, is one of the most eye-catching pieces in ``Unmistakably 
Mackie,'' a glittering retrospective of the designer's work that 
will be on display at the Museum at the Fashion Institute of 
Technology through Dec. 31. The retrospective took more than a year 
to organize. It includes Mackie's childhood doodles, original 
sketches and designs from a career that has spanned nearly four 
decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Clothing designed for Cher and comedian Carol Burnett fill  
entire sections of the exhibit, which includes more than 125 
outfits and almost 20 of his special-edition Barbie dolls. Diana 
Ross, Madonna and ``Seinfeld'' regular Julia Louis-Dreyfus have 
been dressed by the ``Designer to the Stars.'' He has also dressed 
Mitzi Gaynor, Barbra Streisand, Liza Minnelli, Sharon Stone and 
RuPaul. 
</P>
<P>
	``You see things you haven't seen in a while and you think `not  
bad,''' Mackie said as he walked through the exhibit. 
</P>
<P>
	The retrospective includes the animal-print jumpsuit that Cher's  
``Laverne'' character wore on her 1970s variety series. The outfit 
is one of the designer's favorites. Mackie also created the sheer 
gown with black sequins that Cher wore when she accepted the Oscar 
for best actress (``Moonstruck'') in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	``The outfits are sometimes mistaken for fashion, but they're  
costumes like for a character in a play,'' said Mackie, shaking off 
criticism of Cher's often outlandish wardrobe. ``I want people to 
have fun. I want people to say `Wasn't that interesting?' or 
`Wasn't that wild?''' 
</P>
<P>
	Mackie created 22 to 24 glamorous dresses per season for the  
opening segment of Burnett's long-running variety show, along with 
dozens of costumes for the comedy sketches. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love doing funny things. One week I'd have to make Carol an  
unattractive postal worker, and who knows what I'd have to do the 
next,'' said Mackie, wearing an olive shirt, olive slacks and a 
black tie. 
</P>
<P>
	He designs miniature versions of his gowns for Barbie dolls.  
``Right now, I'm in my `international fantasy goddess' phase,'' he 
said. ``I don't do `Barbie goes to the supermarket.''' 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit's title is also the name of a new book and a new  
fragrance. 
</P>
<P>
	Mackie continues to dress Cher, Burnett and Ross. He created the  
``Elizabeth'' gown that Whoopi Goldberg wore when she hosted this 
year's Oscars. 
</P>
<P>
	Mackie, 59, is a seven-time Emmy Award winner. As a child, he  
was inspired by Hollywood's Technicolor movie musicals. Using a 
record as a soundtrack, he would create tabletop shows using 
hand-drawn puppets in elaborate costumes. He's been nominated for 
three Oscars. 
</P>
<P>
	He enjoys creating costumes and eveningwear. ``It is all about  
looking good and living your fantasies. You can dream you're a 
czarina or Hedy Lamarr.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
