<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ditka To Chicago: Get Over It </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- In Chicago, they still think of him as Da  
Coach of Da Bears. But Mike Ditka thinks only in terms of black and 
gold these days. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm the New Orleans Saints coach,'' Ditka said. ``It's where I  
want to be and it's where I want to stay. I don't live in the past. 
This is my team now and this is my city.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Saints play the Bears on Sunday in Chicago and, while people  
in the Windy City might still be mourning the loss of Iron Mike, 
Ditka is thinking about just one thing -- picking up his second win 
of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to go up there and win,'' defensive coordinator  
Zaven Yaralian said. ``That's been Mike's focus on the game. If 
it's any different than the other 15, he hasn't shown it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Much of Ditka's reputation was forged in Chicago -- as coach for  
11 years, he's second only to team founder George Halas in tenure 
and victories. During that time, the Bears dominated the NFC 
Central, won the division six times and the Super Bowl once. 
</P>
<P>
	Memories of victories and of Ditka stalking the sideline,  
screaming at players, coaches and officials, remain strong. It was 
the basis of many ``Saturday Night Live'' skits in which a group of 
blue-collar guys praised both ``Da Bears'' and ``Da Coach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a lot of great memories from Chicago and still have a  
lot of friends there,'' Ditka said. ``It will always be a special 
place for me. But you can't live in the past. I don't. This is my 
home now, the Saints are my team. I love this place and this team. 
They only way they'll get me out of here is to force me to leave.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Compared to the Chicago years, Ditka's reign in New Orleans has  
been unexceptional. He's made more headlines off the field than on 
-- criticizing the city, quitting -- then retracting it -- during his 
first year, and donning a dreadlocks wig and wedding attire after 
drafting Ricky Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	But now that he has the running back he wanted and has settled  
in (he's opening a New Orleans restaurant called ``Ditka's'' this 
fall), Ditka said the 6-10 records of his first two years and the 
Saints' status of being the only NFL team to never win a playoff 
game are destined to be over. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a good place, the people work hard, they're good  
people and they've been more than good to me,'' he said. ``Now I 
want to be the one to bring them a Super Bowl. I can do it with 
this organization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Winning a Super Bowl in New Orleans is probably what it will  
take to fully cement his new image, Ditka admits. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until that happens, we're not going to be as well known or  
remembered as what happened in Chicago,'' Ditka said. ``It'll 
happen here. I absolutely believe that. It will happen here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ditka's new team is forged along the lines of the Chicago team  
he remembers so fondly -- strong running back, journeyman 
quarterback, staunch defense. And he has stressed getting players 
with the kind of work ethic he nurtured with the Bears. These days, 
however, he refers to those blue-collar players as ``Boudreauxs,'' 
not ``Grabowskies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I was fortunate in Chicago because I had a lot of warriors,''  
Ditka said. ``You need a lot of warriors to win in this league. 
Guys have to have a lot of character. They have to have a lot of 
character when the going is tough. We have a lot of guys like that 
right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So Sunday, when Ditka walks onto the field in Chicago, he'll be  
focused on only one thing -- winning. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of silly, isn't it?'' Ditka said of the furor his  
return to face his old team stirs. ``What happened 15 years ago 
should have no bearing on what's going on now. It doesn't really. 
You can't take the past away from you, but you can't live in the 
past. I don't do that. It's just a football game.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
