<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asia stock markets closed mixed Wednesday, with  
the key indexes slipping in Tokyo and Hong Kong on profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 43.42  
points, or 0.25 percent, to close at 17,282.28. On Tuesday, the 
average closed up 504.64 points, or 3.00 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei fell as investors locked in profits following a surge  
in the stock market the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese stocks also came under moderate selling following an  
overnight decline on Wall Street, where the Dow Jones industrial 
average was down 27.86 points, or 0.2 percent, to 10,275.53 on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders say the market will remain cautious until the release of  
the Bank of Japan's quarterly survey of business sentiment on 
Monday and the U.S. Federal Reserve's policy board meeting, also 
next week. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 106.90 yen  
late Wednesday, up 0.38 yen from late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, the blue-chip Hang Seng Index slipped 10.04  
points, or 0.07 percent, closing at 12,834.89. On Tuesday, the 
index had gained 84.47 points, or 0.66 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said some investors took profits following losses  
overnight on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Concerns about the lack of progress on China's bid to join the  
World Trade Organization and a possible U.S. rate increase next 
week also dampened sentiment in Hong Kong, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korean share prices slumped, with the key index plunging  
3.5 percent on fears of a local interest rate hike. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korea Composite Stock Price Index fell 31.85 points to  
868.88. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Taiwan shares rose for the first time since last week's  
earthquake, as bargain hunters gradually came off the sidelines and 
bought up oversold chip stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taipei market's key Weighted Stock Price Index rose 37.60  
points or 0.5 percent, to 7,615.45. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed little changed. The  
benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index edged up 0.67 point to 2,015.71. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed higher, extending their gains  
for a second day. The Philippine Stock Exchange index of 30 
selected companies rose 10.98 points, or 0.5 percent, to 2,081.41. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian stock market closed lower, pressured by a  
wave of selling in the gold sector after its exceptional rally 
earlier in the week. The All Ordinaries Index closed at 2,897.8, 
down 22.8 points, or 0.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed lower in thin trading. The  
benchmark Straits Times Index fell 6.87 points, or 0.3 percent, to 
2,017.57. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares closed higher following some  
afternoon buying by government-linked institutional funds. The 
Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip stocks, rose 4.37 
points, or 0.6 percent, to 683.51. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares closed mixed as continued-profit  
taking in select blue chips dragged down the main index. The 
Composite Index fell 0.5 percent, or 2.752 points, to 526.469. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed higher. The Thailand SET Index  
rose 5.84 points, or 1.5 percent, to 391.07. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
