<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 23:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holyfield Mum on Lewis Rematch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Evander Holyfield ate his words the first time  
he fought Lennox Lewis, so ``mum'' is the word for the rematch. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be a prediction, I just won't let anybody know,''  
the WBA-IBF champion said Wednesday at a media luncheon to hype the 
Nov. 13 fight in the Thomas &AMP; Mack Center at Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	Holyfield said before he fought WBC champion Lewis on March 13  
in Madison Square Garden that he would win on a third-round 
knockout. 
</P>
<P>
	The fight ended in a draw, although most ringsiders thought  
Lewis won clearly, and led to a several hearings and a grand jury 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt the fight was even,'' said Holyfield, adding that he  
suffered abdominal cramps from a virus before the fight and leg 
cramps during the match. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why he didn't pull out of the bout, Holyfield said, ``When  
I train as hard as I trained for the fight, I'm going to fight. I 
never took so many chances in my life. I knew the reason I was 
getting hit so much was that I couldn't shift my legs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They call him a warrior,'' Lewis said. ``But all I can say is  
Evander always makes excuses after a poor performance. His only 
problem was me punching him. I still say Evander Holyfield has 
never seen a boxer like me, and he still don't have an answer for 
Lennox Lewis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis said that he was irked by people saying that while he won  
the fight, he should have knocked out Holyfield, but that he was 
too cautious. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look at all my fights, and you can see any time Lennox is put  
under pressure, he answers with pressure, with punches. He doesn't 
run into a hole.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis also said, however, ``I look at the tape of the fight and  
I see things I could have done and should have done, and in this 
fight I'll do them. I don't think this fight will go the 
distance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rematch in the Thomas &AMP; Mack Center will be a pay-per-view  
bout, as was the first fight for which Holyfield was guaranteed $20 
million and Lewis $10 million. Each is guaranteed $15 million in 
November. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 16:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> St. Mary's Coach Accused of Rape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. MARY'S CITY, Md. (AP) -- Othell Wilson, who played with Ralph  
Sampson at Virginia, has been accused of raping a student and was 
placed on leave as basketball coach at St. Mary's College. 
</P>
<P>
	He was arrested Monday and charged with abducting a 22-year-old  
woman and raping her at his apartment. The 38-year-old coach was 
being held without bond Wednesday at the St. Mary's County 
Detention Center in Leonardtown. He also faces charges of false 
imprisonment and assault. 
</P>
<P>
	A call to the home of a St. Mary's spokesman was not immediately  
returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson picked up the woman at her home in Fairfax County, Va.,  
for a date Friday night, St. Mary's County Sheriff's Lt. John Horne 
said. Police said he then drove the woman to his apartment in St. 
Inigoes, held her against her will until Sunday morning and hinted 
he had a knife. 
</P>
<P>
	``He told her that if she left, he would kill her,'' Horne said.  
``She is very, very afraid of this guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson then is accused of driving her home and threatening to  
kill her if she told anyone what happened, Horne said. The victim 
contacted police and was examined at a hospital in Fairfax County. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson joined St. Mary's as an assistant coach in 1998 and was  
promoted to head coach in August. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a point guard for Virginia and played on Final Four teams  
in 1981 and 1984. In the NBA, he played for Sacramento and Golden 
State. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
