<DOCNO> APW19990929.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 20:05:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Jockey Valenzuela Rides Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- A cheer went up as Patrick Valenzuela  
strode into Santa Anita's paddock ahead of the horses to ride his 
first race in two years Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	He was greeted by shouts of ``Way to go, Patrick,'' and ``We  
love you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fans, jockeys and horsemen knew they were witnessing what  
many believe is the final comeback of a talented jockey who won the 
1989 Kentucky Derby only to have his career implode because of 
drugs, alcohol, unexplained absences and run-ins with the police. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't screw up anymore, Pat,'' shouted Anthony Gonzales of El  
Monte. 
</P>
<P>
	Valenzuela, 36, seems to realize he won't be back on the track  
if something goes wrong this time. Five months ago, he was pulling 
weeds at a nursery for $10 an hour. Earlier this year, he spent 30 
days in jail before armed robbery charges against him were dropped. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as horse racing, this is my last chance,'' he said.  
``There's conditions on my license where there's no mistakes to be 
made.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Valenzuela didn't win with any of his four mounts on opening day  
of Santa Anita's Oak Tree meeting. He finished sixth, fourth and 
seventh on his first three. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm having a ball,'' he said between races. ``I feel like I  
won the big race already.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Riding the ironically named Holy Hope, Valenzuela was last among  
11 horses in the $100,000 Senator Ken Maddy Handicap -- the first 
stakes mount of his comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	``I basically feel like a bug boy (apprentice jockey) that just  
got his license,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's OK because I'm very excited about it and I feel like I'm  
totally jazzed to go out there and ride hard on any horse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Valenzuela charged out of the starting gate to the lead with his  
first two mounts, a familiar position for the rider known as a 
frontrunner. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's where P-Val likes to be. That's his patented spot, so  
he hasn't lost his touch,'' Hall of Fame rider Chris McCarron said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, he received a one-year jockey's license. Among the  
conditions under which he can ride are required attendance at 
twice-weekly counseling sessions, random drug testing and no 
unexcused absences. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they are watching me, it's OK,'' said Valenzuela, who  
claims he attends Alcoholics Anonymous four times a week. ``I 
invite them to watch me, I invite them to ask me any question 
they'd like because I'll answer it honestly and fully to the best 
of my knowledge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trainer Sanford Shulman took a chance on Valenzuela, just as the  
trainer has for Valenzuela's other comebacks over the last decade. 
Their friendship dates back 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``He really is down deep a very good person. He means well, but  
ufortunately, the demons sometimes get ahold of him,'' Shulman 
said. ``I want to help him as a person. He's not going to get many 
more chances from the horse racing board. It just makes sense that 
this is going to be the last shot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Valenzuela's agent, Nick Cosato, said he has 25 mounts in the  
first 11 days of the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Valenzuela, who said he weighed 149 pounds in May, rode at 118  
pounds Wednesday. To reach his goal of 116-117 pounds, he's eating 
one meal a day, usually salad with grilled chicken and non-fat 
dressing or chicken with a plain baked potato and plenty of water. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm cutting down a lot on my food. It takes a little bit out  
of your energy,'' he said. ``I'd say two or three weeks from now I 
will feel 100 percent the way I felt two years ago and maybe even 
better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone is wild about having Valenzuela around. Those with  
mixed feelings remember his positive drug tests, numerous 
suspensions and a 1988 fight in the jockey's room that left him 
with a broken hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``He knows that this is going to be probably his last chance and  
I really don't think he's going to blow it this time,'' Hall of 
Fame rider Laffit Pincay Jr. said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people probably don't like what's going on, but he keeps  
coming back and he keeps trying,'' Pincay said. ``If he had the 
guts to come back and face everybody, I don't see why I shouldn't 
wish him well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Valenzuela said he was surprised by the welcome reception from  
fans and horsemen, some of whom he burned in the past by missing 
riding commitments. 
</P>
<P>
	``These last two years have been hell, but it's getting sweeter  
every day,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 21:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schoolgirl Shot in Florida </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- A 10-year-old girl was shot in the head  
outside her school. She thought she had been struck by lightning, 
and she managed to get up and walk inside. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifth-grader Lauren Klingensmith was hit by a small-caliber  
bullet Monday. She was in fair condition Wednesday, though the 
bullet could not be removed. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said the bullet could have been fired from more than 50  
yards away. They didn't know whether Lauren's injury was the result 
of a reckless shooting, an accidental discharge or a deliberate 
attack. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
