<HEADLINE> Dollar Gains Against Yen Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar edged higher against the Japanese yen  
for a third straight day Wednesday, but fell sharply against the 
euro. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 106.98 yen,  
up from 106.10 yen on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0641, up from $1.0554 a day earlier.  
</P>
<P>
	The dollar has been rebounding against the yen following a  
weekend meeting by major industrial nations where officials issued 
a statement sharing Japan's concern over the yen's rapid advance. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen's sharp gains could derail Japan's recovery from a  
recession by making Japanese products more expensive overseas, 
cooling demand for that nation's exports. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Wednesday, the dollar was quoted at 1.5036  
Swiss francs, down from 1.5175 on Tuesday; and 1.4641 Canadian 
dollars, up from 1.4613 the day before. The British pound fell to 
$1.6442, down from $1.6502. 
</P>
<P>
	The currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are  
no longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed 
rate. Based on Wednesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8380 
German marks, down from 1.8534 on Tuesday; 6.1644 French francs, 
down from 6.2159; and 1,819.63 Italian lire, down from 1,834.63. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
