<HEADLINE> Japanese Firm Sued for Bid Rigging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department filed a civil lawsuit  
Wednesday against a Japanese electronics company accused of rigging 
bids on contracts for telecommunications systems at a U.S. military 
base in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit against Kyowa Exeo, the first to be filed under the  
Japanese Anti-Monopoly Act, accused the company of conspiring to 
fix bids on 25 contracts from 1981 to 1988 for work at the U.S. 
Pacific Contracting Office at Yokota Air Base, near Tokyo. The 
lawsuit seeks to recover damages worth about $19 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kyowa's liability for its participation in the bid-rigging  
conspiracy has been clearly established,'' David Ogden, the acting 
head of Justice's Civil Division, said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The case was filed in the Tokyo High Court.  
  	   	
</P>
