<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brockermeyer Back With the Bears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) -- For nine days, Blake Brockermeyer's  
head throbbed. 
</P>
<P>
	This was no ordinary headache. It wasn't even an ordinary  
migraine, if there is such a thing. This was a pounding headache so 
bad it hurt just to look at a light. A migraine so severe it put 
him in the hospital for three days and made him wonder if his 
football career was over. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was pretty scared,'' the Bears offensive tackle said  
Wednesday after practicing for the first time since leaving 
Chicago's Sept. 19 game against the Seattle Seahawks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just being in the hospital and not really knowing exactly  
what's causing all of this was kind of a concern for everyone,'' he 
added. ``Thank God, it went away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Brockermeyer's head began to hurt Sept. 16, he figured it  
was probably a migraine. He'd had one before -- although that one 
was much less severe -- so he wasn't overly concerned. 
</P>
<P>
	When it didn't go away, team doctors thought maybe it was a  
sinus infection. That didn't sound like a big deal, either, 
Brockermeyer thought, certainly not enough to keep him out of the 
Seattle game. 
</P>
<P>
	But as the game wore on, the pain got worse.  
</P>
<P>
	``Just a real painful, pressure-type, throbbing headache,'' he  
said. ``It was constant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors were at a loss to explain what was wrong. Brockermeyer  
was admitted to Northwestern Memorial Hospital, and numerous tests 
were done. A life-threatening illness was ruled out, but doctors 
couldn't tell him what was causing the headaches. 
</P>
<P>
	They did tell him football wasn't to blame, Brockermeyer said.  
Playing might have aggravated the pain, but it probably didn't 
cause it. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, doctors decided it was nothing more than a severe  
migraine and put him on medication. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just kind of takes its course,'' he said. ``The medication  
that they can give you for migraines, you kind of have to catch it 
right when it happens. We were a little bit late on that. They gave 
me some medication for the pain, but that just masked the headache. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just kind of went away on its own. Hopefully, it's gone  
forever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If it is, Brockermeyer will be more fortunate than Denver  
Broncos running back Terrell Davis, who takes daily medication to 
prevent the migraines he's suffered since he was a child. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis missed almost the entire second quarter of Super Bowl  
XXXII with a migraine. He went back into the game after taking some 
medicine, rushed for three touchdowns and was named the MVP in 
Denver's 31-24 victory over Green Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something more serious than it sounds,'' said Bears  
utility man Glyn Milburn, who played with Davis in Denver. ``It's 
not just a headache where you take some aspirin and a couple of 
hours later you're OK. They affect a lot of people and they can be 
debilitating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides missing practice last week, Brockermeyer had to cancel  
the kickoff for his Blake W. Brockermeyer Foundation, a charitable 
organization to benefit children in Chicago and Fort Worth, Texas. 
The pain went away last Friday, but he sat out Sunday's game at 
Oakland as a precaution. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors can't tell Brockermeyer whether the headaches will come  
back, so he's trying to go back to his normal life -- football 
included. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it comes back, I'll be a little bit upset. But so far, so  
good,'' he said. ``I'm going to go out and play like I've always 
played. If it comes back and something happens, I'll just have to 
deal with it when it comes. 
</P>
<P>
	``But right now, I'm not anticipating that. I'm just going to go  
out there and do my thing and just let the Lord take care of what's 
going to happen.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
