<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Veteran Tackle Ball Back With Vikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- The Minnesota Vikings are starting to  
look like the team they were a year ago, at least on the defensive 
line. 
</P>
<P>
	Run-stuffing veteran nose tackle Jerry Ball, who signed with  
Cleveland as a free agent in the offseason after spending two years 
in Minnesota, returned to the Vikings on Wednesday in a trade with 
the Browns. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dwight asked me what I thought,'' Ball said, referring to  
Dwight Clark, Cleveland's director of football operations. ``I'm 
like, `Shoot, do it. Give me an opportunity to go on and finish up 
on a better note.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns received third-year defensive end Stalin Colinet and  
a seventh-round pick in next year's draft. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings assumed Ball's two-year, $2.6 million contract.  
</P>
<P>
	``It just gives us more depth,'' coach Dennis Green said.  
``Jerry was one of our top players last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The return of the 300-pound Ball, along with that of 37-year-old  
end Chris Doleman a week earlier, gives the struggling Vikings a 
versatile and veteran defensive line. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the biggest thing is we went from being a young  
defensive line that was trying to learn its way to being an 
experienced group now,'' defensive line coach Andre Patterson said. 
``When you can add Chris Doleman with all his years of experience 
and now Jerry Ball, already in there with Joe Phillips and John 
Randle, you know, that's a bunch of guys who have been through a 
whole lot of games in the NFL.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ball, 34, a 13-year veteran and three time Pro-Bowler, had 15  
tackles for losses last season, tied with teammate Ed McDaniel for 
the league lead. He started 25 consecutive games at nose tackle for 
the Vikings in the past two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent weeks, the fun-loving Ball had become more evasive  
with reporters in Cleveland and had begun to regret leaving 
Minnesota after seeing the expansion Browns were planning to use 
younger players to build for the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was tough and I can tell you that I regretted it and I felt  
that it was a mistake,'' Ball said. ``But in this business you have 
to go ahead and make decisions based on the circumstances at the 
time. And at that point, there wasn't any money under the salary 
cap here. So, that pretty much put me on the outs. I had to take 
the deal that was available.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, he's back in his element.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's just hitting the recall button,'' Ball said. ``I think  
the first thing I have to do right now is get out there and get a 
good thud and let guys know that I'm still Jerry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the Tampa Bay Buccaneers coming to town Sunday with their  
rushing punch of Mike Alstott and Warrick Dunn, the timing of 
Ball's return was impeccable. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bucs handed the Vikings their only regular season loss last  
year by rushing the ball effectively and keeping Minnesota's 
high-octane offense on the sideline in a 27-24 thriller at Tampa. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know he's looking forward to having another crack at them,''  
Patterson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The additions of Doleman and Ball, along with recent  
reacquisitions of veterans Corey Miller and Mike Morris, show the 
Vikings mean business, cornerback Jimmy Hitchcock said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just know that the time is now to get things done,''  
Hitchcock said. ``It's not like we're trying to do this tomorrow. 
It's right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ball started his career with Detroit, then played for the old  
Browns in 1993 before moving to the Raiders and then Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Ball appeared to have lost about 20 pounds since leaving the  
Vikings. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's in real good shape. He's smaller than he was a year ago  
at this time,'' Patterson said. ``So, obviously they conditioned 
him pretty well over there in Cleveland. But I mean, hey, he's 
Jerry. First day back he's making smart comments to guys and 
practiced hard and held down the middle well. We're just excited to 
have him back.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
