<DOCNO> APW19990929.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 13:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Education Goals Not Being Met </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An ambitious education plan set a decade ago  
by government and business leaders has failed to meet its goals of 
raising youngsters' skill levels and producing world-class students 
in math and science, says a key figure in the effort. 
</P>
<P>
	That deflating message is what executives and governors are  
likely to hear at an education summit Thursday in Palisades, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something that has been troublesome for all of the  
governors, Republican as well as Democrat, as well as to the nation 
at large,'' said Republican Gov. Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin, who 
with IBM chairman Louis Gerstner Jr. is heading the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson remembers the excitement in 1989, when President Bush  
met with governors and business leaders and set six broad education 
goals for 2000 -- from ensuring children are properly immunized and 
eating the right foods so they are ready to learn, to raising the 
high school graduation rate to at least 90 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics said the goals were vague. Governors thought otherwise  
and adopted them. 
</P>
<P>
	The third education summit this week will assess progress on  
those goals -- included some added since President Clinton took 
office, Thompson said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	While Bush launched the education reform package, Clinton, who  
headed the governor's association at the time, has popularized the 
goals with more than $1.7 billion in grants to help states set 
standards and find ways to chart progress. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton signed the Goals 2000: Educate America Act in 1994,  
writing the original education goals into law and adding new ones 
on teacher quality and parent involvement. 
</P>
<P>
	In Georgia, Goals 2000 support for school reform has been  
described as a ``turning point.'' Democratic Gov. Thomas Carper of 
Delaware has said improved test scores in his state show ``we're on 
the right track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	North Carolina and Texas have been recognized for creating  
national models for boosting student achievement. West Virginia was 
praised for reaching one national goal by increasing the high 
school graduation rate for people ages 18 to 24 from 83 percent in 
1990 to 90 percent this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Education Secretary Richard Riley said recently, ``We've  
eliminated the tyranny of low expectations for children by placing 
high standards for academic achievement at the heart of education 
reform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet, American students have not caught up to high-performing  
children in other countries, according to the National Education 
Goals Panel, a committee of governors, legislators and federal 
officials that measures the goals' progress. 
</P>
<P>
	Only in fourth-grade science did the United States lead the  
world, according to the Third International Mathematics and Science 
Study. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. James Jeffords, chairman of the Senate Health, Education,  
Labor and Pensions Committee, suggests educators replicate programs 
that work and discard failing ones. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was always the perception that we were the biggest, the  
strongest, therefore the best,'' said Jeffords, R-Vt. ``But that's 
not necessarily true. We have to make tough decisions and 
substantial changes if we are to succeed. 
</P>
<P>
	Some contend the goals have led to successes.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, just 14 states had set standards for learning --  
essential information students should know in certain subjects by a 
particular grade. Today, 49 states have such standards. 
</P>
<P>
	State spending for education is up and more states issue public  
report cards on schools, require tests for students' to graduate or 
move on to the next grade, punish low-performing schools and reward 
those who do well. 
</P>
<P>
	``We learn with and from each other,'' said Thompson. ``That's  
one of the main reasons to have these summits.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 20:03:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dudley Moore Has Brain Disorder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST ORANGE, N.J. (AP) -- Dudley Moore is beginning to have  
vision problems as an incurable degenerative brain disorder he has 
had for several years progresses, his doctors said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore, 64, was diagnosed several months ago with progressive  
supranuclear palsy, a rare disorder related to Parkinson's disease, 
said Dr. Thomas Galski, who has been working with Moore at the 
Kessler Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's in the very early stages of this disease, but vision  
problems have started to creep in,'' Galski said. He said Moore was 
undergoing physical and speech therapy. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore, known for the 1981 movie ``Arthur,'' said in a statement  
Wednesday: ``I understand that one person in 100,000 suffers from 
this disease, and I am also aware that there are 100,000 of my 
union, the Screen Actors Guild, who are working every day. I think, 
therefore, it is in some way considerate of me that I have taken on 
this disease for myself, thus protecting the remaining 99,999 SAG 
members from this fate.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
