<DOCNO> APW19990929.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 08:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kobe Steel To Build in Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Kobe Steel Ltd., a major Japanese steel and  
aluminum maker, said today it will build two chemical plants in 
Saudi Arabia worth a combined $160 million. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be Kobe Steel's first project in Saudi Arabia, said  
company spokesman Gary Tsuchida. 
</P>
<P>
	The final contract on the project will be concluded with Saudi  
Arabia's Arabian Industrial Development Co., or NAMA, next month, 
Tsuchida said. 
</P>
<P>
	The facilities -- one with an annual production capacity of  
70,000 metric tons of chlor-alkali and the other with a capacity of 
30,000 metric tons of epichlorohydrin per year -- will be built in 
the Al-Jubail Industrial City on the Persian Gulf about 60 miles 
northwest of Dhahran. 
</P>
<P>
	Chlor-alkali is used to make caustic soda, used in synthetic  
fibers, perfumes, pharmaceuticals, soap, paper and pulp. 
Epichlorohydrin is used in making epoxy resin which is used in 
paints, adhesives and protective covering materials. 
</P>
<P>
	Construction of the two plants will be completed by January  
2002, Tsuchida said. NAMA will sell both caustic soda and epoxy 
resin in Saudi Arabia and neighboring countries, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
