<HEADLINE> Facts on Bell's Long-Distance Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Facts about Bell Atlantic's application to offer long-distance  
phone service in New York: 
</P>
<P>
	--Bell Atlantic wants to offer long-distance service to more than  
8 million homes and businesses in New York, which has an $8 
billion-a-year long-distance market. 
</P>
<P>
	--More than 400 companies are authorized to provide long-distance  
telephone service in New York, but the market is dominated by AT&AMP;T, 
Sprint and MCI. 
</P>
<P>
	--Bell Atlantic says competitors are providing 1 million local  
phone lines in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Federal Communications Commission has three months to  
decide on the application. If approved, Bell Atlantic could get 
into the long-distance market at any time after that. 
</P>
<P>
	--Bell Atlantic has a total of more than 43 million telephone  
lines in its local service region that covers 13 states and the 
District of Columbia, and it hopes eventually to offer 
long-distance in the other parts of its local service area. It also 
has nearly 10 million wireless customers. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
