<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Moves To Help Poor Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton told a gathering of finance  
ministers and central bankers today the United States will take a 
major step to help wipe out the debt owed by some of the world's 
poorest countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``Simply put, unsustainable debt is helping to keep too many  
poor countries and poor people in poverty,'' the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am directing my administration to make it possible to  
forgive 100 percent of the debt these countries owe to the United 
States, when needed to help them finance basic needs and when the 
money will be used to do so,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The president spoke at a Washington hotel before the annual  
meeting of the heads of the World Bank and the International 
Monetary Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton noted the international organizations are meeting at a  
dramatically different time than last year, when Asia's economy was 
plunging and fears of a global crisis were spreading. Clinton said 
it was perhaps the most severe crisis since World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	But now, the president said, ``Economies that were sliding are  
rising again.'' Still, he said, countries that were hit by the 
crisis were hit very hard and ``many are still reeling.'' He said 
it was ``certainly not a time for complacency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He lamented that 1.3 billion people survive on less than $1 a  
day and that nearly 40 million people die of hunger each year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope we will start the new millennium with a new resolve, to  
give every person in the world, through trade and technology, 
through investments in education and health care, the chance to be 
part of a widely shared prosperity in which all the people's 
potential can be developed more fully,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said it was a challenge for the IMF and World Bank. ``And for  
me, it is a personal priority of the highest order.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said poor nations need not always be impoverished.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we can in good conscience say we support the  
idea that they should choose between making interest payments on 
their debt and investing in their children's education,'' the 
president said. ``It is an economic and moral imperative that we 
use this moment of global consensus to do better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want this to wind up being like our dues to the United  
Nations, Clinton said. ``Now that we have advocated this and gotten 
everyone else to agree to it, we have to pay our fare share, so I 
hope all of you will help us pass the legislation through Congress 
to do just that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United Nations says the United States owes $1.6 billion in  
back dues and legislation in the Republican-controlled Congress to 
pay the arrears is stalled again this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton played a major role in urging partners from the wealthy  
industrialized nations to provide quicker, faster and deeper debt 
relief to poor countries at the Cologne summit in June. 
</P>
<P>
	British Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown, the head of  
the IMF's policy-making Interim Committee, told the IMF-World Bank 
meeting the debt relief initiative ``signaled a worldwide alliance 
against poverty. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said that in the wake of allegations about alleged  
misuse of IMF funds by Russia the organization must ``review its 
procedures and controls to strengthen the safeguards'' on use of 
its money. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF has warned no more of its money would be disbursed to  
Russia until the government and the central bank prove they were 
serious about battling corruption and publish quarterly central 
bank audits. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has denied any IMF funds were used illegally and  
complained the industrialized nations were treating it unfairly. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the controversy, IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus  
said the international community should not stop working with 
Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be the height of irresponsibility to turn our back on  
this great nation,'' Camdessus said. He said the economic program 
that Russia and the IMF agreed on was on track and real progress 
had been made in the past seven years in helping the government 
develop a market economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Camdessus and James Wolfensohn, president of the World  
Bank, urged the international community to do more to fight global 
poverty. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
