<HEADLINE> Knicks' Sprewell Explains Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARTINEZ, Calif. (AP) -- Latrell Sprewell says his bad judgment  
was to blame for a car crash last year in which two people were 
hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Knicks guard is being sued by Arnulfo Perlas, 55,  
and Irma Feliciano, 54, who were treated and released for minor 
injuries after the crash. Both have testified they have problems 
with nightmares and depression caused by the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell told a jury in Contra Costa Superior Court Wednesday  
that he used bad judgment when he lost control of his Mercedes 
Benz. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously it was the wrong thing to do,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell admitted in court that he caused the accident when he  
tried to get back on the freeway from an exit-only lane near Walnut 
Creek. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked if he made a mistake, Sprewell answered, ``Without a  
doubt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The civil suit went before a jury this week after repeated  
attempts to reach a settlement were unsuccessful. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell pleaded no contest to reckless driving in connection  
with the crash and was sentenced to 90 days in jail, which he 
served under electronic home detention at his Milwaukee home. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
