<DOCNO> APW19990929.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 08:03:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA Approves Metal Bat Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The speed of a baseball hit with a metal bat  
would not be greater than one hit with wood under new standards 
adopted Tuesday by the NCAA. 
</P>
<P>
	The association's executive committee affirmed a recommendation  
made last month by a research panel to limit the exit speed of 
metal bats to 97 mph in games involving NCAA schools for at least 
three years, starting in January. 
</P>
<P>
	``The moratorium will give the baseball community time to adjust  
to the new standards and for the panel to do further research,'' 
said Charles Wethington, University of Kentucky president and NCAA 
executive committee chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, we reserve the right to make adjustments in the  
standards for bats and balls at any time if necessary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to make metal bats perform more like wood, the panel  
recommended a batted-ball exit speed be adopted for non-wood bats 
equivalent to the highest average speed using major league-quality 
34-inch solid wood bats, which is less than 97 mph. The executive 
committee received the report in August but delayed implementing 
the panel's recommendations pending further tests. 
</P>
<P>
	Many college teams last season went to smaller aluminum bats,  
one of the recommendations by the panel, to increase safety and to 
reverse a trend of higher scoring than with wood bats, which broke 
easily. 
</P>
<P>
	Early metal bats were heavy and only the strongest players could  
generate much speed in their swing. But in recent years, 
manufacturers have refined their products to make them lighter and 
capable of producing power from a larger area of the bat. A 
well-hit ball off an aluminum bat can reach speeds of more than 100 
mph. 
</P>
<P>
	A record 62 home runs were hit in last year's College World  
Series and the tournament ended with Southern Cal's 21-14 victory 
over Arizona State. In this year's 14-game College World Series, 
with the smaller bats in use, there were only 35 homers, and the 
164 total runs were the fewest since 1994. In the title game, Miami 
beat Florida State 6-5, with each team hitting just one home run. 
</P>
<P>
	In a related matter, Easton Sports, Inc., announced it has  
settled its lawsuit against the NCAA connected to the 
organization's August 1998 ruling restricting the use of aluminum 
bats. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that a number of our bats have already been tested  
and meet the new standard confirms that aluminum bats can be very 
safely used in NCAA and all other levels of play,'' Jim Easton, 
chairman of Easton Sports, said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the settlement agreement, no financial figures were  
released. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA also approved specifications recommended last year by  
the association's Baseball Rules Committee, including the reduction 
in maximum diameter from 2 3/4 inches to 2 5/8 inches and in the 
difference between the length of a bat and its weight from five 
units to three units. That is, a 34-inch bat could weigh no less 
than 31 ounces, not including the grip. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 15:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Love, Leonard at Buick Challenge  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PINE MOUNTAIN, N.C. (AP) -- With the cheers of a Ryder Cup  
victory still ringing in his ears, Davis Love III arrived Wednesday 
for the Buick Challenge and figured it was time to get down to 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Already, his two children are starting to ask questions about  
that annual trip to Hawaii for the winners-only Mercedes 
Championship at the start of the season. Right now, all Love can do 
is shrug his shoulders. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't won yet,'' he said. ``I'm not in Kapalua, and my  
kids are starting to put pressure on me. I want to get back to my 
goals for the year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After an incredible comeback in the Ryder Cup, which Love  
described as 12 players with a single purpose, the rest of the year 
is for individual goals. Love already has won more than $1.7 
million, the most he has ever earned in 14 seasons on the PGA Tour. 
</P>
<P>
	He just hasn't won.  
</P>
<P>
	This wouldn't be a bad place for him to start. Love has 10  
consecutive rounds under par on the Mountain View course at 
Callaway Gardens, and he returned from the Ryder Cup in Spain two 
years ago and won the Buick Challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	Better yet is his back.  
</P>
<P>
	Love missed three weeks with a pinched nerve in his neck that  
caused his fingers to go numb and didn't play 18 holes until a week 
ago Tuesday at The Country Club. But his play in the Ryder Cup 
didn't suffer -- Love was unbeaten (1-0-3), a nice turnaround from 
his 0-4 performance two years earlier at Valderrama. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a lot of confidence in my game,'' he said. ``I felt  
like my putting would turn around and it did. I want to play well 
after last week, so my expectations are high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other three Ryder Cup players in the field for the Buick  
Challenge are Jeff Maggert, Steve Pate and Justin Leonard, who 
still hasn't fully grasped how he made that 45-foot birdie putt on 
the 17th hole that ultimately returned the Ryder Cup to American 
soil. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an emotional week,'' Leonard said.  
</P>
<P>
	Also in the field is John Daly, playing for the first time since  
Callaway Golf dumped him because Daly ended 26 months of sobriety 
and refused to go back to rehab. 
</P>
<P>
	The defending champion is Steve Elkington, who has as much to  
gain as anyone over the next four weeks. While the sweet-swinging 
Australian won earlier this year at Doral, he has slipped to No. 31 
on the money list and needs to pick it up if he wants to make the 
season-ending Tour Championship, which offers a $5 million purse. 
</P>
<P>
	Elkington, like Love, has a strong affinity for the Mountain  
View course. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not that easy to get here, but once you do, it's well  
worth it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Buick Challenge has been feast or famine for Elkington. He  
won last year, beating Fred Funk on the first hole of a playoff, 
and he also won by five strokes in 1994 when the event was cut to 
54 holes because of rain. 
</P>
<P>
	But he missed the cut in four of the other five times he has  
played the Buick. This wouldn't be a good year for that to happen. 
The Tour Championship is being played at Champions Golf Club in 
Houston, which is Elkington's home course. 
</P>
<P>
	``I played terrible three years ago and finished 10th,'' he  
said. ``It's a big advantage if I get into the field.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
