<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ugly Oranges Said Taste Good / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARLINGEN, Texas (AP) -- Mysterious markings have shown up on  
some Rio Grande Valley oranges, making them less attractive. But 
those in the citrus industry say fruit with damaged peels tastes 
just as good. 
</P>
<P>
	``Someone remarked that it's such a pity that we are judged by  
the part of the fruit that they always throw away,'' said Rio Hondo 
gift basket shipper Violet Lang, who has not been affected by the 
recent batch of flawed fruit. 
</P>
<P>
	The harvest of early oranges in the Rio Grande Valley is under  
way and some of the N-33 Navel, Marrs and Everhard oranges have 
turned up with strange blemishes. The permanent spots, which cover 
up to 30 oil glands on the orange peel, are about half a centimeter 
large and are yellow to orange in color. The fruit is picked green, 
but the spots remain lighter as the oranges ripen. 
</P>
<P>
	Citrus Center entomologist Victor French estimates that less  
than 1 percent of Valley orchards have been affected. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not all orchards have it, by any means,'' French said. ``It's  
not prevalent at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although some of the markings have been blamed on herbicide  
damage, scientists at the Texas A&AMP;M-Kingsville Citrus Center in 
Weslaco are continuing to conduct tests on other possible causes. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the suspects are weather and pests.  
</P>
<P>
	The dry spells in the Valley that have been broken by heavy  
downpours could be responsible. 
</P>
<P>
	Another potential culprit is the leaf-footed bug, which gets  
into fruit and causes raised mounds of gum just under the surface. 
French is exposing clean fruit to leaf-footed bugs to see if he can 
duplicate the damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Green stink bugs or a creature known as the false spider mite  
also might be responsible. French said false spider mites have 
usually affected Valley grapefruit in the past, and that the pests 
currently are damaging oranges in Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	The fact that the cause is a mystery is not unusual.  
</P>
<P>
	``Some years there are pests we don't see and then the following  
year they're very prevalent,'' he said, adding that he expected the 
Valley's citrus crop this year to be a good one overall. 
</P>
<P>
	In any case, the mystery spots have not affected the taste,  
French said. Still, growers selling the fruit on the fresh fruit 
market need oranges that appeal to the eye as well as taste buds. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Lang, who had not seen or heard of the recent batch of  
damaged citrus, said the fruit she and her husband ship in 2,000 
gift baskets a year must be attractive. Damaged ``number two'' 
fruit is sold for lower prices to roadside peddlers or others. 
</P>
<P>
	Donald Thompson, president of Thompson Grove Care in Weslaco,  
owns about 100 acres of citrus and looks after an additional 700 or 
800 acres for other growers. He said clean, undamaged fruit can go 
for $120 to $150 a ton in the fresh fruit market while peel-damaged 
fruit might bring only $50 a ton at a juice plant. 
</P>
<P>
	``The eye appeal is what everybody buys by, which is really  
sad,'' Thompson said. ``We cull out a lot fruit that is just as 
good to eat as the other.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 13:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> La-Z-Boy buying furniture Maker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Not sitting idle as one of the world's largest  
furniture makers, La-Z-Boy Inc. is buying Ladd Furniture Inc. in a 
$197.8 million stock deal that one analyst says ``sets up La-Z-Boy 
as an industry behemoth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal unveiled Tuesday, La-Z-Boy also will assume  
Ladd's debt of $101.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Ladd, based in Greensboro, N.C.,is among North America's largest  
residential furniture makers and one of the world's leading 
suppliers to hotel and motel, assisted living and government 
markets. It markets a broad range of bedroom, dining room, and 
upholstered furniture under several brand names including American 
Drew, Barclay and Clayton Marcus. 
</P>
<P>
	La-Z-Boy is the largest U.S. maker of upholstered furniture and  
a leading manufacturer worldwide of recliners.The company, based in 
Monroe, Mich.,had sales of $1.29 billion in the fiscal 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Ladd, based in Greensboro, N.C.,had 1998 sales of $571.1  
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal ``sets up La-Z-Boy as an industry behemoth'' and should  
help the company ``leverage capacity, brands and styles to be of 
greater service to retailers, and ultimately to consumers, said 
analyst Saul Cutler of BDO Seidman 
</P>
<P>
	The deal calls for the exchange of each Ladd share for 1.18  
shares of La-Z-Boy and represents a price of $24.34 per Ladd share, 
based on La-Z-Boy's closing stock price yesterday of $20.63. 
</P>
<P>
	La-Z-Boy said it expects to take a still-undetermined  
transaction-related charge in the quarter in which the deal is 
completed. 
</P>
<P>
	The transaction -- requiring approval by regulators and Ladd  
shareholders -- should be completed by early 2000. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
