<DOCNO> APW19990929.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 08:18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Bill Would Curb Bounty Hunters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chinelle Moore says she quickly opened her  
front door when five armed men knocked on it before sunrise one 
morning because they claimed to be police officers. 
</P>
<P>
	Once they got inside, they didn't act like officers.  
</P>
<P>
	Moore, a single mother in Laurel, Md., said they turned out to  
be bounty hunters -- non-government individuals who hunt down bail 
jumpers for pay, but need not heed the same laws police must 
follow. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore told a news conference Tuesday that she told them she knew  
nothing about the man they were seeking that morning in July 1998, 
but they beat her, breaking her nose, covered her with pepper spray 
and pulled a gun on her 5-year-old daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bounty hunters held us in the house against our will,''  
she said. ``They made us sit on the bed and answer questions while 
they ransacked our house and went through our drawers, our phone 
books and kept us from answering the phone,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore asked Congress to pass a bill introduced Tuesday by Rep.  
Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., that would put new restrictions on bounty 
hunters and the bail bondsmen who hire them. 
</P>
<P>
	Most bounty hunters, who are enlisted to track down people who  
have failed to show up for trial or other court appearances as 
promised, are trained and responsible professionals, Hutchinson 
said. But some are rogues ``who've seen one too many `Dirty Harry' 
movies,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The tragic results are obvious in the countless cases of  
innocent citizens who are shot, beaten and terrorized,'' Hutchinson 
told reporters. ``Unbelievably, these innocent victims have little 
recourse after suffering such abuse'' since outdated laws enacted 
during the ``Wild West'' period give bounty hunters more power and 
authority than police officers, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hutchinson said the bill would:  
</P>
<P>
	--Make bounty hunters and the bail bondsmen who hire them liable  
for civil rights violations. 
</P>
<P>
	--Require bounty hunters who cross state lines to report their  
intentions to local law enforcement authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	--Require the attorney general to develop model guidelines that  
state legislatures can consider enacting to regulate bounty 
hunting. 
</P>
<P>
	``When people are harmed by bounty hunters, the victims ... have  
little recourse at all,'' said Rep. Alcee Hastings, D-Fla., who 
supports the bill. ``It is frightening to me that individuals can 
be given the power that exceeds the power of law enforcement 
personnel.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
