<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Beatty to Give Long-Awaited Speech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- Warren Beatty, toying with a  
presidential run, got a chance Wednesday to outline his views of 
Democratic Party issues before an international audience. 
</P>
<P>
	Beatty has said little since disclosing seven weeks ago that he  
is flirting with the idea. He wrote an opinion column lamenting the 
state of the major political parties last month, and granted a 
couple of interviews to newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	His silence has only heightened interest in the speech Wednesday  
night to the Southern California Americans for Democratic Action, 
which was presenting him with an award. 
</P>
<P>
	Journalists with news outlets based in Germany, Japan, France,  
Spain, Italy, Great Britain and Canada, as well as national 
reporters based in New York and Washington, D.C., flocked to the 
Beverly Hilton, as did a battery of liberal politicians and 
Hollywood stars. 
</P>
<P>
	``First of all Warren Beatty is a movie star, as big as exists  
on the planet, and there is a celebrity frenzy all over the world 
now,'' said Lila Garrett, president of ADA, which views itself as 
guardian of the Democratic Party's ``progressive'' wing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The progressive wing of the Democratic Party has been shut  
out, and the air in that shut room of conservative Democrats become 
stale,'' Garrett said. ``Warren Beatty has opened that door 
slightly and the rancid air is moving out and the fresh air is 
moving in,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Beatty played a brutally honest politician in the film  
``Bulworth,'' which was Beatty's call for campaign finance reform. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
