<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Banker Denies Money Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's top central banker denied allegations  
that Russians laundered billions of dollars through a U.S.-based 
bank, but acknowledged huge amounts of money flee Russia illegally 
every month, a newspaper reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Viktor Gerashchenko, chairman of Russia's Central Bank, called  
media reports of money laundering through the Bank of New York 
``far-fetched,'' in an interview in the weekly Arguments and Facts. 
</P>
<P>
	Media reports have said Russian businesses and organized crime  
may have illegally laundered billions of dollars through the bank, 
the 15th largest in the United States. The reports have said the 
scandal could be one of the largest cases of money-laundering ever 
uncovered in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Gerashchenko played down those reports, he said bank  
specialists in Russia estimate about $1 billion leaves Russia every 
month illegally. 
</P>
<P>
	The chairman of Russia's Vnesheconombank, the state bank in  
charge of foreign debt, said the capital going abroad was not 
necessarily criminal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot categorically state that the major part of the  
Russian capital (that has left the country) is of criminal 
nature,'' Andrei Kostin said during a visit to Washington for the 
annual meeting of the International Monetary Fund and the World 
Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	``The major part of the capital which flies from Russia is not  
worse than the capital in any Western country which tries to find 
the best place where it can be invested,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerashchenko also denied rumors that he was planning to resign  
as bank chairman despite allegations that the Central Bank may have 
improperly used loan money from the International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he said he was planning to step down before his four-year  
term expires. He was appointed Central Bank chief last fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a family, a parrot and a cat, whom I see on rare  
occasions. It is necessary to yield to the young in good time after 
all,'' he said in the Arguments and Facts interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Financial Times newspaper in London reported  
today that a Bank of New York executive fired in connection with 
the money-laundering investigation has filed a compensation claim 
for unfair dismissal. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for Lucy Edwards, a central figure in the  
money-laundering probe, filed the claim with a London industrial 
tribunal, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	A London-based vice president for the bank, Edwards was  
dismissed for gross misconduct, violation of the bank's internal 
policies, falsification of bank records and failure to cooperate 
with the bank's investigation. She has denied any wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. investigators are trying to determine whether Russian  
criminal groups laundered up to $10 billion through the bank. No 
charges have been filed in connection with their investigation. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 08:20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Builder Revives Tower Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- A Japanese developer said Wednesday that  
with Asian economic troubles easing, it will resume construction of 
the world's tallest skyscraper next year in Shanghai. 
</P>
<P>
	The 90-story, 1,518-foot-tall Shanghai Financial Center is being  
redesigned to make it even taller, said Mori Building Co. president 
Minoru Mori. He wouldn't say what the new height target is. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't announce it yet, because some people might want to  
surpass it again,'' he said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Skyscraper rivalry shifted to Asia when the 1,480-foot-tall  
Petronas Towers were finished in 1996 in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, 
and became the world's tallest. The main building displaced the 
Sears Tower of Chicago, which had held the title since 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	Developers announced plans for taller buildings in Shanghai and  
Taipei, Taiwan. The Taipei competitors were later forced to scale 
down their 110-story project to a mere 90 stories to keep it from 
becoming a nuisance to airliners. 
</P>
<P>
	In the United States, a developer announced plans to win back  
Chicago's record-holding status with a 119-story, 1,537-foot-tall 
skyscraper. 
</P>
<P>
	Work on the Shanghai World Financial Center started in the  
mid-1990s in Pudong, a newly developed business district being 
promoted as China's financial capital. Mori Building suspended 
construction in 1997, leaving a foundation pit with support pilings 
jutting out of the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Mori blamed the Asian financial crisis, which bankrupted several  
Japanese banks backing the project and made others more reluctant 
to get involved. 
</P>
<P>
	The planned 94-story Financial Center is to rise from a square  
base to a narrow wedge at its tip, with space for offices, a hotel, 
stores and restaurants. A huge circular hole punched through its 
top floors is to contain an open-air observation deck. 
</P>
<P>
	The cost and financing arrangements will change, Mori said. Mori  
Building had planned to pay 30 percent of the $235 million cost. 
</P>
<P>
	``We might have to increase our share, because some of the banks  
have failed,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Financial Center would enter a depressed Shanghai real  
estate market glutted with vacant space. Vacancy rates for offices 
in some areas are as high as 70 per cent, forcing landlords to 
slash rents. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mori was optimistic about luring tenants, pointing to the  
success of a 46-story tower opened by his company in Pudong last 
year. He said it has rented 90 percent of its space to foreign 
banks and other premium customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``This already demonstrated to everyone that you can achieve  
high occupancy if you maintain certain global standards,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 03:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gene Therapy Experiment Halted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- A gene therapy experiment has been halted  
following the death of an 18-year-old Arizona man who volunteered 
to join the study to help others suffering from his rare metabolic 
disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Jesse Gelsinger died Sept. 16, several days after researchers  
began infusing his liver with genetically engineered viruses 
designed to counter ornithine transcarbamylase deficiency, a 
disease that impairs the body's ability to rid itself of ammonia. 
</P>
<P>
	The disorder often leads to coma and death in infancy.  
Gelsinger, who was first diagnosed with OTC at age 2, had coped 
with the disease through a regimen of medications and low-protein 
foods. Ammonia is produced in the breakdown of protein. 
</P>
<P>
	``This kid was as happy as can be,'' Jesse's father, Paul  
Gelsinger, told The Arizona Daily Star. ``He was saying, `Dad, they 
might be able to come up with a cure.' He wanted to do it and I 
encouraged him. I was really proud of this kid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The experiment involving 18 patients has been halted until  
researchers can determine why Jesse died, The Washington Post 
reported today. The newspaper referred to the death as the first 
linked by doctors to the field of research that seeks to cure 
people by giving them new genes. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal officials were expected to send letters today to more  
than 100 scientists across the country conducting human research 
with similar viruses, asking them to report any evidence of 
trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	In the study at the University of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia,  
DNA without the genetic mutation that causes OTC was inserted into 
a virus. The virus was then sent directly to the organ where the 
mutated gene was active -- the liver. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first 24 hours looked pretty similar to other patients,''  
said Dr. Mark Batshaw, one of the pioneers of OTC research. ``After 
24 hours, though, he just went rapidly downhill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jesse became comatose, his face swelled, his body was jaundiced  
and his oxygen intake dipped to dangerously low levels. Soon his 
entire body was swelling, inside and out. 
</P>
<P>
	``The doctor said our son was brain dead,'' Paul Gelsinger said.  
``He was symptomatic maybe three times in his life and now we had a 
vegetable. He didn't have a mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jesse was taken off life support one week after he flew to  
Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know why this happened,'' Batshaw said. ``We view him  
as a hero. He was one of those rare people who tried to help 
others. In the history of research, these things happen.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 14:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge: Pitcher's Rights Violated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- A judge said police violated a former  
baseball pitcher's rights, but did not dismiss the charges against 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	John Eric Rosengren, a former Arizona Diamondback minor league  
pitcher, sought to call his father, an attorney, when he was 
involved in a fatal car crash. 
</P>
<P>
	A police officer refused to allow him to do so, Judge Richard S.  
Fields of Pima County Superior Court was told. 
</P>
<P>
	Fields said Tuesday he needed additional time to review the case  
and probably won't rule on a defense dismissal motion until next 
week. Meanwhile, he delayed the trial until Nov. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	The 27-year-old Rosengren is charged with manslaughter in a  
one-vehicle rollover accident Feb. 28 that killed his passenger and 
Diamondbacks teammate, 29-year-old Kenneth Neal Robinson Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	The players were in Tucson for spring training.  
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for Rosengren argue that because their client wasn't  
allowed to consult his father for legal advice, he was denied a 
crucial opportunity to develop evidence in his favor. 
</P>
<P>
	Failing a dismissal, lawyers Michael Piccarreta and Michael  
Bloom want Fields to suppress a blood sample taken from Rosengren 
the night of the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Police had the sample taken after obtaining a search warrant  
through a city magistrate. 
</P>
<P>
	Toxicology tests based on a blood sample drawn at St. Mary's  
Hospital showed Rosengren's blood-alcohol level the morning of the 
crash was 0.16 percent, more than 1 1/2 times the level for 
presumptive drunken driving. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
