<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Bank May Alter Money Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's central bank, under intense pressure at  
home and abroad, is tempting currency markets with hints that it 
may alter its money supply policy to cap the rise of the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	An about-face by the bank has been urged by Japanese finance  
officials and politicians. Worried the yen's sharp rise this summer 
could snuff out the nation's fledgling economic recovery, the 
government has been clamoring for efforts to rein it in. 
</P>
<P>
	The government wants the yen weakened against the U.S. dollar to  
help the nation's big exporters. A stronger yen hurts these 
companies by making their goods more expensive overseas. 
Export-oriented Sony Corp., for instance, saw profits plunge 55 
percent due to the rising yen in the three months ending June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Big business would not be the only beneficiary of an easing of  
monetary policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Weakening the yen, and flirting with inflation, could be a key  
to getting Japan's close-fisted consumers to finally spend money 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's economy, stagnant for most of the decade, has seen  
prices and consumer spending plummet during the past several years, 
a process known as deflation that could be disastrous for any 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Theoretically, the threat of its opposite -- inflation, or rising  
prices -- could persuade consumers to start buying again. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan has been reluctant to weaken the yen, in part  
because of fear that inflation could get out of control and 
politically destabilize the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the BOJ does trigger inflation, then savings get  
destroyed,'' said Andrew Shipley, an economist at Schroder 
Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the Bank of Japan has been adamant about asserting  
its independence since being freed from the aegis of the Ministry 
of Finance last year. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last few months, the dollar has tumbled from more than  
124 yen in May to just above 103 yen earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank enraged government leaders last week by  
announcing that it would not use monetary policy to weaken the 
currency, citing the fact that short-term interest rates already 
are close to zero. 
</P>
<P>
	But last weekend BOJ governor Masaru Hayami hinted vaguely in  
Washington that the bank might switch gears and print money to 
weaken the yen. He stirred up more confusion by later denying this 
was a change in the bank's policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Several times this summer, the Bank of Japan has intervened in  
currency markets in an effort to pull back the yen. Those actions 
involved selling yen and buying dollars on the open market, but 
they did not seem to have an enduring effect. 
</P>
<P>
	Many private economists say the inflation that would result from  
a weaker yen would be good for Japan, but the positive effects 
would not be immediate because of the country's current high 
unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unlikely for demand to immediately recover, even if  
prices start to rise,'' Shipley said in an interview. ``There's no 
easy way out for Japan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hayami's comments in Washington have already begun to push the  
yen down against the dollar this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders seem to expect the BOJ will inject money into the  
banking system, a maneuver that could lead to lower interest rates 
and a decline of the yen's value against other currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Shipley said the BOJ should buy bonds to weaken the yen rather  
than pump funds into the banking system, since the nation's 
beleaguered, debt-ridden banks are still reluctant to lend money. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, some economists say a significant change in the  
yen-dollar rate may not be enough to send the lagging Japanese 
economy toward full recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	Referring to U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers' oft-cited  
advice, Kazuki Fujita of the Industrial Bank of Japan said, 
``Domestic demand-led growth, as Summers always says, is 
necessary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Fujita, a senior foreign exchange trader, said the Japanese  
government needs to spend more money on economic stimulus to 
increase demand to keep the nation from toppling back into 
recession. ``Japan needs budgetary help,'' he said. 




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
