<HEADLINE> Chicago OKs Tallest Building Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The City of Big Shoulders has taken a big step  
toward being home to the world's tallest building -- again. 
</P>
<P>
	The city council on Wednesday unanimously approved a developer's  
plans for a 108-story, 1,550-foot-tall skyscraper. 
</P>
<P>
	Alderman Burton Natarus said the slender, still-unnamed  
mega-building would be a ``bonanza'' for the city in tax income. 
</P>
<P>
	The $500-million structure would include offices, condominiums,  
retail stores and parking spaces. It would be built at the site of 
a 17-story building located about six blocks from the 1,450-foot 
Sears Tower, knocked from its spot as world's tallest building in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The Petronas Towers in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, reign as the  
tallest buildings in the world at 1,483 feet. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
