<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steelers Urged on Throwing Deep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Kordell Stewart isn't scrambling or throwing  
deep, allowing opposing defenses to stack the line of scrimmage 
against running back Jerome Bettis. 
</P>
<P>
	There's a new offensive coordinator in Pittsburgh, but it sure  
sounds like old times. 
</P>
<P>
	One of offensive coordinator Kevin Gilbride's main goals after  
being brought in to overhaul the underachieving offense of a season 
ago was to reinstate the deep pass and get Stewart scrambling 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	Unable to loosen defenses by throwing deep last season, and with  
Stewart seemingly chained to the pocket, the Steelers' offense 
became increasingly easy to read -- and, as the 7-9 season 
progressed, easy to stop. 
</P>
<P>
	After showing measurable improvement this season with victories  
over AFC Central doormats Baltimore and Cleveland, the Steelers 
bogged down again Sunday in a morass of mistakes, poor execution 
and easy-to-diagnose play-calling in a 29-10 loss to Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	``They never really stretched the field, and that enabled us to  
stay close and keep them from running,'' said Jay Bellamy, who made 
one of five interceptions thrown by Stewart and Mike Tomczak. ``We 
knew if they threw anything, it would be short.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle linebacker Chad Brown, formerly of the Steelers,  
suggested Pittsburgh's offense limits Stewart's ability to rally 
them from a big deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Steelers' offense is based on running the football. They  
don't ask the quarterback to win the game for them. When they get 
behind like that, it's not part of the quarterback's makeup,'' 
Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sound familiar?  
</P>
<P>
	The Steelers' offense was so inefficient -- it didn't score until  
Seattle had opened a 26-0 lead -- that coach Bill Cowher took the 
unusual step, for him, of singling out players for post-game 
criticism. 
</P>
<P>
	At the top of his list: Stewart, whom Cowher said should have  
been more eager to duck the blitz by scrambling out of trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart's longest completion was for 23 yards; the week before  
against Baltimore, it was 22 yards. His longest this season was a 
42-yarder to Hines Ward in the opener in Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Cowher denies that the Steelers have erased the deep pass from  
Stewart's playbook because they fear interceptions or that their 
receivers won't get open. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Stewart averaged 12.8 yards per completion in 1997, the  
Steelers have lost their top two receivers from that season, Yancey 
Thigpen and Charles Johnson. They drafted Troy Edwards from 
Louisiana Tech to add a big-play threat, but he can't beat out 
Courtney Hawkins and plays only when extra receivers are employed. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart averages 9.3 yards per completion this season.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know we went downfield on two occasions against Baltimore,  
we hit Hines Ward with one and Courtney Hawkins with one,'' Cowher 
said. ``I guess last week we took a couple of chances. The 
circumstances in that game were that it got so they were not going 
to give up the long ball. If they take that away, we have to be 
able to run the football. If they're going to put a couple of 
safeties back there, we have to make the running game go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They couldn't do that, either, as Jerome Bettis was limited to  
39 yards, with 20 coming on his final carry. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Steelers (2-1) realize they probably can't rely on  
short, simple pass routes and their running game if they are to 
beat defending division champion Jacksonville (2-1) on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just want to score points and win football games,'' Cowher  
said. ``I don't think it's a question of trying to establish 
something. If we feel like the deep ball was there and people are 
sitting on certain routes, we need to make sure we stretch the 
field. That's always going to be the objective we have.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
