<DOCNO> APW19990929.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 08:03:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawsuit Vs. Notre Dame To Proceed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Notre Dame should take reasonable steps to  
prevent fans from being injured during scrambles for footballs that 
land in the stands during games, the Indiana Court of Appeals says. 
</P>
<P>
	The court ruled Tuesday that Letitia Hayden, who was injured by  
someone lunging for a ball during a 1995 game, can proceed with her 
lawsuit seeking unspecified damages against the university. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision reversed a ruling by St. Joseph Circuit Court Judge  
Terry Crone that dismissed the lawsuit on grounds that Notre Dame 
did not owe a duty to protect Hayden from the criminal acts of a 
third party. 
</P>
<P>
	``Notre Dame well understands and benefits from the enthusiasm  
of the fans of its football games,'' the unanimous appeals court 
ruling said. ``It is just such enthusiasm that drives some 
spectators to attempt to retrieve a football to keep as a 
souvenir.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hayden and her husband, William, were sitting behind the goal  
post in the south end zone at a game Sept. 16, 1995, when one of 
the teams kicked a football toward the goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Several people lunged for the ball and one of them struck Mrs.  
Hayden from behind, fracturing her left shoulder and collarbone. 
She sued the university for failing to exercise care to protect 
her. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she and her husband had attended Notre Dame games for  
years and saw footballs land in the seats around them many times. 
</P>
<P>
	Her husband testified that the net behind the goal post caught  
kicked footballs only about half the time. He also said student 
managers who worked for the university used to aggressively attempt 
to recover footballs, but no longer did that. 
</P>
<P>
	Notre Dame contended that the action of the person who injured  
Mrs. Hayden was unforeseeable and it therefore owed no duty to 
anticipate it and protect her. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court said there was evidence of many prior  
incidents in which people were jostled or injured by fans trying to 
retrieve balls. 
</P>
<P>
	John Ulmer, an attorney for Mrs. Hayden, said she was  
permanently impaired because of the incident. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a manager at Michigan State in the late '50s for the  
football team, and that is why we went into the stands -- to keep 
control and get the football without anyone getting hurt. Notre 
Dame used to do that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	William Hoye, an attorney for Notre Dame, was out of the office  
and unavailable for comment. Jill Bodensteiner, another Notre Dame 
attorney listed in the appeal's court ruling, did not immediately 
return a phone call seeking comment Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 15:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Republicans Unveil TV Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- More than a year before Election Day, House  
Republicans unveiled their first television commercials of the 
campaign on Wednesday, accusing Democrats of planning to raid the 
Social Security surplus for ``big government programs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va., chairman of the House GOP campaign  
committee, said the commercials would initially run in the 
districts of ``upwards of a dozen'' Democratic lawmakers viewed as 
vulnerable to an electoral challenge next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The only one he would name was Rep. Jim Maloney of Connecticut,  
who swiftly accused the GOP of leveling charges that ``are 
blatantly untrue. In fact they know they're untrue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now the Democrats and the president have a budget plan  
to raid Social Security for more spending on wasteful big 
government programs,'' says the announcer in one of three 
variations of the same advertisement. Each includes the message: 
``Stop the raid on Social Security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri rebutted that  
the Republicans were out ``to try to convince the American people 
that they're not doing something that they're doing. ... It is the 
most cynical thing I've ever seen in my time in politics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a telephone interview, Maloney noted he had voted for a  
Republican-crafted ``lockbox'' bill to safeguard Social Security 
funds. He added that he had voted against the GOP tax cut measure 
``precisely because it used money that should have gone to protect 
Social Security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP commercials come as Republicans are girding for a  
year-end budget battle with the White House and Democrats. After 
conceding they would not keep two earlier pledges -- meet an Oct. 1 
deadline for passing all spending bills and hold spending under 
caps in the 1997 balanced budget agreement -- Republicans now say 
they will refuse to dip into the Social Security surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	The commercials are to underscore that policy.  
</P>
<P>
	Davis said Republicans were seeking donations from lawmakers and  
interest groups to pay for the commercials. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats had hopes for picking up a House seat in the Maryland  
suburbs around Washington as the year dawned. There was speculation 
that the incumbent, moderate seven-term Republican Rep. Connie 
Morella, would give up her seat to run for the Senate. In the 
meantime, Democrats sought to entice Mark Shriver, a state 
legislator and member of the Kennedy family, into the race for her 
seat. 
</P>
<P>
	But Morella decided to stay put, and Shriver declined to run.  
Now party officials say the only announced Democratic candidate, 
Ralph Neas, has dropped out, citing family reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Morella gained 60 percent of the vote in defeating Neas last  
year, and Democrats are now searching for a candidate in a district 
where President Clinton has twice won comfortably. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton journeyed to the Senate this  
week to tout Democratic legislation to raise the minimum wage. 
</P>
<P>
	She spoke only briefly and made no reference to her unannounced  
campaign for the Senate from New York. Nor did the script call for 
her to respond to questions. 
</P>
<P>
	But one reporter shouted out: ``How do you like the offices  
here?'' 
</P>
<P>
	At that, the first lady stopped, smiled, and then headed  
wordlessly for the exit. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
