<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 20:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Heavy rain stretched across the East and parts of the Gulf Coast  
on Wednesday, with severe thunderstorms in the Ohio Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain and scattered storms extended along a cold front from the  
Great Lakes to Alabama and Mississippi, and spread eastward during 
the afternoon through the Appalachians and into the East Coast 
states. 
</P>
<P>
	Parts of eastern North Carolina, already flooded since Hurricane  
Floyd two weeks ago, had gotten as much as 8 inches of rain in two 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	And from Mississippi, the thunderstorms and heavy rain continued  
southwestward in a line across the coastal regions of Louisiana and 
Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	A severe thunderstorm watch was posted for eastern Ohio and  
Kentucky and western sections of West Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday night, several homes and businesses were damaged or  
destroyed by tornadoes that swept through central North Carolina. 
One man had his leg broken, officials said, apparently when a tree 
crashed into his home. 
</P>
<P>
	A tornado also struck South Carolina Wednesday night. About 10  
mobile homes were destroyed in the northeast part of the state and 
some residents were taken to a hospital, officials said. None of 
the injuries were serious. 
</P>
<P>
	In Ohio, wind up to 60 mph knocked down power lines and trees in  
the Columbus area. An estimated 10,000 American Electric Power 
customers lost power around noon, but about half of them had 
service again by late afternoon. Heavy rain also may have been a 
factor in an afternoon school bus accident; several children were 
taken to a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	A tornado watch was issued for sections of western New York,  
western Pennsylvania and lakes Erie and Ontario. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, a few light showers were scattered across Montana and  
North Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from  
a morning low of just 15 degrees at Craig, Colo., to midday 
readings of 88 at Palm Springs, Calif., and Mayport, Fla. The 
lowest wind chill was 1 below zero at Leadville, Colo., and the 
highest heat index by the middle of the day was 107 at Biloxi, 
Miss. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 23:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Davis: Broncos Will Find Groove </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Terrell Davis has a simple remedy for what ails  
the Denver Broncos' running game. A firm tug on the rope should 
suffice. 
</P>
<P>
	``Like I told somebody today, it's almost like trying to start a  
lawn mower,'' Davis said Wednesday. ``You're pulling it and pulling 
it and it wants to start, but it's not starting. But I think once 
it starts, we'll start rolling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, who led the NFL with 2,008 yards rushing last season,  
barely is on pace for 1,000 this season. The Broncos, who ranked 
second in the NFL in rushing last season, stand 21st after three 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if Team Toro is any closer to finding solutions for its  
ground woes, Davis said, ``I don't think it's a big problem right 
now, as far as what needs to be fixed. I think it's just little 
things. We're close to breaking long runs. We're close to 
establishing drives. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the main thing we need to do is just hold some  
consistent drives together. A lot of times it takes the running 
game some time to get into sync. It's hard to get a running game in 
sync when you're going three-and-out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opposing defenses deserve some credit for throttling him thus  
far, Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're playing pretty close to the line of scrimmage,'' he  
said. ``If we could break the line of scrimmage, we'd have a chance 
to make a long run. I don't know whether they're stacking or not. I 
don't see that too often. I think it's just that people are playing 
us a little harder right now, making more plays than we're 
making.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, who has 193 yards on 59 carries and only one touchdown,  
remains upbeat. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have all the confidence in the world that this running game  
is going to work and our offense can still move the ball and we can 
put points on the board,'' he said. ``I'm not deterred by what has 
happened these past three games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His sunny disposition could suffer, however, if the Broncos  
(0-3) continue to misfire on Sunday in a home game against the New 
York Jets (0-3). 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets, who lost to Denver 23-10 in the AFC championship game  
last season, rank 20th in the league on offense and 27th on 
defense. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Cornerback Dale Carter missed practice on Wednesday to be  
with his younger sister, who was assaulted during an apparent 
robbery in the Atlanta area. ... Center Jason Watts, signed to 
Denver's developmental squad on Tuesday, worked out with the team 
Wednesday. Watts was released from jail in July after serving 3 1/2 
months for a drunken-driving crash that killed a teammate and 
another man. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
