<DOCNO> APW19990929.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 08:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Six Asian Countries Reduce Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- Six southeast Asian nations agreed today to  
reduce tariffs to a maximum of 5 percent for most agricultural and 
manufacturing products by Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The tariff cut will apply to Thailand, Singapore, Malaysia,  
Indonesia, Brunei and the Philippines -- the six founding members of 
the regional economic grouping called the Association of Southeast 
Asian Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	But Malaysia urged ASEAN officials meeting here to postpone  
reducing tariffs on imported cars. 
</P>
<P>
	Explaining that the Malaysian auto industry was hit hard by the  
economic crisis, Malaysian Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz 
told reporters that cutting tariffs on imported cars should be 
delayed until after Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``What happens after that, we have not decided,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	ASEAN's goal is to make the region a ``zero tariff'' trade area  
by 2015 for the six founding members. The other members -- Laos, 
Vietnam, Myanmar and Cambodia -- are to join by 2018, ASEAN 
officials said in a joint statement. 
</P>
<P>
	today's talks precede the formal ministers' conference on  
general economic issues starting Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Wednesday, ASEAN economic officials agreed to open  
restricted or closed industries to regional investors by January 
2003. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, ASEAN countries have drawn up lists of proposed  
manufacturing products to be included in the deal. Lists for 
agriculture, forestry, fishery and mining industries are to be 
completed by year's end. 
</P>
<P>
	``This important first step makes the whole investment  
environment more transparent,'' Singapore Trade and Industry 
Minister George Yeo told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``This is not to be construed as an exclusionary  
scheme that would exclude non-ASEAN investors. ASEAN remains open 
to foreign investors.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 08:01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Network TV in Season Opening / TV Ratings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The new television season may not be just for  
kids after all. 
</P>
<P>
	After much attention was paid to network efforts to appeal to  
teen-agers and young adults, it was the more serious adult fare of 
dramas that did best during a promising opening week of the TV 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC narrowly won the first week's Nielsens ratings race over  
CBS, primarily because the strong ``Saturday Night Live'' 25th 
anniversary special Sunday blunted the impact of CBS's strongest 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are encouraged by the way people are tuning in to network  
television and we look forward to a good season for all of us,'' 
said Scott Sassa, NBC's West Coast president. 
</P>
<P>
	Two new dramas premiered in the week's top 10: ABC's critically  
acclaimed ``Once and Again,'' about two recently-divorced parents 
fumbling through a romance, and NBC's ``Third Watch,'' about an 
emergency medical team. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC also had strong showings by ``West Wing,'' the White House  
drama with Martin Sheen as president, and the spinoff series, ``Law 
and Order: Special Victims Unit.'' ABC was pleased with the showing 
of its new ``Snoops,'' despite tough competition Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Two legal dramas did well for CBS: ``Family Law,'' about a  
marital attorney who must rebuild her career when her own marriage 
breaks up, and ``Judging Amy,'' which fell off a bit from its 
premiere the previous week but still posted encouraging numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	Lately, audiences have proven more willing to try new dramas  
because they're intrigued by the stories, said Garth Ancier, NBC 
Entertainment president. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've all been sampled well and, by and large, they've been  
good programs,'' Ancier said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Viewers also returned to some old favorites. ABC's Emmy-winning  
``The Practice'' had its largest audience ever last week and NBC's 
``Law and Order'' had its best season-opening audience since its 
premiere in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Comedies haven't done nearly as well. Fox's ``Action,'' perhaps  
the most critically acclaimed new series of the fall, and NBC's 
``Stark Raving Mad'' have been particular disappointments. 
</P>
<P>
	Ancier said comedies take a longer time to build an audience  
because viewers need to become comfortable with the characters. 
Critics generally agreed that it was an unusually weak fall season 
for new comedies. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox has had a tough season so far. Its average audience last  
week was 7.8 million, down from 8.6 million a year before, though 
series like ``Ally McBeal'' and ``The X-Files'' have yet to 
premiere. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week, NBC had a 9.9 rating and 16 share and CBS had a  
9.7 rating and 16 share. ABC had an 8.3 rating and 14 share and Fox 
was at 5.3 and 9. NBC easily won among the 18-to-49-year-old 
demographic advertisers watch closely. 
</P>
<P>
	The WB had a 2.9 rating and 5 share, UPN had a 2.5 rating and 4  
share and Pax TV was at 0.8 and 1. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC's ``World News Tonight'' won the evening news ratings race  
with a 7.3 rating and 16 share. The ``NBC Nightly News'' was second 
with a 7.2 rating and 16 share, and the ``CBS Evening News'' was at 
6.4 and 14. 
</P>
<P>
	A rating point represents 1,008,000 households, or 1 percent of  
the nation's estimated 100.8 million TV homes. The share is the 
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week of Sept. 20-26, the top 10 shows, their networks  
and ratings were ``Friends,'' NBC, 17.8; ``Frasier,'' NBC, 16.6; 
``NFL Monday Night Football: Atlanta at Dallas,'' ABC, 15.2; 
``Third Watch'' special,'' NBC, 14.1; ``Saturday Night Live 25th 
Anniversary Special,'' NBC, 14.0; ``Jesse,'' NBC, 13.9; ``NFL 
Monday Showcase,'' ABC, 12.6; ``Country Music Association Awards,'' 
CBS, 12.3; ``Once and Again,'' ABC, 12.3; ``Stark Raving Mad,'' 
NBC, 12.3. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 14:01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Garcia's Caddie: I Was Attacked  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLOGNE, Germany (AP) -- Boorish conduct by U.S. fans at the  
Ryder Cup didn't stop at the course. 
</P>
<P>
	The American caddie for European Ryder Cup star Sergio Garcia  
said Wednesday he was attacked in a hotel bar after the tournament 
and had to go to a hospital with a head wound. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Higginbotham, sporting a black eye and bruised cheek, said  
several men taunted him because he was an American working with the 
European team. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the guys had obviously had a bad day and had definitely  
had too much to drink,'' said Higginbotham, caddie this week for 
Garcia in the German Masters. 
</P>
<P>
	Police in Boston and Brookline, Mass., on Wednesday said they  
have no record of the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	The confrontation is the latest instance of hostility  
surrounding the tournament, in which the United States made the 
greatest comeback in the history of the event. 
</P>
<P>
	The Europeans were angered by the celebrations of the Americans  
on the 17th green after Justin Leonard made a 45-foot putt that led 
the U.S. team to victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The European team and British media assailed the rowdy  
galleries. European star Colin Montgomerie was heckled mercilessly 
and a fan spit on the wife of European captain Mark James. 
</P>
<P>
	James said European golfers might refuse to play another Ryder  
Cup in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Higginbotham, who caddied for American Mark O'Meara at the 1997  
Ryder Cup in Spain, described the attack in the hotel bar. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said some things I didn't like and I said a couple of  
things back to him because I'll always defend myself,'' he said. 
``And then boom, he comes up on the blind side and down I went, 
hitting my head on the way down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Higginbotham took some of the blame.  
</P>
<P>
	``What I should have done was walk away,'' he said, ``but the  
whole thing leaves a sour taste in the mouth.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 07:50:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Long-Term Capital Mgmt. Repays Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Long-Term Capital Management said Tuesday it  
will repay another $800 million to the group of financial companies 
that kept the fund from going under last year. 
</P>
<P>
	With this installment, Long-Term Capital Management will have  
repaid 75 percent of the $3.63 billion it borrowed to cover 
mounting losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve Bank of New York had to call an emergency  
meeting of industry leaders to prevent the speculative hedge fund's 
woes from spreading to other institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	The bailout included 14 high-profile investment firms, including  
Goldman Sachs Group, Chase Manhattan Corp., Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and 
JP Morgan &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The group formed an oversight committee to monitor the fund's  
recovery efforts. On Tuesday, the committee issued a statement 
saying, ``We are very pleased to have made such progress in the 
course of one year. This would not have been possible without the 
full support of the entire LTCM organization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Today, Long-Term Capital Management has decreased its level of  
risk by 90 percent from its weakest point last year. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 14:23:33 </DATE_TIME>
