<HEADLINE> McCain Invokes Reagan's Spirit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIMI VALLEY, Calif. (AP) -- Presidential hopeful John McCain  
invoked Ronald Reagan's spirit Wednesday, but bent the former 
president's ``Eleventh Commandment'' against speaking ill of fellow 
Republicans with thinly veiled criticisms of his rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Arizona senator never mentioned Texas Gov. George W. Bush or  
conservative candidate Pat Buchanan by name in a speech that 
stressed his own military record -- a background that distinguishes 
him from Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain also defended U.S. intervention in World War II, which  
Buchanan has questioned in a new book. 
</P>
<P>
	``History speaks for itself. The service and sacrifice of  
250,000 Americans speaks for itself as well,'' McCain told 
reporters after his speech at the Ronald Reagan Presidential 
Library and Museum. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain's speech blended his signature issues -- reducing the  
influence of money in politics, beefing up the military and 
restoring pride in public service -- with references to his 
experience as a prisoner of war during the Vietnam War and calls 
for a firmer foreign policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, the GOP front-runner, served in the Texas Air National  
Guard during the Vietnam War, but never served overseas. Bush also 
campaigned Wednesday in southern California. 
</P>
<P>
	In a clear slap at Buchanan's anti-interventionist views and  
Bush's lack of combat experience, McCain said the United States 
must continue to intervene for good around the world but that a 
president needs ``broad and deep experience'' when making such 
life-and-death decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	His speech repeatedly invoked the spirit and words of Reagan -- a  
time-honored campaign tactic for GOP candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Nancy Reagan sat in the front row but did not speak or give  
interviews. The former president, who has Alzheimer's disease, did 
not attend. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain later told reporters that he met with Mrs. Reagan earlier  
in the day but that she did not indicate whether she would endorse 
him over Bush. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
