<HEADLINE> Hula Queen Wins Opening Day Feature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- Hula Queen, bumped at the start, went  
wide in the stretch to win the $112,900 Senator Ken Maddy Handicap 
by 3 1/2 lengths Wednesday on opening day of Santa Anita's Oak Tree 
meet. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridden by Alex Solis, Hula Queen covered 6 1/2 furlongs in 1:13.05  
and paid $31.60, $11 and $5.60. 
</P>
<P>
	Irish-bred Desert Lady returned $4 and $2.80, while Ecudienne  
was another three-quarters of a length back and paid $4.80 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	``She broke a little slow and then I got bumped, and that's why  
I was behind,'' Solis said. ``I wasn't planning on being there, but 
it just happened and I had to just go from there and improvise and 
try to win it any way I could.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first stakes victory in the United States for  
Argentine-born trainer Luis Seglin, who's been training here for 20 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the best moment for me,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The victory was worth $67,740.  
</P>
<P>
	Jockey Patrick Valenzuela resumed his riding career Wednesday  
after two years off due to suspension and personal problems. He had 
no winners in four mounts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
