<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 23:40:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Civil War Sites Under Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANASSAS, Va. (AP) -- Five years after Walt Disney Co. canceled  
plans to build a $650 million theme park near the site of the 
battles of Bull Run, urban sprawl may pose an even greater threat 
to the region's Civil War sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Developers in northern Virginia, driven by the area's booming  
economy, have chewed up land at a frantic pace with new 
condominiums, subdivisions and strip malls. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like being nibbled to death by ducks,'' said Kat Imhoff,  
executive director of the Preservation Alliance of Virginia. ``You 
don't even realize the quantity of resources we're losing because 
it's so piecemeal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, Disney pulled the plug on plans to build an American  
history theme park four miles from Manassas National Battlefield 
Park, where the Confederate and Union armies engaged in the first 
full-scale battle of the Civil War in 1861. 
</P>
<P>
	Fighting Disney was tough, but tracking the seemingly endless  
local development proposals may be even more difficult, said 
Elliott Gruber, executive vice president of the Civil War Trust, 
the country's largest Civil War battlefield preservation group. 
</P>
<P>
	``The threats just continue to expand,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Robert Sutton, superintendent of the Manassas park, spends hours  
at zoning and planning board meetings fighting proposals for hotels 
or strip malls that would ruin the views from the battlefield. A 
strip mall was built last year on the park's southern boundary. 
</P>
<P>
	``As more of the region is built up, there will be even more  
pressure'' to develop around the park, Sutton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Lighthizer of the trust says an acre of Civil War  
battlefield is lost somewhere in the United States every 10 
minutes. With that in mind, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and 
others are urging Congress to dedicate permanent funding to buy 
historic lands and open spaces. 
</P>
<P>
	When Disney announced in 1993 that it wanted to build a  
3,000-acre park in tiny Haymarket, 35 miles southwest of 
Washington, the plan ignited a national debate over urban sprawl 
and historic preservation. 
</P>
<P>
	Eighteen Civil War battlefields, 14 historic towns or villages  
and 60 sites on the National Register of Historic Places were 
within a half-hour drive of the Disney site. While the project had 
the support of many elected officials, citizens soured on it when 
they envisioned the traffic, hotels, gas stations, convenience 
stores and fast-food restaurants that would accompany the park. 
</P>
<P>
	The Disney proposal served as a national referendum on urban  
sprawl, said Richard Moe, president of the National Trust for 
Historic Preservation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Disney was a watershed event,'' he said. ``There was nothing  
historic on that property, but the collateral development that 
would have sprouted in all directions would have overwhelmed the 
fragile battlefields and the beautiful landscape.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Urban sprawl is now considered such a threat to quality of life  
that Vice President Al Gore has made it a theme in his campaign for 
the Democratic presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	The Disney proposal taught preservationists and  
environmentalists that they had to work more closely together. 
Although preserving history is not the mandate of environmental 
groups, by protecting battlefields they are preventing sprawl and 
its associated pollution and loss of open space. 
</P>
<P>
	``Historic preservation groups have become more concerned about  
road projects and local zoning than ever before,'' said Trip 
Pollard of the Southern Environmental Law Center, who also serves 
on the board of the Historic Preservation Alliance of Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	But not everyone agrees that battlefields should be set aside.  
</P>
<P>
	The federal government's purchase of land for historic  
preservation costs jobs and prevents landowners from fully 
profiting from their properties, said Carl Grenn, past president of 
the Civil War Roundtable of Fredericksburg. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who is willing to give up a job because his place of  
employment may be near land once part of the fighting during the 
Civil War?'' Grenn wrote in a letter published in The Free 
Lance-Star of Fredericksburg. 




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 11:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Plans Medicare Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- White House officials are laying the  
groundwork for a meeting with key senators in an attempt to salvage 
major Medicare changes, including new prescription drug coverage 
for senior citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief of staff John Podesta last week extended an invitation to  
Senate Finance Committee Chairman William Roth, R-Del., for all 
members of the committee to meet with President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``Senator Roth has said that he wants to proceed,'' Podesta  
said. ``We're working now together I think to decide how to proceed 
and on what schedule, but I would anticipate that they would meet 
with the president sometime in the near future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This week, Podesta said, he and other administration officials  
are talking with some of the committee's 20 Republican and 
Democratic senators and their staffs individually. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, Roth has been working to develop a Medicare proposal  
with broad enough appeal that his committee -- which has a core of 
moderates from both political parties among its members -- could 
pass it this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Although progress has been slow and the clock is running down,  
Roth spokeswoman Tara Bradshaw said, ``He's just going to take it a 
step at a time and take it as far as he can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The most likely area for progress, however, is not an agreement  
for a new round of sweeping Medicare changes, such as the addition 
of a new prescription drug benefit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, I find it hard to see big changes for Medicare.  
There's a ton of reasons, topped off by lack of time, why it's 
unlikely much is going to happen,'' said John Rother, public policy 
director for the AARP, the nation's largest organization of older 
adults. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, lawmakers are closest to a deal that would undo some of  
the changes they made to Medicare as part of the 1997 balanced 
budget act -- putting back some of the billions of dollars cut from 
payments to health care providers. 
</P>
<P>
	Caregivers from hospitals to nursing homes are complaining that  
their budgets are too tight. And some studies have found evidence 
that Medicare patients with expensive medical problems are having 
trouble getting services such as home health care. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers from both political parties say they would like to  
further bolster Medicare, the nation's health insurance program for 
the elderly and disabled, in anticipation of baby boomer 
retirements. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans and Democrats also agree that senior citizens need  
some help paying for increasingly expensive prescription drugs, 
which Medicare doesn't currently cover. 
</P>
<P>
	However, attempts to reach a deal on the details have taken a  
back seat to a broadly waged political battle over how to spend 
future government surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders want a 10-year tax cut of nearly $800  
billion, about the same amount Clinton wants to pour into Medicare, 
in part for a new prescription drug benefit. 
</P>
<P>
	Possibilities for compromise exist, including less generous tax  
cuts or finding other sources of money for Medicare. Clinton, for 
example, has said he does not rule out the possibility of requiring 
wealthier senior citizens to pay more out-of-pocket overall for 
their Medicare coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 2000 presidential and congressional elections and  
advertising generated by special interest groups are encouraging 
stark political divisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Television and radio ads sponsored by the AFL-CIO this month  
targeted Republican congressional districts, pitting tax cuts ``for 
big business and the rich'' against Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Citizen's for Better Medicare, a coalition that  
includes the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and the Pharmaceutical 
Research and Manufacturers of America, has peppered the nation with 
ads featuring a gray-haired bowler, ``Flo,'' who criticizes 
Clinton's Medicare prescription drug proposal as ``big 
government.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
