<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Concrete Scribblers Taken to Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROANOKE, Va. (AP) -- Writing in wet cement may seem like child's  
play, but it landed three young scribes in court. 
</P>
<P>
	An 11-year-old girl and two boys, ages 12 and 13, were charged  
Tuesday with unlawful destruction of city property. The punishment 
so far has been just a stern lecture. 
</P>
<P>
	Roanoke Juvenile and Domestic Relations Court Judge Joseph P.  
Bounds said he'll take all three cases under advisement for a year 
and then decide if punishment is necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	The three had carved their first names into nine newly-laid  
cement sidewalk panels last June. 
</P>
<P>
	The children's parents called the issue innocent child's play.  
</P>
<P>
	``They're making her out to be a bank robber or something,''  
said Joseph Russell, the stepfather of the 11-year-old girl. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dan Bowman, who discovered the damaged cement near his house  
and called police, disagreed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's destruction of public property. It's an eyesore  
for one thing,'' said Bowman, 61. ``The city decided to replace 
that sidewalk and paid for it with my tax dollars, your tax dollars 
and the parents of those kids' tax dollars. I don't appreciate it 
being defaced.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bounds said the city should decide if the children should pay an  
estimated $3,000 in restitution for replacing the 30-foot section 
of sidewalk. 
</P>
<P>
	The fact that the scribble squabble made it all the way to court  
outraged some Roanoke residents. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's just silly,'' said Lawrence Berndt, 23, a waiter.  
``This thing should have been settled at home with the parents.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
