<HEADLINE> Disneyland Paris Plans Second Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Euro Disney plans to build a second theme park next  
to its Disneyland Paris park site to give visitors a backstage look 
at the movies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Les studios Disney'' (The Disney Studios) is set to open in  
the spring of 2002 at the Magic Kingdom theme park and will cost 
about $650 million, the comoany announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	At the new theme park, actors will come out from behind the  
screen to meet the audience. Themes will comes from French, 
European and Hollywood cinema, cartoons and television, the company 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Euro Disney said it expects an estimated 4.2 million visitors  
annually once the park is fully operational in 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	The company had said in January that it had started discussions  
with French authorities about a 1987 agreement, which had mentioned 
building a second theme park at its site east of Paris before 2011. 
</P>
<P>
	Euro Disney, 39 percent owned by the Walt Disney Co., opened in  
April 1992 to widespread concern that American-style family 
entertainment would not catch on in the Old World. 
</P>
<P>
	Some financial analysts worried that Europeans would balk at the  
prices. Others worried that Paris's cool weather and frequent 
showers would be incompatible with a theme park that made its 
fortune under the sunny skies of California and Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	But Disneyland Paris, which posted losses during its first two  
years, proved itself in 1995 by posting profits a full year ahead 
of schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	The park's directors saved Disneyland Paris with a complex  
restructuring of debts, cuts in ticket prices, attractive 
hotel-park packages and tight cost controls. 
</P>
<P>
	Attendance seemed to level off in 1998, falling to 12.51 million  
visitors from 12.57 million the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	But despite the slight drop in attendance, profits were up 34  
percent from the previous year. Net income in 1998 was 290 million 
francs, or $48 million, up from 217 million francs in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	And the park's hotels, half empty during the park's first year,  
had more than 80 percent occupancy during 1998. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 03:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Higher, Tokyo Stocks Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar edged higher against the yen  
Wednesday, as Tokyo share prices dipped on profit-taking in 
relatively quiet trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. dollar bought 106.90 yen on the Tokyo foreign exchange  
market late Wednesday, up 0.38 yen from late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 43.42 points,  
or 0.25 percent, to close at 17,282.28. On Tuesday, the average 
closed up 504.64 points, or 3.00 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The greenback traded in a narrow range between 106.11 yen and  
107.24 yen as investors remained cautious over possible central 
bank action to stop the dollar's slide. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan disappointed markets last week by refusing to  
yield to pressure from the Japanese government and inject money 
into the banking system as a way of easing interest rates and 
weakening the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	But hopes for action to press the yen down were renewed after a  
weekend meeting in Washington, where financial officials from the 
Group of Seven nations said they shared Japan's concern over the 
yen's rapid rise. 
</P>
<P>
	Zembei Mizoguchi, chief of the international bureau at Japan's  
Finance Ministry, reiterated Wednesday that the ministry will 
continue to carefully watch market moves. But he said it was too 
early to say whether the yen's recent strengthening has stopped. 
</P>
<P>
	An excessively high yen could negatively affect Japanese  
exporters by reducing profits they earn from overseas sales. That 
in turn could threaten a fledgling economic recovery in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	In the stock market, Tokyo share prices fell slightly on  
profit-taking as investors locked in profits following a surge in 
the stock market the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese stocks also came under moderate selling following an  
overnight decline on Wall Street, where the Dow Jones industrial 
average was down 27.86 points, or 0.2 percent, to 10,275.53 on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders say the market will remain cautious until the release of  
the Bank of Japan's quarterly survey of business sentiment on 
Monday and the U.S. Federal Reserve's policy board meeting, also 
next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``The wait-and-see attitude is very strong,'' said Masatoshi  
Sato, manager at Kankaku Securities, who added the market's 
cautious stance Wednesday was reflected in the relatively thin 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazunori Jinnai, general manager at Daiwa Securities SB Capital  
Markets, said a better-than-expected tankan could send the Nikkei 
as high as 17,800. However, the market's gains are likely to be 
capped by renewed worries about a resurgence of the yen against the 
dollar, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A weaker-than-expected tankan, meanwhile, may push the market  
down to around the 16,800 level, said Kankaku's Sato. But beyond 
that point, the Nikkei average should be supported by hopes for 
looser monetary policy by the Bank of Japan, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo Stock Price Index, covering all first section issues,  
fell 11.18 points to 1458.11. 
</P>
<P>
	Decliners outnumbered advancers 801 to 404, while 124 issues  
remained unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the first section of the Tokyo stock exchange was  
estimated at 373.49 million shares, higher than 350.51 million 
shares Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 112.52 yen, up from  
111.61 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell  
to 1.6800 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.7150 percent. Its 
price rose 0.30 point to 100.17. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
