<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Official Convicted in Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The man the United Nations put in charge of  
travel arrangements for U.N. peacekeepers in the Balkans was 
convicted of stealing $800,000 from the organization by submitting 
false invoices. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Kim, the former U.N. chief of travel and traffic in  
Zagreb, Croatia, was convicted Tuesday in federal court on five 
counts of conspiracy and wire fraud. He faces five years in prison 
for each count and a fine of as much as twice the amount he stole. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim was responsible for making arrangements for U.N.  
peacekeepers traveling to Bosnia-Herzegovina from 1995 to '98. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, several airlines would waive baggage fees for  
peacekeepers. But federal prosecutors said Kim and travel agency 
Zagrebtours, based in Zagreb, submitted false invoices for excess 
baggage charges of $400,000, which the United Nations paid. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim also was convicted of conspiring with a former Air France  
employee to submit other inflated invoices totaling $400,000, also 
paid by the U.N. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Attorney's office said Kim tried to conceal the scheme  
by directing subordinates to destroy documents and lie to U.N. 
investigators. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
