<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Air Drops Halted in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Air drops to feed tens of thousands of  
starving East Timorese were halted today after a 3-year-old boy was 
hit by a falling box and his leg had to be amputated. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, in a sign of the violence that has torn apart East  
Timor, the charred bodies of 10 men were found in a pickup truck 
near the airport outside Dili, the capital. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. investigators surrounded the grisly find, and said they  
believed the killings took place before the arrival of the 
multinational peace force nine days ago. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the largest group of bodies to be found so far amid  
reports that hundreds, perhaps thousands, were killed by militias, 
backed by the Indonesian military, angry that East Timorese had 
voted Aug. 30 to break away from Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia today rejected plans for a U.N. fact-finding mission  
into the reported atrocities, saying foreign experts could instead 
join its own human rights probe. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Nations' main human rights body voted Monday to  
establish an international inquiry for East Timor -- a possible 
first step toward setting up a war crimes tribunal. 
</P>
<P>
	On the ground in East Timor, the cancelation of food drops  
forced aid workers to resort to convoys on roads through the 
countryside, where militias are believed to still be lurking. 
</P>
<P>
	Guarded by members of a 200-strong deployment of the elite  
Gurkhas, a convoy ventured into the region where attackers ambushed 
and killed a nine-member aid mission led by two Roman Catholic nuns 
on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Aid organizations have expressed frustration over what they say  
is the slow pace of returning security to East Timor and a looming 
humanitarian disaster if thousands of refugees who took to the 
hills during the militias' rampage don't get food soon. 
</P>
<P>
	But the troops remained stretched thin at only two-thirds of  
their authorized 7,500-member strength. 
</P>
<P>
	In the eastern districts, pro-independence guerrillas have taken  
control of areas abandoned by the Indonesian military but not yet 
reached by the multinational force, guerrilla leader Taur Matan 
Ruak said by telephone. 
</P>
<P>
	Guerrillas were fighting militia members and Indonesian soldiers  
for the countryside surrounding the southern coastal town of 
Betano, Ruak said, speaking by telephone from his mountain base 
southeast of Dili. 
</P>
<P>
	The air drops, which scattered some 28,000 food packets a day,  
were halted after the child was hit by a box Tuesday and Australian 
surgeons had to amputate his lower leg, said U.N. humanitarian 
coordination spokeswoman Afia Ali. 
</P>
<P>
	Pilots for the private airline conducting the drops also needed  
a rest after seven straight days of work, Ali said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. officials could not say if the flights would resume, but  
Ali said aid workers will shift to a land-based distribution system 
now that more refugees are coming down from the mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	They will also distribute rice instead of the high-protein  
biscuits that airplanes had been showering over the countryside. 
The biscuits apparently didn't sit well with the East Timorese, who 
are accustomed to a high-starch diet, Ali said. 
</P>
<P>
	The return of thousands of people from their hideouts in the  
hills is bringing life back to the capital's once-deserted streets. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Australian soldiers came and they told us, `You can come  
down now. We can guarantee your safety,' '' said Ito Borges, who 
returned Tuesday after two weeks in the mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	Borges was at a French military hospital, helping to tend five  
East Timorese who said Indonesian soldiers shot them Sunday when 
they ventured out of hiding to get rice for their families. Six 
people were killed in the shooting at a roadblock, the East 
Timorese said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tent cities are springing up in Dili as refugees scrounge  
plastic sheeting and scrap wood to build makeshift shelters in the 
courtyards of their burned houses. 
</P>
<P>
	But even the stronghold of the foreign troops was far from  
stable. Fire gutted an army barracks today, apparently the latest 
arson in pro-Indonesian forces' scorched-earth withdrawal from East 
Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	Overnight, a warehouse was looted of three tons of rice by  
unknown culprits, possibly hungry returnees, U.N. World Food 
Program spokeswoman Abby Spring said. 
</P>
<P>
	Western districts are expected to be the key scene of contention  
as pro-Indonesian militias retreat toward Indonesian-controlled 
West Timor. Up to 200,000 East Timorese are believed to be crowded 
into camps in West Timor, reportedly forced to accompany the 
retreating militias and now at their mercy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
