<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Group Seeks New Equity Rights Act / Commentary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *AP Business Analyst    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- As Sam Beard describes it, money is the ticket  
to the greatest show on earth, that show being the U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let money make money for everyone,'' he says, sounding like a  
cross between a philanthropist and a day trader who had just hit 
the jackpot. 
</P>
<P>
	His spiel cannot be interrupted. ``Money is an economic tool,''  
he stresses, and ``we need to put this tool into the hands of all 
Americans'' because this, he announces, ``is the age of equity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beard is neither day trader nor philanthropist -- he founded and  
heads a nonprofit organization, Economic Security 2000, and he is 
speaking about revamping Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	Few people do it more relentlessly, as Beard has demonstrated in  
visits to 50 cities a year, in broadcasts over 2,000 radio and TV 
outlets, and in visits to at least 140 editorial boards. 
</P>
<P>
	In a sense, it's an old story. Beard is an idea man who, mainly  
through the not-for-profit National Development Council, which he 
founded, influenced administrations as far back as Richard Nixon. 
</P>
<P>
	Through the council, of which he is now chairman, Beard and his  
staff sought economic opportunities in the slums, and by some 
estimates raised $30 billion and created more than a million jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	He delivers his ideas apolitically to both the right and the  
left, and to leaders of foundations and large corporations. He 
squeezes funds from both and convinces them to sit on his board. 
</P>
<P>
	He has his argument down pat. There are two pillars of financial  
success, wages and savings, he says. Most Americans, as many as 
two-thirds, rely on wages alone, having no meaningful savings. 
</P>
<P>
	However, one-third of all income in this country comes from  
savings and existing wealth, which in turn create more income and 
wealth. Wage earners are largely excluded from this income source. 
</P>
<P>
	Bad enough, says Beard, when so much wealth is being created  
through stock investments made from savings and existing wealth. 
But, he says the disparity between rich and poor is now widening. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom 50 percent of Americans own just 2 percent of the  
country's wealth,'' he continues, citing a 1995 Rand Institute 
study from which he also gleans this nugget: 
</P>
<P>
	``The financial wealth of the top 10 percent of households is  
4,653 times greater than the financial wealth of the bottom 20 
percent,'' a gap, he suggests, that is widened by investments. 
</P>
<P>
	That this should continue, he contends, is senseless and  
unnecessary, since a worker earning just $20,000 a year already 
sets aside $2,480 for Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	The big divide widens rather than closes, however, because that  
$2,480 isn't invested. Were it put into securities, he says, the 
$20,000 worker could retire with more than $300,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Democratize the earning power of equity,'' says Beard. Grow  
the middle class. Make its members stakeholders in prosperity. 
``Owning money has become the new breakthrough economic tool.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beard and his organization preach this gospel with a staff of  
six based in Washington, and with volunteers in 88 cities in 41 
states, zealously believing they'll fulfill their mission by 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Economic Security 2000 proposes a new ``Equity Rights Act'' that  
would set aside and invest a minimum of $500 a year into 
individually owned savings accounts for all Americans. It would be 
expanded from there. 
</P>
<P>
	Itsagenda also includes a broader savings policy for higher  
education, home ownership and business ownership, all of which 
contribute to and reflect participation in economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The group's arguments, developed over the past five years, are  
woven through with lesser themes built around what they view is the 
inevitable demise of the existing Social Security structure. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 03:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Judge Handles Complaint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Republican appointee on the federal appeals  
court is presiding over a formal complaint about the handling of 
criminal cases against Clinton friends Webster Hubbell and Charlie 
Trie. 
</P>
<P>
	Appeals Judge Stephen Williams, appointed by President Reagan in  
1986, wrote in a Sept. 3 letter that a ``judicial misconduct 
complaint'' filed by a conservative group, Judicial Watch, ``has 
been assigned to me, as acting chief judge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams' letter did not explain why he was handling the  
conservative group's complaint rather than the chief judge on the 
appeals court, Harry Edwards, a 1980 Carter appointee. 
</P>
<P>
	The conservative group filed the complaint after the chief judge  
of the federal district court here, Norma Holloway Johnson, 
bypassed the normal system of randomly assigning cases and sent 
prosecutions of Hubbell and campaign fund-raising figure Trie to 
appointees of President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The group also complained about meetings of Clinton appointees  
on the district court and whether various courses of action were 
discussed in an effort to obtain favorable results for the Clinton 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The conservative group had complained earlier to Edwards, who  
responded on Aug. 6 that ``I remain uncertain as to what it is you 
are seeking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams said in his letter that ``I am aware of Chief Judge  
Edwards' earlier correspondence on this matter and regret the need 
to ask for further clarification'' with further details. 
</P>
<P>
	Judicial Watch released the Williams and Edwards letters on  
Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
