<DOCNO> APW19990929.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 14:21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bell Atlantic Readies Long-distance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's largest local phone company, Bell  
Atlantic, asked federal regulators Wednesday to let it enter the 
New York long-distance market. By year's end, it could be the first 
regional Bell company to offer long-distance service to its local 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell Atlantic, which serves the Northeast and mid-Atlantic  
states, filed its application with the Federal Communications 
Commission detailing the steps it has taken to open its local phone 
business in New York to competition. That's the standard the 
company must meet, under the 1996 Telecommunications Act, before 
regulators will let it provide long-distance in its region. 
</P>
<P>
	Other Bell companies have tried this before, without success.  
But Bell Atlantic says its case is different. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have every confidence that we've done everything that's  
been required,'' Ivan Seidenberg, Bell Atlantic's chairman, told a 
news conference. ``The market is very competitive and irreversibly 
open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bell Atlantic officials pledged that if approved, consumers  
would benefit with more choices and lower costs, gaining savings 
from having a number of services -- local, long-distance and 
wireless -- provided by one company, said James Cullen, Bell 
Atlantic's chief operating officer. He said the company also would 
reach out to customers who make fewer long-distance calls, offering 
them plans with no minimum usage fee. 
</P>
<P>
	The company can deliver long-distance service over its existing  
network of phone lines going into local customers' homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell Atlantic hopes to have 25 percent of residential and  
business customers in the $8 billion-a-year New York long-distance 
market in five years. The company eventually hopes to offer 
long-distance service in Massachusetts, Pennsylvania and New Jersey 
as well. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC Chairman Bill Kennard, who met with Seidenberg on Wednesday,  
said, ``I look forward to the day when a Bell company is able to 
demonstrate that it has met the test of opening up its local market 
as a condition to being able to offer long-distance service in its 
market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC has 90 days to render a decision. It must give  
substantial consideration to a Justice Department evaluation, and 
the New York Public Service Commission, which has been actively 
involved in the process, can weigh in. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts say the difference between Bell Atlantic's application  
and past attempts by Bell companies is a 2 1/2-year process the 
company underwent to demonstrate its local market is open to 
competition. An independent third-party consultant conducted tests 
to see whether Bell Atlantic's systems can handle orders sent by 
competitors for switching customers to other local phone services. 
</P>
<P>
	The tests showed Bell Atlantic successfully processed the vast  
majority of orders, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It requires that kind of effort to build the confidence that  
they are meeting the requirement for parity,'' said Mark Cooper of 
the Consumer Federation of America. He stopped short of endorsing 
the application. 
</P>
<P>
	New York's competitive market -- with companies such as AT&AMP;T  
intending to deliver local service over its cable lines -- also will 
work in Bell Atlantic's favor, said Ragu Gurumurthy of Booz-Allen &AMP; 
Hamilton in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``The prospect of it being successful is very high,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	But New York rivals, particularly long-distance companies  
getting into the local market, say Bell Atlantic still has glitches 
when it tries to switch customers to competing local phone 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's critical that these orders be handled smoothly and  
accurately ... anything less means customers will be afraid or 
unable to choose a competitor,'' said Jim Cicconi, AT&AMP;T's general 
counsel. 
</P>
<P>
	Some consumer advocates said the application may be premature.  
</P>
<P>
	``Bell Atlantic still hasn't passed the test to show it can  
fully meet consumers' needs when it switches (local) phone 
companies,'' said Richard Kirsch of Citizen Action of New York. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
