<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tech Millionaires Follow Gates Idea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Few high-tech retirees have the wherewithal to  
match Bill and Melinda Gates' recent $1 billion gift to put a 
select number of deserving minority students through college. 
</P>
<P>
	But a growing number of ``mini-Bills'' are using their good  
fortune to help others. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Oki is among them. The retired Microsoft Corp. millionaire  
two years ago co-founded Social Venture Partners, in which 190 
partners each kick in at least $5,000 per year for distribution to 
worthy causes, mostly involving children and education. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle group's contributions increased from $300,000 in  
1998 to $670,000 this year. Next year's goal is just over $1 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Oki said the partners are doing more than just funneling money.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're thrusting them into the nonprofit area and saying, `Make  
a difference.' And they are,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	No one knows how many high-tech millionaires the past 20 years  
have brought to the Puget Sound region. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle area has more than 74,000 households with a net  
worth of at least $1 million, not counting the value of their 
primary residence, according to Tampa, Fla.-based Payment Systems 
Inc. An estimated 10,000 people alone got rich working from 
Microsoft, the huge software company run by Gates. 
</P>
<P>
	But instead of hoarding their wealth, more people are looking to  
help out others -- and charities are reaping the benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're just seeing the beginning of it,'' said  
Microsoft retiree Barbara Dingfield, now board chairwoman for 
United Way of King County. ``It's incredibly exciting for the 
Pacific Northwest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1989, contributions to United Way increased overall from  
$38.9 million to $68.6 million. Microsoft's contributions have 
grown from $938,000 to $10.5 million, while gifts from the 
high-tech industry generally have risen from $2 million to $12.7 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Microsoft and employee giving topped $26.6 million in  
cash -- about $9.6 million from employees and $17 million in matches 
and other donations from the corporation. 
</P>
<P>
	Dingfield shrugs off cynics who suggest all this giving may have  
something to do with getting tax breaks in exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you have a certain amount of net worth, it's just not that  
important,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Union Gospel Mission, which feeds and shelters the homeless,  
also has received some large donations from the high-tech 
community. And Ray diCasparo, 43, who left Microsoft after 8 1/2 
years, is working to establish a National Kidney Foundation office 
in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	He's still putting in 50-hour weeks, ``only now it doesn't feel  
like work because it's by choice and I feel like I'm helping 
people,'' he said. ``Before I was chasing the buck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many are just getting used to the idea that they're rich.  
</P>
<P>
	``They don't feel wealthy because they don't live that way,''  
said United Way president and chief executive Joanne Harrell. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Dingfield, who worked in corporate giving at Microsoft, said  
most employee donations go to human services and education, 
followed by arts and the environment. 
</P>
<P>
	``In general, health and education always get the lion's  
share,'' said Wendy McDowell at the Pacific Northwest Ballet. But 
she has hopes that the dance company and its school will benefit, 
too. 
</P>
<P>
	Gates, Microsoft's chairman and the world's richest man with an  
estimated net worth of $85 billion, earlier this month announced 
the ``Gates Millennium Scholars Program,'' which will provide 1,000 
scholarships a year for 20 years to Asian-American, black, Hispanic 
and American Indian students through the Bill and Melinda Gates 
Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	With assets of $17 billion, the foundation is the second-largest  
philanthropic foundation in the world, behind London-based Wellcome 
Trust. 
</P>
<P>
	Gates is subscribing to Henry Ford's notion that it's ``a better  
thing to empower your employees to make their own philanthropic 
choices,'' said Peter Hall, an expert on nonprofits and a senior 
research scholar at Yale. 
</P>
<P>
	``By creating this whole cohort of millionaires,'' Hall said,  
``he's also created a philanthropic community.'' 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
