<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> At ARM's Length No More? / On the Money  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- With mortgage rates on the rise, ARMs are no  
longer getting a cold shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Adjustable rate mortgages, or ARMs, as they're best known, are  
slowly making a comeback after being ignored by many borrowers who 
had felt their reduced initial rates didn't produce enough monthly 
savings to warrant the risk of higher rates later on. 
</P>
<P>
	But with rates on 30-year fixed mortgages creeping above 8  
percent -- up from a three-decade low of 6.68 percent last fall -- 
adjustable loans carrying initial rates in the 5-, 6- or 7 percent 
range are starting to look more attractive to some folks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year was a no-brainer to take a 30-year fixed-rate  
mortgage,'' said Keith Gumbinger, a vice president for HSH 
Associates, a Butler, N.J.-based mortgage research firm, which 
provides rate information to consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	``You couldn't market an ARM before; it was a waste of marketing  
money,'' he said. ``But as we have progressed through the summer, 
there has been a step up in market allocations for ARMs of all 
forms. We've had an appreciable increase in the amount of consumer 
interest in ARMs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ARMs now account for about a quarter of all home mortgages, more  
than double their market share from last spring -- just weeks before 
the Federal Reserve began to hike up interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed raised short-term rates twice over the summer as a  
pre-emptive strike against inflation. As a result, long-term rates 
in the public bond markets also headed higher, and that pushed up 
consumer loan rates, including rates on 15- and 30-year mortgages. 
The rate on a 30-year loan stood at nearly 8 percent by late 
September while the rate on a 15-year loan averaged around 7.6 
percent and the rate on a one-year ARM was 6.33 percent, according 
to HSH. 
</P>
<P>
	For those who don't expect to be in their homes very long --  
perhaps under three years -- a one-year ARM with a low ``teaser'' 
rate might be a good bet. The rate is adjusted annually according 
to prevailing market rates, usually tied to the one-year Treasury 
bill. And there's usually a two-point annual cap, so the rate won't 
go sky high should interest rates rise that second year. (There's 
usually a 6 percent cap over the life of the loan.) 
</P>
<P>
	``People who have been on ARMs have done very well because rates  
have pretty much trended downward for the past decade,'' said Peter 
G. Miller, author of several consumer books on mortgages, including 
``The Common Sense Mortgage.'' (Contemporary Books, Chicago) ``So 
getting an ARM when there's a temporary spike in interest has 
proven to be a pretty good bet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, not everyone may feel comfortable with a loan that  
carries an interest rate that changes every year. For them, there 
are ``hybrid'' ARMs, in which rates are fixed for longer periods, 
usually anywhere from three to 10 years, then adjusted each year 
thereafter. There are also ARMs that are fixed for a period of 
time, adjusted once, then fixed for the remainder of the loan -- 
like a 7-23, which has seven years of stability, one change, then 
23 years of fixed payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Gumbinger says hybrid ARMs have become increasingly popular in  
recent weeks, particularly the 5-1 loan, which carries a 7.25 
percent rate for the first five years before it's adjusted 
annually. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over the next five years you can save a few bucks,'' Gumbinger  
said, comparing the current rate of a 5-1 loan to a 30-year 
fixed-rate loan. 
</P>
<P>
	According to his calculations, interest and principal on a  
$100,000 5-1 loan at 7.25 percent would be $682.17 per month during 
the first five years, with interest totaling $35,309.34 during that 
time. Someone with a 30-year fixed mortgage at 7.95 percent would 
pay $730 each month, or $38,842.99 in interest for the five years. 
Total savings in interest: $3,533.65 -- enough to fill your home 
with some furnishings or appliances. 
</P>
<P>
	The rates on other hybrid ARMs are also lower than 30-year  
rates. By late September, the 3-1 loan initially averaged 7.13 
percent; the 7-1, 7.51 percent; and the 10-1, 7.67 percent, 
according to HSH. 
</P>
<P>
	Because borrowers have stayed away from ARMs for some time, many  
will probably have to reacquaint themselves with the concept. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to sit down and run the numbers to see what things  
really cost you.'' said Miller. ``You have to ask yourself how long 
are you going to be in the property.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller says the advantage of getting an ARM right now is not  
only lower rates but more liberal qualification standards. Many 
ARMs are kept on lenders' books rather than sold into the secondary 
market, which is often the case with fixed-rate mortgage 
originators. Therefore, that means they often don't have to meet 
strict federal guidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	``Someone with a given income can borrow more or someone who  
might not have qualified with a fixed-rate loan will qualify with 
an ARM,'' Miller said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
