<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nichols Gets Attorney He Wanted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Terry Nichols got the attorney he wanted  
for his state trial on murder charges in the Oklahoma City bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Hermanson was originally appointed by the Oklahoma  
Indigent Defense System to represent Nichols, but his contract was 
canceled after state lawmakers withdrew $900,000 that had been set 
aside for Nichols' defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, the Oklahoma Supreme Court has approved almost $1  
million for Nichols' defense. The money will come from a state 
court fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Nichols wrote Associate District Judge Robert M. Murphy Jr. of  
Payne County in July asking that Hermanson be retained. He said 
replacing the attorney ``would seriously jeopardize my defense ... 
and thus, in the long run cost more money and court time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an order Wednesday, Murphy noted that Nichols and Hermanson  
had established a bond that should not be disturbed except for 
compelling reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Nichols is serving a life sentence on federal conspiracy and  
involuntary manslaughter convictions in the April 19, 1995, bombing 
that killed 168 people and injured more than 500. 
</P>
<P>
	Timothy McVeigh, his former Army buddy, was convicted of murder  
and weapons counts and sentenced to death. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
