<DOCNO> APW19990929.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 23:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study Examines Spider Eyesight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A European spider uses two of its eight eyes as an ``optical  
compass'' to find its way home after an evening of prowling for 
victims, researchers reported today in the journal Nature. 
</P>
<P>
	Because three-quarters of all spider species are equipped with  
similar eyes, the research suggests they also navigate by using the 
organs to produce a sort of sky road map in polarized light. 
</P>
<P>
	Swedish scientists studied Drassodes cupreus, an inch-long  
spider found in northern Europe. The spider constructs a silky nest 
under rocks and leaves and forages at dusk in search of prey. 
</P>
<P>
	As it creeps about, the brown and gray spider uses its special  
set of flat blue eyes to scan the evening sky like a pair of 
polarized sunglasses to filter out light scattered by the 
atmosphere, the researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The spider can't actually see with the eyes. Instead, the eyes  
reveal polarized light patterns that change as the sun moves across 
the sky. 
</P>
<P>
	The patterns serve as a sort of road map the spiders pair with  
images from their regular eyes to lead them home, said Marie Dacke, 
one of the researchers and a doctoral student in zoology at the 
University of Lund. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's partly cloudy that's not a problem -- all it needs is a  
portion of clear sky to work. But if it's totally overcast or 
raining it won't work,'' said Dacke, who worked with four other 
scientists. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers built a model of the eyes and found that it  
works best at dawn or dusk, when the spiders are most active. The 
model eye was useful for up to an hour after sunset, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	While some insects and vertebrates also interpret polarized  
light for navigation, Dacke said her team's research is the first 
time specialized polarizing optics have been found in any animal. 
</P>
<P>
	Dacke's team found that nine of 10 spiders that made a nest in  
one of four shelters within the enclosure returned to the same nest 
after their first foraging trip. 
</P>
<P>
	But when the spiders had their secondary eyes obscured with  
black paint, only three out of 10 returned to their original 
shelter. The same results were obtained when unpolarized light was 
projected into the spider's enclosure. 
</P>
<P>
	Dacke is currently studying 15 other species of spiders to see  
whether they also use secondary eyes to see in polarized light. 
</P>
<P>
	Jonathan Coddington, the Smithsonian Institution's top spider  
researcher, said the research may explain the hereto unexplained 
purpose of similar eyes found in 25,000 of the world's 37,000 
spider species. 
</P>
<P>
	The secondary eyes, which cannot discern spatial structures,  
have puzzled spider experts for decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would be willing to bet a lot of money that what's true for  
this spider is true for many other spiders,'' Coddington said. 
``These folks have provided an explanation that is powerful. It 
will certainly rock the world of spider research.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 16:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patriots Sign Two, Waive Two </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- The New England Patriots on Wednesday  
signed running backs Jerry Ellison and Marques Brigham and waived 
offensive tackle Damon Denson and defensive tackle Garrett Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellison, who played four seasons with Tampa Bay, fills a need on  
special teams where the Patriots suffered injuries last Sunday 
night to key players Harold Shaw, Chris Floyd, Tebucky Jones and 
Bernard Russ. Shaw is a running back and Floyd a fullback. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Pete Carroll said he didn't know if any of the four would  
play next Sunday at Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Denson, a fourth-round draft pick by the Patriots in 1997, was  
released on the last roster cutdown of training camp. He was 
re-signed after offensive linemen Heath Irwin and Zefross Moss were 
injured, but both could play against the Browns. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, signed as a free agent, was cut on Sept. 5 then signed  
to the Patriots practice squad Sept. 7. He was replaced on the 
practice squad by Brigham, who had been cut after signing with 
Oakland as a rookie free agent following this year's draft, then 
signed by the Patriots Aug. 17 and cut Aug. 30. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
