<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 23:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Acting More Like Challenger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore is reinventing his  
campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination -- with the 
tactics of a challenger, not those of a lofty front-runner. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a role reversal for the vice president who began as the  
presumed nominee-in-waiting, with former Sen. Bill Bradley running 
but not threatening. 
</P>
<P>
	No more.  
</P>
<P>
	Gore challenged Bradley to campaign debates. He is moving his  
headquarters from Washington to Nashville, ``closer to the 
grassroots and out of the Beltway.'' The campaign payroll will be 
pruned in the process. 
</P>
<P>
	``I welcome the new shape of this campaign,'' Gore said  
Wednesday, as though he wouldn't have preferred the old one to the 
``hard, tough fight'' he foresees now. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, he said he no longer felt like a front-runner.  
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like the underdog. I'm going to campaign like the  
underdog and I think that's the way to get elected,'' he said 
Wednesday night on CNN's ``Larry King Live.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said a ``hard fought'' contest will sharpen both campaigns,  
both candidates. But campaigns are not workouts waged to make 
better candidates -- the aim is winning. Gore is no longer sure 
enough of that to run on his earlier campaign plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Not with Bradley gaining on him in polls of Democrats in the  
early primary states, and raising ample funds, despite Gore's still 
comfortable lead in national polls. That is among Democrats, not in 
matchups for the general election, which put Republican Gov. George 
W. Bush of Texas ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	While Bradley served three terms in the Senate from New Jersey,  
he's cast himself as the outsider, the candidate of change, and the 
one with the best chance of winning. He has been making headway 
using all three. And when Gore said he would take his campaign 
``directly to the grassroots'' with open meetings in the early 
primary states, Bradley countered that he already was. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's debate challenge put him in the role usually played by  
the candidate trying to catch up with a leader, as when the 
Republicans trailing Bush tried it, unsuccessfully. 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president said he wants to meet Bradley in a series of  
debates on specific issues. Bradley countered that he was not in 
the habit of responding to every change in tactics by the vice 
president. He said he'd already agreed to joint appearances, and 
the first is scheduled for Oct. 27 in New Hampshire, the first 
primary state. 
</P>
<P>
	With the first voting, in Iowa, some four months away, the  
preseason has not gone well for Gore. He came into it in apparent 
command of the Democratic campaign, with Bradley too far behind to 
require his mention. 
</P>
<P>
	That's standard procedure for a front-runner; the theory is that  
talking about rivals, let alone debating them, only gets them 
attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the last 10 months, the vice president and his campaign  
have been ignoring me and now they want to debate me,'' said 
Bradley, campaigning in California for the primary that could be 
pivotal. ``I think that shows we're making some progress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Gore, as for any front-runner, every misstep is magnified.  
As in the talk of a listless beginning, the rumors of friction with 
the president, denied on both sides. There was said to be 
infighting, indecision, a campaign spending too much money on a 
top-heavy staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley hasn't faced such strains. He can travel lighter than a  
vice president. His headquarters is West Orange, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	He also took in campaign money at a rate that surprised the Gore  
camp. While Gore leads in raising money, he also leads in spending 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	For all of it, while Gore's lead for the nomination may have  
eroded, it is not gone. The vice president has the backing of the 
Democratic establishment, endorsements from more than 100 members 
of Congress, the advantages of the office from which no vice 
president who sought the presidential nomination has been denied it 
since 1952. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it is a worried establishment. Sen. Daniel Patrick  
Moynihan of New York said why when he endorsed Bradley. ``Nothing 
is the matter with Gore, but he can't be elected,'' Moynihan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Add the Clinton factor. Elections are about change. Gore has to  
offer change while running as Clinton's No. 2. ``I think there's 
fatigue with questions about Clinton fatigue,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's still there.  
</P>
<P>
	One of the old problems lingering for the ``brand new campaign''  
he said is ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist  
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national 
politics for more than 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
