<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farm Bill Nears Passage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican leaders in Congress were close  
Wednesday night to breaking a week-long impasse on agricultural 
spending after burying a Senate plan that would have allowed U.S. 
food and medicine sales to Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders needed the blessing of a House-Senate conference  
committee on a proposed agreement that would provide farmers 
plagued by droughts, floods and low prices with nearly $9 billion 
in emergency assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	Two leading Democrats on the panel endorsed the deal late  
Wednesday after winning a pledge that it would include $125 million 
in special subsidies for dairy farmers. Shelved was an effort to 
overturn the Clinton administration's milk pricing program. 
</P>
<P>
	In a joint statement, Rep. David Obey and Sen. Herb Kohl  
predicted that the deal would ``go forward'' to final approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Both are from Wisconsin. Obey is the senior Democrat on the  
House Appropriations Committee, while Kohl is the senior Democrat 
on the Senate's agricultural appropriations subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	Another panel member, Sen. Conrad Burns, R-Mont., announced his  
support for the deal after winning a provision that would require 
meatpackers to report the prices they pay for livestock. ``That 
means a lot ... I'm happy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But GOP leaders refused to budge on the Cuba issue and came  
under fire from members of their own party. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be foolhardy if we addressed the emergency but failed  
to address this structure where farmers are not able to market 
their products around the world,'' said the measure's sponsor, Sen. 
John Ashcroft, R-Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	House leaders didn't want non-spending provisions in the bill,  
said John Feehery, a spokesman for House Speaker Dennis Hastert. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to get this thing done,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Democrats complained they were excluded from negotiations, but  
they will not try to slow down the bill if it gets out of the 
conference committee, said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, 
D-S.D. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't think we have much leverage because we're not even in  
the room,'' Daschle said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some farm groups, including the huge American Farm Bureau  
Federation, wanted lawmakers to reject the proposed deal if it 
didn't include the dairy and trade provisions and enough money to 
cover farmers' weather-related losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Chamber of Commerce also weighed in Wednesday against  
the agreement because of the Cuba issue. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to opening trade with Cuba, Ashcroft's measure would  
forbid the president from stopping sales of agricultural products 
and medical supplies to other countries without congressional 
approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers from dairy states in the South and East had opposed  
the administration's new milk-pricing system, which had been 
scheduled to take effect Friday, and tried to use the bill to 
overturn it. A federal judge on Tuesday postponed implementation of 
the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Kohl and Obey support the new system and fought to keep it out  
of the bill. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
