<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Surge / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks surged Thursday morning, bolstered  
by the dollar's relative steadiness against the yen and higher 
futures prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average climbed 324.74  
points, or 1.88 percent, to 17,607.02 at the end of the morning 
session. On Wednesday, the average closed down 43.42 points, or 
0.25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 106.82 yen at late morning, down 0.08 yen from  
late Wednesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 
106.98 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo share prices moved higher from the opening of trading as  
investors were actively buying international blue chips and other 
domestic issues, including pharmaceuticals and banking stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Hiroichi Nishi, deputy general manager at Nikko Securities Co.,  
said the stock market was boosted by some bullish factors, 
including the dollar's brief rise to 107 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Also supporting the market was a rise in futures prices. The  
December Nikkei futures contract was up 350 points to 17,600 at 
midday Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 62.05 points, or 0.6 percent, to 10,213.48. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 34.91 points, or 2.39 percent, to 1,493.02. 
The TOPIX closed down 11.18 points, or 0.76 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite a slight retreat, the dollar still held onto its  
strength in New York, where the greenback gained ground for a third 
consecutive day Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders still expect the Bank of Japan may ease credit following  
a weekend meeting by major industrialized nations, a move seen as 
potentially weakening the yen. At the Washington meeting, officials 
of the Group of Seven nations expressed concern over the yen's 
rapid rise. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen's strong gains could derail Japan's recovery from a  
recession by making Japanese exports more expensive abroad and thus 
reducing demand for its products. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 113.74 yen, up from  
112.52 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.7000 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.6750 percent. Its 
price fell 0.21 points to 100.00. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
