<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Tops $25 a Barrel; Gold Falls  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil futures rocketed briefly above $25 a barrel Wednesday  
to a 33-month high on the New York Mercantile Exchange, propelled 
by falling U.S. stockpiles. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold, too, remained above a noteworthy threshold it reached this  
week -- $300 an ounce -- but just barely after prices tumbled 3 
percent on the heels of a stunning rally. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium belatedly followed gold's rise, jumping 3 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	Continuing a year of steady increases, crude topped $25 for the  
first time in 2 1/2 years and then rose to $25.12 before falling back 
in a flurry of late-session profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest surge came after the U.S. Department of Energy said  
Wednesday that already-low U.S. crude stockpiles had dropped by 4.3 
million barrels last week. That exceeded an earlier report by the 
American Petroleum Institute that showed a 3.7-million-barrel 
decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil prices have more than doubled since last spring, when the  
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries opted for significant 
production cuts in order to chip away at the world oil glut that 
had caused prices to sink. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say no end appears in sight to the trend, although  
there could be more profit-taking to slow it down. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market looks pretty favorable going forward,'' said an oil  
futures trader who asked not to be named. But, he said, ``We're due 
for a correction before we resume some upward movement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the day, West Texas intermediate crude oil for November  
delivery rose 36 cents to settle at $24.69 a barrel. 
</P>
<P>
	October heating oil rose .45 cent to 62.13 cents a gallon;  
October unleaded regular gasoline rose half a cent to 73.25 cents a 
gallon; November natural gas fell 3.1 cents to $2.824 per million 
British thermal units. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent crude rose 5 cents to $23.81 a  
gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold's frenzied price rally stalled and went into reverse on the  
Comex division of the New York Merc. Profit-taking sent the price 
down $8 to close at $302 per troy ounce, just a day after it had 
spiraled as high as $329 and closed 9 percent higher in the biggest 
one-day rally in nearly 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Also driving gold down was news that Russia may place 7.3  
million ounces with Western banks, enabling it to be lent to the 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the market was readjusting after the wild ride  
that has taken it from $255 an ounce in a week -- a more than 20 
percent rise until Wednesday's slump. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite price slides in other metals such as silver and  
platinum, palladium bucked the trend and settled up $13.70 at 
$391.85 an ounce. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier the metal hit $405, in what market-watchers said was a  
delayed reaction to gold's rise. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium is used heavily in the automotive industry in the  
manufacture of emission-control devices. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
