<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> eBay Moves Against 'Piggybackers' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Online auctioneer eBay is cracking down on  
new Internet services that sift through auction Web sites to find 
the best prices for potential bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also has released a new user agreement that  
prohibits individual users from collecting or sharing certain 
information found on eBay's Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman Kevin Pursglove said the moves were made to protect  
eBay from companies or individuals seeking to ``piggy-back'' on 
eBay's success. 
</P>
<P>
	Several new Web sites search sites for goods being auctioned and  
compare prices offered. BiddersEdge.com and another service, Ruby 
Lane, stopped using eBay auction data when eBay refused to give 
them permission. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, eBay also asked AuctionWatch.com to stop  
using eBay information. 
</P>
<P>
	Pursglove said part of the problem is that the other sites  
misrepresent what is being offered on eBay. For example, a search 
for Pez candy dispensers on AuctionWatch.com, which searches items 
listed on eBay, Yahoo, Amazon.com and other sites, turned up 227 
listings, at a time when eBay's site listed about 1,900 Pez items. 
</P>
<P>
	``How accurate is the information being distributed?'' Pursglove  
asked. ``Not very.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rodrigo Sales, chief executive officer and cofounder of San  
Bruno, Calif.-based AuctionWatch.com, said his customers were 
concerned about eBay's new user policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``As an advocate of the user community, we think it is more  
important to represent user reaction rather than our own take,'' 
Sales said in a statement Wednesday. ``From the reaction on our 
message boards, I can say that users are not happy about the 
revised terms, because they feel it restricts their freedom to buy 
and sell across the Web.'' 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
