<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vintner Winning Respect for Wines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GOULDSBORO, Maine (AP) -- Most fruit wines either fall under the  
categories of dessert wine or cheap, sweet wine consumed from 
bottles wrapped in paper sacks. Some call them ``country wines.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Robert Bartlett thinks fruit wines can be just as good as  
traditional wines made from grapes. And he is winning respect as a 
vintner using everything from honey to blackberries to pears. 
</P>
<P>
	He realizes he has a skeptical audience.  
</P>
<P>
	``We get people in the wine-tasting room who are grape wine  
connoisseurs. You can see in their face that they are impressed,'' 
Bartlett said. ``That's the hard part -- getting people to try it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bartlett, whose 18-year-old Bartlett Maine Estate Winery  
produces about 7,000 cases of wine a year, is among fewer than 200 
fruit wineries across the country, said Dan Archibald, editor of 
Fruit Winemaking Quarterly in California. 
</P>
<P>
	Although it makes up only a fraction of total wine sales, fruit  
wine -- the term applied to wine made from fruit other than grapes -- 
is gaining greater public acceptance, Archibald said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even some wineries with major lables, such as Gallo, Sutter Home  
and Arbor Mist, are experimenting with fruit flavors. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinchero Family Estates, which produces Sutter Home, has come  
up with combinations such as white zinfandel with kiwi-strawberry, 
white zinfandel with peach-mango and zinfandel with raspberry. 
</P>
<P>
	In just 18 months, wine makers nationwide have shipped between 4  
million to 5 million cases of those flavored wines, said Stan Hock, 
spokesman for Trinchero Family Estates in California, which created 
two special labels, Portico and Soleo, for its fruit-flavored 
offerings. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether the success of fruit-flavored grape wines translates to  
success for pure fruit wines remains to be seen. 
</P>
<P>
	Bartlett is nearing his maximum production unless he buys more  
equipment to expand his operation, which consists of a German 
press, 10 stainless steel vats for fermentation, wooden casks for 
aging and Italian bottling and labeling equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	Like many fruit vintners, Bartlett opted for nontraditional  
fruits because Maine's climate is not conducive to growing grapes. 
He uses native blueberries and apples, among other fruits. 
</P>
<P>
	For many, the very thought of those fruits conjures notions of  
syrupy sweet wines, and that's how many still perceive fruit wines, 
which often have a higher sugar content than grape wines. 
</P>
<P>
	But vintners like Bartlett are winning over fans of grape wines  
by producing traditional dry wines. 
</P>
<P>
	Bartlett has put his blueberry wine up against conventional red  
wines and has done well. 
</P>
<P>
	In blindfolded tastings, people were unable to tell the  
difference between traditional red wines and his blueberry wines, 
some of which are aged in either American or French oak casks, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	His Winemaker's Reserve Blueberry, which sells for $23.99, was  
ranked one of the world's top 40 red wines by the Beverage Testing 
Institute Inc., as reported in ``Wine Enthusiast'' magazine in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	His pear, blueberry and ``Coastal White'' wines, along with his  
raspberry dessert wine, also did well in the latest tests of 
domestic wines published in August in the institute's journal, 
``Tastings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes I think it's becoming more mainstream,'' Bartlett  
said. ``Then sometimes I think it's not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For now, most fruit wine makers cater to regional niche markets,  
said Ted Huber, owner and winemaker Huber Orchard Winery in 
Starlight, Ind., across the Ohio River from Louisville, Ky. 
</P>
<P>
	Huber said fruit wines allow him to use excess fruit produced on  
his farm, and they also allow him to spread out his wine production 
throughout the season, starting with strawberries in the spring, 
blackberries, raspberries and peaches through the summer, Concord 
grapes in the fall, and apples in November. 
</P>
<P>
	``If people haven't tried a fruit wine from a small winery that  
cares about its product, they need to get out and try it,'' said 
Huber, who makes 27,000 gallons a year. ``I think they'll be 
pleasantly surprised.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nationwide, vintners are more willing to experiment after the  
success of white zinfandel, a creation of domestic vintners that 
became a best seller despite being looked down upon by 
traditionalists and by vintners in Europe, Hock said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Purists scoff at it, but Americans love it,'' he said. ``That  
tells us we can emulate what the French do and shove it down the 
throats of Americans, or we can make what Americans want.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whether such small fruit vintners make a bigger splash may  
ultimately be decided by a new generation of wine drinkers. 
</P>
<P>
	Generation X currently doesn't drink much wine and vintners hope  
they can lure them in with the fruit wines. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's this whole issue of what's going to be the buying  
interest of the 'Generation X-ers,''' Archibald said. ``Nobody has 
really taken the time to look at this emerging group and what their 
tastebuds are.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
