<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Tiger Cubs Make D.C. Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Three rare Sumatran Tiger cubs enjoyed their  
coming out party at the National Zoo on Wednesday, frolicking in 
their den under the watchful eye of their mother and some curious 
humans. 
</P>
<P>
	Chrissie, Eric and Mike were born June 24 to Kerinci, a  
14-year-old tigress, but have been hidden from spectators until 
now. Each weighs about 27 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like to watch them, because they're playful and they're  
cute. I also think they would make good pets, because if somebody 
tried to hurt me they could save me,'' said 7-year-old Kaitlyn 
Osteguin, who was visiting the zoo with her class. 
</P>
<P>
	The tiger that sired the cubs -- 8-year-old Rokan -- was kept away  
for fear he would hurt them. But looking on like a proud papa was 
curator John Seidensticker, credited by zoo officials with bringing 
Kerinci to Washington from a zoo in Jakarta, Indonesia, in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is great. This is what we do,'' said Seidensticker, as he  
watched the cubs play hide and seek among bamboo leaves. 
</P>
<P>
	This is Kerinci's third litter. Conservationists say the zoo has  
helped to save the Sumatran Tiger from extinction. Fewer than 500 
live in the wild on the island of Sumatra, experts say. 
</P>
<P>
	Just one of Kerinci's other cubs, named Soy, remains at the  
National Zoo. Soy is expected to mate with Rokan someday. 
</P>
<P>
	A certain rivalry exists between mother and daughter. ``They  
would kill each other if we didn't keep them apart,'' said lion 
keeper Brad Blaine. 
</P>
<P>
	While Kerinci will stay here, the new cubs are expected to go to  
other zoos when they are about 2 years old, Seidensticker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chrissie and Eric were named for children who won an art  
contest. Mike was named for Zoo Director Michael Robinson and the 
Smithsonian's outgoing director, I. Michael Heyman. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his namesakes, Mike isn't the one with the leadership  
skills. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chrissie is definitely the leader. She's the bold one,''  
Seidensticker said. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Live video of the tiger cubs is available at the  
National Zoo Web site: www.si.edu/natzoo 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
