<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 16:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bengals' Carter Out for Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Ki-Jana Carter is going to miss another season  
because of injury, adding to his legacy as a star-crossed No. 1 
draft pick. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cincinnati Bengals put Carter on injured reserve Wednesday,  
three days after he dislocated his right kneecap in a 27-3 loss at 
Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	They also waived fullback Brian Milne, who was inactive the last  
two games because of a sprained knee. It was a surprising move for 
an 0-3 team that has the least-experienced roster in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a shame,'' said Milne, who has started 36 games in  
Cincinnati. ``Last year, I was told I was in the top five in 
fullbacks in the NFL. The Bengals are losing a real good 
fullback.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals promoted running back Michael Basnight from their  
practice squad and claimed running back Sedrick Shaw off waivers 
from Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	For the third time since he was the No. 1 overall pick in 1995,  
Carter suffered a major injury when no one touched him. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's freaky. It's unfortunate,'' coach Bruce Coslet said. ``I  
don't have an adjective to describe it. It's indescribable to me 
because I was counting on him and now I don't have him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carter tore up his left knee on his third carry of the 1995  
preseason, going down after making a cut in the backfield before a 
defender touched him. He had reconstructive surgery and missed the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	He tore the rotator cuff in his left shoulder early in the 1997  
season but continued to play. Last year, he shattered his wrist 
when he fell backwards after making a reception in the season 
opener, causing him to miss the season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals planned to feature him in the backfield with Corey  
Dillon this year, but he dislocated his kneecap while changing 
direction after Jeff Blake threw an interception. 
</P>
<P>
	As with the broken wrist, Carter wasn't near a defender when he  
got hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``People talk about is he snake-bit, just unlucky, is he jinxed,  
is he not taking care of himself, is he not in shape? None of the 
above? Who knows?'' Coslet said. ``I couldn't tell you. On the last 
two -- the broken wrist and the dislocated kneecap -- he didn't get 
touched, he just fell over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carter wasn't at the team's practice facility Wednesday. He'll  
begin a rehabilitation program that might allow him to avoid 
surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Milne's teammates were stunned when they came out of Wednesday's  
meetings and saw him packing. He received one hug after another. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll tell you what: With the look on some of these guys' faces  
when I told them, this team's going to be devastated,'' Milne said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coslet declined to talk about the move.  
</P>
<P>
	General manager Mike Brown said in a telephone interview from  
home that Milne was waived because the team felt it needed another 
running back with Carter out. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaw, 26, played in the Browns' first three games, picking up  
two yards on three carries and eight yards on two receptions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Brian played hard and effectively for us,'' Brown said. ``We  
don't feel that we can afford to go into a game as thin at running 
back as we are. And Shaw is a veteran. He'll come in and he'll take 
a week or two to get up to speed perhaps, but at least when he does 
he's a guy who's been there before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Milne said he'll file a grievance because he was waived while he  
was still recovering from the sprained knee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
