<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Treasury Head Notes Complacency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- Former U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert  
Rubin warned Wednesday that the world has grown complacent about 
its financial system as it has emerged from a series of crises. 
</P>
<P>
	``With each successfully averted crisis, with each near miss,  
our complacent certainty that matters will always work out grows, 
as does the unsoundness of our decisions,'' Rubin said in a 
comments prepared for delivery to a meeting of global business 
leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said the world financial system has grown stronger after  
two to three years of crisis. He credited the international 
community, including the International Monetary Fund, for trying to 
ensure that globalization continues. 
</P>
<P>
	``But the underlying problems have not vanished,'' he said. ``I  
believe the greatest danger we now face is the danger of 
complacency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said that technology, globalization and other factors are  
changing economics. 
</P>
<P>
	Vulnerable countries must continue reforms and ``too often,  
despite real progress, substantial commitments have not been fully 
met,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
