<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hot Weather Hinders Firefighters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIG SUR, Calif. (AP) -- Temperatures in the 90s made work tougher  
on firefighters battling wildfires that have burned more 125,000 
acres of California wilderness. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the higher temperatures, the higher winds and the low  
humidity, you do have more active fires,'' said fire information 
officer Juanita Freel. ``But that's not the main difficulty in 
fighting these fires. It's the terrain. It's steep and rugged.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 3,300 firefighters were battling two large wildfires that  
had burned 49,543 acres in the Los Padres National Forest on the 
scenic central California coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Fire lines that were expanded Monday to protect homes north of  
Lucia, on the coast about 115 miles south of San Francisco, 
continued to hold Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents were evacuated from the area on Monday. Fire officials  
did not know the exact number of residents told to leave, but said 
there were up to a dozen homes and numerous other buildings at 
risk. 
</P>
<P>
	A camp helper in Trinity Alps Wilderness died late Monday after  
suffering a heart attack while being evacuated. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest problem was the Hare Fire, which had burned 20,993  
acres as of Tuesday and was only 20 percent contained. Another 
fire, the Tassajara fire, had burned 28,450 acres and was 45 
percent contained. 
</P>
<P>
	A series of fires started by lightning last month had burned  
more than 77,000 acres in the region by Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, low humidity and winds gusting to 30 miles an hour  
pushed the so-called Megram Fire over containment lines, burning 
60,602 acres by late Tuesday. It was 40 percent contained. 
</P>
<P>
	To the south in Shasta County, fire fighters continued to  
monitor a wildfire that destroyed 49 homes and 110 other buildings 
on Sunday. The Happy Valley fire burned 2,580 acres and caused an 
estimated $1 million in damage, said Dee Floyd of the California 
Department of Forestry. Full control of the blaze was expected by 
Thursday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
