<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 07:50:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> After-Hours Traders To Get Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The organization that operates the New York  
Stock Exchange ticker tape -- which feeds prices to Web sites and 
streams them across TV screens -- will extend its hours of operation 
to help answer calls for a centralized stock information system. 
</P>
<P>
	The extra shift -- from 5:15 p.m. Eastern time to 6:35 p.m. --  
could begin as early as Monday. The change requires final approval 
from the Securities and Exchange Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The move will give after-hours investors more information and  
follows a similar one by the organization that runs the Nasdaq 
Stock Market, meaning that the closing price for most stocks is 
effectively pushed back by one hour and 20 minutes. That could 
force mutual funds, newspapers and others who tally such figures to 
rethink how they will publish the information. 
</P>
<P>
	The proliferation of after-hours trading sessions scattered  
across a number of different stock markets and electronic trading 
networks has prompted calls for the extension of hours of 
centralized stock information systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the NYSE, Nasdaq Stock Market and American Stock  
Exchange all close at 4 p.m., trading now goes on at some regional 
exchanges and electronic networks into the early evening. However 
stock price data is currently collected until 5:15 p.m., making 
that the traditional cutoff time for official closing prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Jones, a professor of finance at the Columbia University  
Business School in New York, said the extended NYSE ticker hours 
are ``a first step'' toward creating a single, centralized market 
information system, a move recently advocated by Securities and 
Exchange Commission Chairman Arthur Levitt. 
</P>
<P>
	The move by the Consolidated Tape Association, which  
disseminates NYSE stock quotes, means investors will have one more 
tool for obtaining ``timely stock price information on trades 
taking place in the after-hours markets,'' Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	The extension of ticker hours was prompted by a request from the  
Chicago Stock Exchange, which trades NYSE-listed stocks for 
regional customers and has applied to the SEC to extend its hours 
to 6:30 p.m. The NYSE and the Nasdaq are also planning extended 
sessions, but not until next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul O'Kelly, an executive vice president at the Chicago  
exchange, said the extended session won't be approved until the 
exchange can show that information on after-hours trades will be 
properly disseminated. 
</P>
<P>
	``An essential part of running a market is dissemination of  
quotes,'' O'Kelly said. ``Now, just as there is during the day, we 
expect that there will be widespread dissemination of stock quotes 
that take place in the after-hours markets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	O'Kelly said the decision to extend Consolidated Tape  
Association ticker hours will grow in importance as additional 
regional exchanges extend their hours. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision by the tape association will only affect investors  
who trade on its member exchanges. That group includes the NYSE, 
the Nasdaq and American Stock Exchange, and the regional exchanges 
in Chicago, Boston and Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	A handful of electronic networks have proposed creating their  
own centralized price dissemination system similar to the 
association. Currently, investors can only get information on the 
specific electronic network where they are trading, which has led 
to criticism that the after-hours sessions are too fragmented 
because investors may not know where to get the best price. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Securities Dealers, which operates  
the Nasdaq, announced last month that it will try to get more 
information to after-hours investors by making Nasdaq stock prices 
available at a central location until 6:30 p.m. beginning Nov. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	All of this raises questions about how mutual funds, newspapers  
and other organizations that use closing stock prices will adapt to 
the changes brought on by the growing popularity of after-hours 
session. 
</P>
<P>
	The mutual fund industry has said it will continue to price  
funds based on the 4 p.m. closing time of the NYSE and the Nasdaq 
until after-hours trading volume warrants a change. 
</P>
<P>
	Newspapers will likely adapt on an individual basis. For  
example, West Coast papers, whose deadlines are later than East 
Coast papers, may use the updated quotes for their stock tables. 
Other papers may use a list of stocks that trade actively after 
hours. Still others may choose to use the prices disseminated at 
5:15 p.m., when the Consolidated Tape Association and Nasdaq 
currently shut down their pricing systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Publicly traded companies, which often wait until after the  
close of the traditional markets at 4 p.m. to make important 
announcements, are not expected to change that practice. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
