<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Diet Drug Co. Still Wants To Settle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A court ruling against a marketer of one of  
its diet drugs will not derail American Home Products Corp.'s 
efforts to settle thousands of diet pill lawsuits filed against it, 
a spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge rejected a $100 million ``limited fund''  
settlement proposed by Interneuron Pharmaceuticals Inc. of 
Lexington, Mass., in connection with its marketing of the diet drug 
Redux, saying he was uncertain it would be fair to all who might 
have claims. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any settlement that American Home Products might reach in the  
diet drug litigation would in no way be a `limited fund' 
non-opt-out settlement, and the Interneuron decision is therefore 
inapplicable to American Home Products' position,'' spokesman Doug 
Petkus said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Petkus declined to comment on how or whether settlement talks  
are progressing. ``When and if the parties do enter into a final 
agreement, the details will become public,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 6 million people took Redux and its chemical cousin  
Pondimin. Pondimin, whose generic name is fenfluramine, was part of 
the once-popular drug combination called fen-phen. Redux and 
fenfluramine were pulled from the market in 1997 after being linked 
to heart valve problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Interneuron marketed Redux from 1996 to 1997 under an agreement  
with American Home Products' Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories division in 
St. Davids. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 25,000 people had filed claims to share in  
Interneuron's ``limited fund'' settlement, some claiming 
heart-valve damage and others, unable to document current ailments, 
claiming fear of future health problems. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 34-page memorandum Monday, U.S. District Judge Louis C.  
Bechtle said he had ``constitutional concerns'' because the deal 
would not allow claimants to opt out and seek separate trials if 
they wish. And he said Interneuron had additional assets that were 
not part of the settlement fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Interneuron proposed to place $15 million in cash and $28  
million in proceeds in the limited fund, and the fund was to 
receive $55 million in royalties from future products if those 
products succeed, a provision Bechtle called ``fraught with risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barbara Wruble, an attorney for Interneuron, said the company  
probably will appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The claimants also are considering whether to appeal Bechtle's  
ruling, said Michael Fishbein, an attorney for plaintiffs in the 
diet-drug litigation. He would not comment on the impact on overall 
settlement negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know that the ramifications of this decision are  
far-reaching insofar as the ability to reach a settlement,'' 
Fishbein said. ``As far as remainder of litigation is concerned, we 
will just proceed forward.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
