</P>
<P>
	Clinton Moves To Help Poor Nations  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton told finance ministers and  
central bankers today the United States will take a major step to 
help wipe out the debt owed by some of the world's poorest 
countries. He said his administration envisions forgiving the 
entire debt that some of the poorest nations owe the United States 
when such a step is necessary to meet basic needs and the money 
will be used for that purpose. Clinton spoke before the annual 
meetings of the World Bank and the International Moneyary fund. He 
noted that many economies are still reeling following last year's 
economic crises. 

</P>
<P>
	Execs More Bullish on 4th Quarter  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- American executives are bullish about the final  
three months of 1999, according to a Dun &AMP; Bradstreet survey that 
reports the first gain in the outlook for exports since the Asian 
financial crisis arose in mid-1997. The survey of approximately 
3,000 executives, conducted in August, had especially strong 
results in its indexes measuring sentiment about exports, sales, 
profits and employment. The survey found that a boost in hiring 
plans might further tighten labor markets, but executives said they 
did not expect wage pressures to significantly increase inflation. 

</P>
<P>
	Durable Goods Orders Rise in August  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Orders to U.S. factories for big-ticket  
manufactured goods rose 0.9 percent in August, led by an increase 
in demand for airplanes, automobiles and other transportation 
equipment. Many analysts had expected the figure to be down by that 
amount. The Commerce Department reported today that orders for 
durable goods -- items expected to last at least three years -- grew 
last month to a seasonally adjusted $206.9 billion. The increase 
followed a revised 4 percent gain in July. August's performance was 
the 12th increase in the last 15 months. 

</P>
<P>
	SkyTel Shareholders OK MCI WorldCom  
</P>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Shareholders of SkyTel Communications Inc.  
today approved the pager company's acquisition by MCI WorldCom Inc. 
for $1.3 billion in stock. Investors holding 68 percent of the 
company's stock voted in favor of the deal, which was announced in 
May. Regulatory clearance for the merger of the two 
Mississippi-based companies was granted by the Federal 
Communications Commission on Aug. 26. The deal is now expected to 
close on Friday, said John Stupka, SkyTel's president and chief 
executive. SkyTel shares were at 18 1/2, down 5/16. MCI WorldCom 
shares were at 72 5/8, down 1 9/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com To Let Anyone Sell There  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Amazon.com is inviting one and all to sell  
merchandise through its web site. Starting tomorrow, more than 
500,000 new items, including vacation packages, buffalo steaks and 
maternity clothes, will be available on Amazon.com through its new 
zSHOPS program. announced today. Amazon.com, which once sold only 
books online, has built itself into an Internet shopping hub in 
just four years. It has more than 12 million customers, up from 
10.7 million just three months ago. Amazon.com also has been 
pouring millions of dollars into outside ventures, such as online 
pharmacy drugstore.com and Internet pet shop Pets.com. Amazon stock 
soared today -- up 14 7/8 to 80 3/4. 

</P>
<P>
	CIA Sets Up Venture Capital Firm  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The CIA is publicly setting up in California's  
Silicon Valley to invest in young companies developing technologies 
with spying potential. In a nod toward the James Bond movie 
character who presides over gadgets, the spy agency named the 
company ``In-Q-It.'' Using $28 million in previously classified 
startup money from Congress, the nonprofit company will invest in 
some high-tech companies and form joint ventures with others to 
nurture Internet-age projects that could benefit the CIA, said the 
new company's chief operating officer, Gilman Louie. 

</P>
<P>
	Chevron Names New CEO  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Chevron Corp. today named a vice chairman,  
Dave O'Reilly, as its new chairman and chief executive officer, 
replacing Ken Derr, who is retiring after running the oil company 
for the last 11 years. Since Nov. 1998, O'Reilly, 52, has been 
responsible for Chevron's worldwide exploration and production 
activities, as well as the effort to cut Chevron's operating costs 
by $500 million. 

</P>
<P>
	La-Z-Boy Buying Furniture Maker  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Not sitting idle as one of the world's largest  
furniture makers, La-Z-Boy Inc. is buying Ladd Furniture Inc. in a 
$197.8 million stock deal that one analyst says ``sets up La-Z-Boy 
as an industry behemoth.'' Under the deal unveiled yesterday, 
La-Z-Boy also will assume Ladd's debt of $101.5 million. Ladd, 
based in Greensboro, N.C.,is among North America's largest 
residential furniture makers and one of the world's leading 
suppliers to hotel and motel, assisted living and government 
markets. The transaction -- requiring approval by regulators and 
Ladd shareholders -- should be completed by early 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	New Republic Editor Steps Down  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New Republic editor Charles Lane has resigned  
after running the magazine for two years. He will be replaced by 
Peter Beinart, a senior editor at the publication. Neither Lane nor 
New Republic owner and editor-in-chief Martin Peretz accepted calls 
today seeking comment. No further information on the management 
change, including when it becomes effective, was released by the 
publication. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Builder Revives Tower Plan  
</P>
<P>
	SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- A Japanese developer said today that with  
Asian economic troubles easing, it will resume construction of the 
world's tallest skyscraper next year in Shanghai. The 90-story, 
1,518-foot-tall Shanghai Financial Center is being redesigned to 
make it even taller, said Mori Building Co. president Minoru Mori. 
He wouldn't say what the new height target is. Skyscraper rivalry 
shifted to Asia when the 1,480-foot-tall Petronas Towers were 
finished in 1996 in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, and became the world's 
tallest. The main building displaced the Sears Tower of Chicago, 
which had held the title since 1973. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic reports:  
</P>
<P>
	Durable goods orders: up 0.9 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Jobless claims  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: New home sales  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Personal income  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Construction spending  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Purchasing managers  



  	   	
</P>
