<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SkyTel Shareholders OK MCI WorldCom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Shareholders of SkyTel Communications Inc.  
on Wednesday approved the pager company's acquisition by MCI 
WorldCom Inc. for $1.3 billion in stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors holding 68 percent of the company's stock voted in  
favor of the deal, which was announced in May. Regulatory clearance 
for the merger of the two Mississippi-based companies was granted 
by the Federal Communications Commission on Aug. 26. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is now expected to close on Friday, said John Stupka,  
SkyTel's president and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	SkyTel, with about 1.6 million customers, has been a leader in  
developing two-way pagers that enable customers to exchange 
messages with other pagers and send e-mail on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom is the nation's No. 2 long-distance phone company  
and one of the world's biggest operators of the ``backbone'' 
networks that make up the Internet, but has almost no stake in the 
rapidly expanding market for wireless voice and data 
communications. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson-based SkyTel fills part of that gap, but the equipment  
and the part of the radio spectrum used by paging networks aren't 
good for carrying voices or high-speed data. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, MCI WorldCom made an overture to acquire the  
mobile phone company AirTouch Communications, but was trumped by 
Vodafone PLC of Britain. MCI WorldCom then started negotiating with 
Nextel Communications, but those talks fell apart in May in a 
dispute over price. 
</P>
<P>
	Now MCI WorldCom is reportedly discussing a merger with Sprint,  
the No. 3 long-distance provider and parent of the wireless phone 
company Sprint PCS. Both companies have declined comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramkrishna Kasargod, an industry analyst with Morgan Keegan &AMP;  
Co., said the companies may be a good match. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the benefits would be that WorldCom would get exposure  
into the wireless business because Sprint has done a good job of 
building out a nationwide wireless presence,'' he said. ``With a 
national wireless presence, WorldCom would have the full suite of 
products.'' 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 19:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UN To Proceed With E. Timor Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United Nations will go ahead with a  
human rights inquiry into atrocities committed in East Timor 
despite Indonesia's rejection of the probe, the U.N. spokesman said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. investigators would like to have the cooperation of  
Indonesia's own human rights organization and access to Indonesia's 
military, but neither is required for the inquiry to go forward, 
spokesman Fred Eckhard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia's Justice Minister Muladi said Wednesday that the  
Indonesian government rejected the inquiry and would issue a 
government decree saying so. Indonesia has said it should be 
allowed to investigate the reports that its army and army-supported 
militias were involved in widespread killings and pillaging 
following a vote on East Timor's independence Aug. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia's foreign minister said Wednesday that some violence  
was inevitable and that the United Nations had to go ahead with the 
ballot or risk the world's condemnation for having denied East 
Timor's people the right to choose their future. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia might also never again have agreed to allow the East  
Timorese to decide whether they wanted to remain part of the 
country or become independent, Alexander Downer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Could it have ever been resolved in an environment of perfect  
harmony and peace? The answer to that is `no', it couldn't have 
been,'' Downer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Passions were too high and East Timor's history too violent to  
have allowed for an easy vote or an easy transition to either 
independence or special autonomy within the country, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But that didn't mean it should never be resolved. And those  
who say the ballot shouldn't have taken place are people who say 
the East Timor situation shouldn't be resolved,'' he told reporters 
after speaking before the U.N. General Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	As he spoke, the United Nations moved ahead with plans to start  
taking over some civilian control of East Timor to try to get the 
territory's water, sanitation, transport and communications systems 
going again. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas met Wednesday with senior  
U.N. officials to discuss what the United Nations could do in the 
month before Indonesia formally hands the territory over to a 
transitional U.N. authority, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Portuguese Ambassador Antonio Monteiro said the U.N. Security  
Council should expand the mandate of the mission currently in East 
Timor to allow it to start rebuilding the territory. But U.N. 
officials said that might not be necessary and could embarrass 
Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	In Geneva, the U.N. refugee agency said Wednesday that efforts  
to reach thousands of refugees in makeshift camps across the border 
in West Timor are going slowly. There have been reports of 
pro-Indonesian militias there harassing people in the camps, some 
of whom were shipped there against their will. 
</P>
<P>
	One member of a U.N.-led mission to West Timor set out on  
Wednesday for the border town of Atambua, which reportedly holds up 
to 100,000 people under militia control, the statement from U.N. 
High Commissioner for Refugees said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the provincial capital, Kupang, authorities were insisting on  
24 hours' advance notice to police from U.N. staff planning to 
visit the refugee camps. 
</P>
<P>
	UNHCR staff who went to a sports stadium in the city were  
accompanied by six policemen armed with automatic rifles and 
sticks. It held some 700 East Timorese, and another 300 were 
sheltering under tarpaulins around the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was enough food, water and sanitation facilities and no  
visible military or police presence in the area,'' UNHCR said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 01:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.H., Iowa Protect Their Turf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- In a quadrennial tussle, New Hampshire  
and Iowa officials are moving to protect their turf and defend 
challenges to their traditional spots opening the presidential 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Under pressure from other states seeking to grab some  
campaign-opening limelight, New Hampshire officials pulled a 
surprise Tuesday and set their primary date for Feb. 1, just a day 
after the tentative date for Iowa's leadoff precinct caucuses. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa officials called that ``a glitch'' that will quickly be  
fixed, but left little doubt that they want the traditional 
eight-day gap between the opening caucuses in Iowa and the first 
primary in New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	``Iowa and New Hampshire have always had an agreement that Iowa  
will go eight days before them,'' said Joe Shannahan, an aide to 
Iowa Democratic Gov. Tom Vilsack. ``We will maintain that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others counseled patience, and predicted a solution through  
quiet bargaining. 
</P>
<P>
	At stake is the campaign time and attention that presidential  
candidates and the national political media devote to states that 
open the presidential campaign season. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on agreements from the past several election cycles, Iowa  
officials had tentatively set precinct caucuses for Jan. 31, on the 
assumption that New Hampshire would hold its primary on Feb. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	But New Hampshire Secretary of State Bill Gardner threw a wrench  
into those plans by announcing the Feb. 1 date. Gardner argued he 
was reacting to then-likelihood that Delaware officials would hold 
their voting on Feb. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was enough for me to decide to set this on Feb. 1,''  
Gardner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa Republican Chairman Kayne Robinson and Democratic Chairman  
Rob Tully huddled to talk about their next step, and suggested that 
some quiet diplomacy and pressure from both political parties could 
resolve the snarl. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would like to resolve it in a way that we could stay (on  
Jan. 31) and we are working with them,'' Robinson said. ``We're 
going to continue to work very hard to make that happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got an awful lot of powerful interests working on this.  
I think what we'll see is that this will be taken care of and New 
Hampshire will go back to the eighth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tully predicted that leaders in both parties would pressure  
Delaware to move back to Feb. 15, allowing New Hampshire's date to 
return to Feb. 8. Both Tully and Robinson said, however, that they 
wouldn't rule out moving the caucuses even earlier if there was no 
change in New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	Shannahan said officials could base their decision on a state  
law requiring that Iowa's caucuses be eight days before New 
Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Vice President Al Gore led Bill Bradley in a new  
survey by Mason-Dixon Polling Research for several Iowa news 
organizations, but Bradley was close enough to suggest the 
potential for a competitive fight between the two Democratic 
presidential candidates. Texas Gov. George W. Bush led among the 
eight Republican candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore was backed by 45 percent of those questioned, compared with  
Bradley, the former New Jersey senator who was backed by 33 
percent. Bush was favored by 41 percent, followed by Steve Forbes 
with 22 percent and Elizabeth Dole with 11 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone survey was conducted Sept. 20-22 among Republicans  
and Democrats who said they were likely to attend the Jan. 31 
precinct caucuses. It has a margin of error of plus or minus 5.5 
percentage points for each group. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
