<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Decline for Third Session / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices fell Wednesday for the third  
straight session, as fears of rising inflation continued to roil 
the market. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 9/16  
point, or $5.63 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in 
the opposite direction, rose to 6.12 percent from 6.08 percent late 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices began to slide early in Wednesday's session after a  
government report of stronger-than-expected orders to manufacturers 
for durable goods in August. With the economy still growing 
briskly, worries persist that it will overheat, rekindling 
inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors continued to speculate that the Federal Reserve Board  
may raise interest rates again at its meeting Tuesday in an effort 
to keep economic growth at a noninflationary pace. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were down 3/32 to 1/16 point, while intermediate maturities fell 
7/32 to 13/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Wednesday, yields on three-month Treasury bills  
fell to 4.82 percent, and the discount fell 0.03 from Tuesday to 
4.69 percent. Six-month yields fell to 4.95 percent as the discount 
fell 0.02 percentage point to 4.76 percent. One-year yields rose to 
5.21 percent as the discount rose 0.03 percentage point to 4.95 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 5.25 percent from 5.31 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 17/32 to 112 7/32. The average yield to 
maturity of the index rose to 5.91 percent from 5.87 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
