<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lemieux Looks to Opener as Owner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANONSBURG, Pa. (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Penguins will have an  
extra passenger on their trip to Dallas for Friday's season opener. 
</P>
<P>
	But even NHL MVP Jaromir Jagr couldn't convince him to pull on a  
game sweater. 
</P>
<P>
	Seems the NHL has this rule that owners can't be players.  
</P>
<P>
	That doesn't mean that Mario Lemieux, the owner, isn't just as  
thrilled about starting a new season as was Mario Lemieux, the Hall 
of Fame player. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very excited about opening night Friday, especially  
against the Stars, the team that just won the Stanley Cup,'' 
Lemieux said Wednesday. ``It's going to be exciting for everyone in 
the organization to go there and see all of the festivities and, 
hopefully, one day to come back here and regain the cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only seven years after leading the Penguins to consecutive  
Stanley Cup titles as one of the most dominating and innovative 
scorers in NHL history, Lemieux moves into the owner's box at age 
33 -- the youngest owner in major professional sports. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux is only two years removed from playing, and several of  
his former linemates now are his employees. Bob Errey, who was 
released last week and now is a team broadcaster, played a season 
in Pittsburgh before Lemieux joined the Penguins in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	The player who seems the least affected by Lemieux's transition  
from the blue line to analyzing the bottom line is Jagr, the NHL 
scoring champion before and after Lemieux took a year off for 
health reasons in 1994-95. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've only been here a couple of times for practices and I  
haven't seen any change in attitude among the players -- except, 
maybe Jagr a little bit,'' Lemieux said. ``He's a different cat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite wrapping up his purchase of the bankrupt franchise on  
Sept. 3, Lemieux still has money matters on his mind. He continues 
to seek additional investors to put up $10 million to $15 million 
to give the Penguins the financial stability they have long lacked. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux spent last week attending the Ryder Cup matches with  
Michael Jordan, and made a second pitch to Jordan to join his 
group, Just as he did during Lemieux's charity golf tournament in 
June, Jordan gave him a thumb's down. 
</P>
<P>
	``I asked him again and he refused again,'' Lemieux said,  
smiling. ``I think he wants to buy his own (basketball) team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Lemieux is as surprised as anyone at making a relatively  
easy transition from retired millionaire player and golf addict to 
owner. He is more than a figurehead; he visits team offices nearly 
daily to learn the ropes of ownership from newly hired team 
executives Tom Rooney and Ken Sawyer. Lemieux also will sit on the 
NHL Board of Governors. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, dressed in a natty dark blue suit and matching blue  
tie, said club employees still can't get over watching him keep 
regular office hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was very surprised when I started this new job and new life  
that I felt very comfortable,'' he said. ``I've surrounded myself 
with smart people who have taught me a lot of things, and I feel 
like I'm learning very quickly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux is keeping a hands-off role on hockey matters, including  
the re-signing of defenseman Darius Kasparaitis to a $3 million, 
two-year contract that may have put the payroll slightly over 
budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux won't seek out general manager Craig Patrick to offer  
advice, but will wait until Patrick seeks it. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the best in business,'' Lemieux said. ``We gave a budget  
to Craig at the beginning of the year and he has to meet that 
budget. I have to answer to our investors and the people that have 
supported me and believed in me throughout this process. If we're 
over budget, I'm sure Craig will do something about it in the near 
future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins have sold 9,000 season tickets, about 1,000 more  
than last year but thousands below Lemieux's initial projection of 
12,000. However, Lemieux didn't close on the purchase until two 
months later than expected, delaying the most ambitious marketing 
campaign in team history. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remain very optimistic that we'll get the support we need  
from our fans. We've made great strides over the last month,'' he 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
