<DOCNO> APW19990929.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 14:21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jaguars' Lake Eyes Steelers Fans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- When Jaguars safety Carnell Lake left  
Pittsburgh, he knew eventually he would have to return. What Lake 
won't know until Sunday is how Steelers fans will respond when he 
comes back. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a common feeling for former Steelers, that long list of  
free-agent defectors that grows each year. 
</P>
<P>
	Lake, who left Pittsburgh for Jacksonville after last season,  
remembers Chad Brown and Willie Williams being booed upon their 
returns. Greg Lloyd got a warm reception. Rod Woodson received 
mixed reviews. 
</P>
<P>
	None of those players, however, ended up with the team that  
supplanted the Steelers at the top of the AFC Central and has begun 
to make a claim as Pittsburgh's top rival. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure what will happen,'' Lake said. ``I'll just gear  
myself for the worst, the boos and everything. But whatever 
reaction I get, positive or negative, I know they'll still remember 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, they will.  
</P>
<P>
	Lake spent 10 years in Pittsburgh, where he built a reputation  
as a hardworking playmaker who was willing to sacrifice his own 
game for the sake of the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody will forget his shift from his natural position of  
safety, to play cornerback over most of the last two seasons, when 
injuries altered the defense. 
</P>
<P>
	They loved him for his willingness to stay, and thrive, despite  
the free-agent defections that came so often. And they were unhappy 
that the Steelers refused to offer him a contract when his latest 
one expired. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the same business principles that forced so many others  
out of Pittsburgh finally had the same effect on Lake. The Jaguars 
offered him $18 million for four seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very disappointing to see that happen to a very  
competitive team,'' Lake said. ``We were going to the playoffs 
every year, we thought we had Super Bowl chances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jaguars may give Lake the best chance to win a Super Bowl  
ring that is the main piece missing from a career in which he has 
made four Pro Bowls and missed only six of 163 games. 
</P>
<P>
	His presence on a defense being run by Dom Capers -- a former  
Steelers coach -- has helped rocket the Jaguars to No. 4 in the 
league in yards allowed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Carnell has seen just about everything you can see from an  
offense,'' said rookie cornerback Fernando Bryant. ``He's been in 
the Pro Bowl four times. It's the way he practices, plays, 
everything. He's the consummate pro. As a rookie, seeing that, you 
can only try to live up to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In many ways, his past successes are the biggest forces working  
against Lake as he prepares to be introduced at Three Rivers 
Stadium for the first time in a visiting uniform. 
</P>
<P>
	The question, meanwhile, will linger until kickoff: do Steelers  
fans still like Lake? 
</P>
<P>
	``They all know he was a commodity to the organization and to  
the city for 10 years,'' said former Steeler Leon Searcy. ``But 
come Sunday, they're going to act like they don't know him. They're 
going to try to beat him down any way they can to get him out of 
his game. Because they know as well as anybody, that he's 
definitely an impact player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lake says he'll accept whatever reaction he gets.  
</P>
<P>
	``I would never say anything negative about Pittsburgh fans,''  
Lake said. ``They're just loyal to Pittsburgh. That's how they are. 
I don't blame them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 18:00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nike Loses Co. Name Battle in Spain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEAVERTON, Ore. (AP) -- Nike has lost a legal battle in Spain  
that has lasted nearly a decade over who has rights to the company 
name -- the shoe giant or a small sporting goods distributor that 
owns the Spanish rights to the name for the Greek goddess of 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The practical effect in Spain could be that Nike can sell  
clothing only with its swoosh logo and no name, a change Nike says 
would have little impact on overall sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing that's important to note is the decision doesn't  
impact our ability to sell Nike shoes, accessories or equipment in 
Spain. This has to do only with Nike apparel in Spain,'' said Lee 
Weinstein, Nike spokesman at company headquarters in Beaverton. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spanish Supreme Court ruled last week in favor of former  
Nike distributor Cidesport, ending a nine-year lawsuit over rights 
to the Nike name, which Cidesport Chairman Lorenzo Rosal claimed 
was registered in Spain in 1932, long before the U.S. company was 
created. 
</P>
<P>
	Calls to Rosal and Cidesport in Spain were not immediately  
returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Nike officials are still deciding how to respond to the ruling,  
Weinstein said. He declined to say whether the company now would 
negotiate with Cidesport. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling does not require Nike to withdraw clothing already in  
stores, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Europe has been the best regional market overall for Nike in  
recent years, but Britain is tops in sales by far, with Spain 
trailing well behind, said Brenda Gall, an analyst with Merrill 
Lynch in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't know what will come of it,'' Gall said. ``But  
Spain is one of their top five markets in Europe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Spanish attorney, Juan Amigo, had bought the Nike trademark in  
1981 from a Barcelona sock company that had registered it based on 
a photograph of a statue of the Greek goddess Nike. 
</P>
<P>
	Nike had refused to negotiate with Amigo and Cidesport, who had  
asked up to $30 million for rights to the trademark. 
</P>
<P>
	Cidesport objected to Nike using the brand name in Spain during  
the 1992 Olympic Games in Barcelona. The Spanish government asked a 
Barcelona judge to allow Nike to continue selling its clothing 
under its name until a ruling had been issued. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
