<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Regulators OK 2 Big Oil Mergers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- European Union regulators on Wednesday  
approved Exxon Corp.'s $82 billion purchase of Mobil Corp. after 
securing antitrust concessions in the deal to create the world's 
largest oil company. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is awaiting approval from the U.S. Federal Trade  
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	To secure EU approval, Exxon and Mobil agreed to pull out of  
businesses where the EU had concerns about competition in the 
15-nation bloc. 
</P>
<P>
	``As initially notified, the operation would have created or  
strengthened dominant positions on eight markets,'' the European 
Commission said in a statement. ``Exxon and Mobil have made a 
series of undertakings to eliminate those concerns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commission said Mobil had agreed to dissolve the fuels part  
of a European joint-venture with BP Amoco, and to divest its share 
in the Aral network of gas stations in Germany, Austria and 
Luxembourg. 
</P>
<P>
	Mobil also agreed to drop its natural gas trading business in  
the Netherlands; and to sell certain rights in natural gas storage 
in southern Germany, the commission said. 
</P>
<P>
	The merged company will divest businesses in the European market  
for base oils used to make lubricants, where it would have had a 
market share of over 40 percent. Exxon also agreed to dispose of 
its aviation lubricants business where the commission feared the 
merger would create a dominant position in the worldwide market. 
</P>
<P>
	At the commission's insistence, the companies will also divest  
interests in fuel pipelines supplying London's Gatwick airport. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, Exxon and Mobil welcomed the commission's  
decision and confirmed they would comply fully with the EU's 
conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	In another huge oil company deal, the European Commission also  
gave the green light to BP Amoco PLC's merger with Atlantic 
Richfield Co. It also awaits Federal Trade Commission approval. 
</P>
<P>
	But to allay competition concerns in the transport of natural  
gas to Britain from fields in the North Sea, as well as in the 
processing of Britain's North Sea gas, BP Amoco agreed to sell some 
pipeline and processing units. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission said its investigations into the two mergers had  
dispelled concerns that the recent spate of mega-mergers in the oil 
sector would create a dangerously small group of big players 
dominating oil exploration worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 'super majors' would still be facing competitive  
constraints from smaller oil companies, and countries on whose 
territory oil and gas is found have no incentives to let oil 
companies restrict production,'' the EU concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission investigates all mergers and takeovers with a  
major impact on markets within the bloc, and can demand changes or 
veto those judged to violate EU rules on fair business competition. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
