<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Tide Hits Florida's Coasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Poisonous red tide algae blooms --  
which can cause eye and respiratory problems and kill large numbers 
of fish -- are making a rare appearance this week on Florida's east 
coast and along the Gulf of Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	``I live two blocks off the ocean,'' said Jimmie Wilkins, head  
of Jacksonville Beach's parks, recreation, and ocean-rescue 
department. ``The breeze was blowing and you could just feel it in 
your throat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	State health officials on Wednesday were urging residents of  
beach areas where red tide has been reported to close their windows 
and run their air conditioners, and if outdoors to wear a paper 
filter mask. 
</P>
<P>
	Beaches remained open, however.  
</P>
<P>
	While common in southwest Florida, red tide is unusual along the  
Atlantic coast and the upper Gulf of Mexico, according to Beverly 
Roberts, research director for the Florida Marine Research 
Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	The critter causing all the problem is known as Gymnodinium  
breve, a stingray-shaped single cell with two whiplike tails. Even 
pieces of the organism contain toxins. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
