<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Sept. 29, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	AP Investigation Uncovers Korean War Civilian Killings  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- South Korean civilian refugees were killed by  
the U.S. military in an unwritten chapter of the Korean War, 
according to an Associated Press investigation that cites villagers 
and veterans who witnessed or participated in the incident in the 
early days of the war. Many women and children were among the 
hundreds who died underneath a bridge at No Gun Ri, a hamlet about 
100 miles southeast of the South Korean capital of Seoul. American 
soldiers, in their third day at the warfront, believed that North 
Korean infiltrators were among the refugees. Once-classified 
documents show U.S. commanders issued orders to treat civilians as 
``enemy.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Bell Atlantic Readies Long-distance  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's largest local phone company, Bell  
Atlantic, asked federal regulators today to let it enter the New 
York long-distance market. By year's end, it could be the first 
regional Bell company to offer long-distance service to its local 
customers. Bell Atlantic, which serves the Northeast and 
mid-Atlantic states, filed its application with the Federal 
Communications Commission detailing the steps it has taken to open 
its local phone business in New York to competition. That's the 
standard the company must meet, under the 1996 Telecommunications 
Act, before regulators will let it provide long-distance in its 
region. 

</P>
<P>
	Study: Infants Sleep Safer in Cribs  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Supporting recommendations that all infants sleep  
in cribs, a new study found that an average of 64 young children 
die each year while sleeping in bed with their parents or other 
adults. Children risk getting their heads trapped or being rolled 
on by an adult when sleeping in adult beds, according to the study 
by the U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission. The study, 
published in the October issue of the Archives of Pediatrics and 
Adolescent Medicine, found that the greatest number of deaths 
involved children under 1 who became trapped between a mattress and 
a bed frame. 

</P>
<P>
	Israel Urges Syria on Peace Talks  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- In a key address to the U.N. General  
Assembly, Israel's foreign minister today urged Syria to start 
talking peace without conditions. David Levy also called on Lebanon 
to enter negotiations on a possible withdrawal of Israeli troops 
from southern Lebanon. Also during his speech, Levy reiterated 
Israel's longstanding position that a united Jerusalem will remain 
the capital of the Jewish state -- an issue that is supposed to be 
decided in final status negotiations with the Palestinians. Levy 
addressed the General Assembly six days after Palestinian leader 
Yasser Arafat appealed to its 188 member nations for increased 
support for an independent Palestinian state which he said would be 
established in the coming year. 

</P>
<P>
	eBay Moves Against 'Piggybackers'  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Online auctioneer eBay is cracking down on  
new Internet services that sift through auction Web sites to find 
the best prices for potential bidders. Spokesman Kevin Pursglove 
said the action was made to protect eBay from companies or 
individuals seeking to ``piggy-back'' on eBay's success. Several 
new Web sites search sites for goods being auctioned and compare 
prices offered. BiddersEdge.com and another service, Ruby Lane, 
stopped using eBay auction data when eBay refused to give them 
permission. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Says Gunmaker Can Be Sued  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A California appeals court ruled today that  
the families of eight people shot to death in a law office in 1993 
are entitled to sue Navegar Inc., the manufacturer of a TEC-DC9 gun 
used in the massacre. This is the first time any appellate court 
has allowed a gun maker to be sued for a criminal shooting. The 
justices acknowledged that other appeals courts to consider the 
issue have ruled that manufacturers of legal, non-defective guns 
cannot be sued for their criminal misuse. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rebounded sharply on Thursday. The  
Nikkei gained 217.25 points to 17,499.53 in early trading. In New 
York, the Dow ended down 62.05 at 10,213.48. 

</P>
<P>
	Mets Stop Braves 9-2  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- John Olerud's grand slam highlighted a startling  
seven-run burst in the fourth inning and the New York Mets stopped 
a seven-game losing streak, beating the Atlanta Braves 9-2 tonight. 
New York, which had a team-record nine hits in the inning, ended 
the Braves' eight-game winning string. But while the outcome 
clearly improved the mood at Shea Stadium, it was not certain to 
help the Mets in the standings. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  






  	   	
</P>
