<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Interviews Consultants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton interviewed potential  
campaign media strategists Wednesday, moving ahead with plans for 
her expected Senate race in New York next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Consultants David Doak and David Axelrod were among those  
invited to the White House for interviews with the first lady and a 
group of top advisers, according to Democratic sources speaking on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Mrs. Clinton's Senate exploratory committee  
refused to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Doak was the media consultant for Gray Davis' winning  
campaign for governor in California and for the losing 
gubernatorial campaign of Democrat Peter Vallone in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Doak also ran the media operations for David Dinkins when he won  
the New York City mayor's race in 1989 over Republican Rudolph 
Giuliani and again in 1993 when Dinkins lost to Giuliani. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani is considered the likely Republican candidate in the  
race to succeed retiring Democratic Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	Axelrod has served as media consultant for New York state  
Comptroller H. Carl McCall and for Andrew Span, the Westchester 
County executive. The New York suburbs, including Westchester, are 
crucial battlegrounds in statewide races. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Doak nor Axelrod immediately returned telephone messages  
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady also is considering a day-to-day manager for her  
campaign. Among the names mentioned are her former chief of staff, 
Maggie Williams, and Bill DiBlasio, a veteran New York Democratic 
operative who is the regional director in New York for the U.S. 
Department of Housing and Urban Development. 
  	   	
</P>
