<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbine Martyr May Not Have Been </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Cassie Bernall may not have been the  
student who said yes when asked by one of the Columbine High School 
gunmen if she believed in God, a story repeated around the world 
after her death. 
</P>
<P>
	Val Schnurr, 18, said in Tuesday's Denver Post that it was she  
who uttered that response after a shotgun blast knocked her out 
from under a library table where she hid during April's attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Schnurr said that as she bled from her wounds, she pleaded,  
``Oh my God, oh my God, don't let me die.'' That, she said, was 
when one of the student shooters asked her if she believed in God 
and she said yes. 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Schnurr said she crawled away as the gunman reloaded. She  
suffered nearly three dozen shotgun wounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Lauren Townsend, a friend hiding with her, was killed, along  
with Miss Bernall, 10 other students and a teacher. The two 
teen-age gunmen killed themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said a student who helped authorities retrace the events  
in the library got sick when he realized it was Miss Schnurr's 
table, not Miss Bernall's, that he was pointing out in describing 
the exchange between gunman and victim. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheriff's spokesman Steve Davis said determining who said yes is  
not a priority for investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have conflicting witness statements from several kids who  
were in the library,'' he said. ``But this is not something we're 
out to prove or disprove. It's not really a part of the 
investigation we're doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Bernall's story turned her into a martyr who had found God  
after falling in with the wrong crowd, dabbling in the occult and 
experimenting with drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Her mother, Misty Bernall, wrote a book -- ``She Said Yes: The  
Unlikely Martyrdom of Cassie Bernall,'' and she has been honored at 
youth rallies. 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Schnurr, who now attends college, said she has no idea  
whether Miss Bernall was asked the same question in her final 
moments. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to be famous or deemed anything,'' she said. ``I  
said I believed in God out of respect for myself and respect for 
God. That's it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a Littleton church will not replant two of 15  
memorial trees cut down Sunday by relatives and friends of 
Columbine victims. 
</P>
<P>
	``We planted 15 trees, and there are 13 trees there now, and  
we'll leave it just like that,'' said Dave McPherson, pastor at the 
West Bowles Community Church, where the trees were planted in a 
memorial garden. 
</P>
<P>
	Friends and relatives of shooting victims Dan Rohrbough and Kyle  
Velasquez cut down two trees in protest. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not mean, heartless people -- we just lost our son,''  
said Rich Petrone, Rohrbough's stepfather. ``We're just adamant 
about not honoring murderers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Church officials had said the two trees were not meant to honor  
gunmen Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, but were for their families. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990929.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 19:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
