<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Gov. Signs Seat Belt Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Vehicles that transport farm workers  
will need to have seat belts under a new law prompted by the deaths 
of 13 tomato pickers whose van crashed into a tractor-trailer. 
</P>
<P>
	The law, signed Wednesday by Gov. Gray Davis, takes effect Jan.  
1. 
</P>
<P>
	Current state law allows farm-worker vehicles that carry more  
than 10 passengers to be classified as buses and operate without 
passenger seat belts. 
</P>
<P>
	The new law was proposed after the crash that killed 13 in  
Fresno County last month. The van was driven by an unlicensed 
driver, and most of the occupants were sitting on carpeted benches 
without seat belts. 
</P>
<P>
	United Farm Workers spokesman Marc Grossman called the new law  
``a good first step.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
