<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Refund Sought From Pa. Dance Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENSBURG, Pa. (AP) -- The Mummers -- known for their elaborately  
choreographed New Year's Day parades with hundreds of feathered 
dancers playing music and twirling through Philadelphia -- are being 
accused of being too drab. 
</P>
<P>
	The Greensburg Volunteer Fire Department expected all the flair  
of New Year's Day when it paid the group's Greater Overbrook String 
Band $12,138 to perform for a parade Saturday where the state 
firemen's convention was the host. 
</P>
<P>
	Now it's demanding a refund.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was utterly disgraceful,'' convention chairman Glenn E.  
Thomas said in Wednesday's Greensburg Tribune-Review. ``Everyone 
said they were lousy and they looked lousy. ... They sounded like 
they picked some people off the street to come here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The contract was for 25 costumed musicians and an unspecified  
number of dancers, as many as 50 Mummers in all, to join the 
four-hour parade. But only 21 dancers and musicians showed up, 
Thomas said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They owe us a lot of money,'' Thomas said. He said the  
department hadn't decided how large a refund to request. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the Philadelphia Mummers said he was not aware  
of any complaints about the performance. The group has 19 musical 
organizations with about 15,000 members. Their performances raise 
money for the Philadelphia New Year's Day parade. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
