<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Durable Goods Orders Rise in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Strong demand for cars and airplanes pushed up  
overall orders for big-ticket manufactured goods in August, fresh 
evidence that U.S. manufacturers are still gaining ground after a 
global financial crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Orders to U.S. factories for all durable goods -- those expected  
to last at least three years -- unexpectedly rose 0.9 percent last 
month to a seasonally adjusted $206.9 billion, the Commerce 
Department said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	August's performance -- the 12th increase in the last 15 months --  
was better than many analysts had expected. They were forecasting 
orders would fall by 0.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``All but a few barometers of manufacturing activity are  
currently running full throttle with expectations of an impressive 
second-half performance well in the making,'' said Richard 
Yamarone, an economist with Argus Research Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, durable goods orders rose a revised 4 percent, better  
than the government previously estimated, and the biggest one-month 
gain since November 1997 when orders grew by 4.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the strong report, many analysts said they don't expect  
the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates for a third time this 
year when its policy-makers meet next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's looks more and more like the Fed will sit tight and let  
this one go by,'' said Robert Dederick, an economic consultant with 
The Northern Trust Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Zandi, an economist at Regional Financial Associates,  
agreed that the central bank will probably leave its target for the 
federal funds rate, the interest that banks charge on overnight 
loans, at 5.25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But Zandi believes the Fed will switch its policy directive --  
intended to signal future moves -- from neutral to one favoring an 
interest rate increase. 
</P>
<P>
	August's increase in durable goods orders was led by a 4.6  
percent gain -- the fourth consecutive increase -- in orders for 
transportation equipment. In July, transportation equipment orders 
rose 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Taylor, chief economist for the National Automobile Dealers  
Association, said Americans feeling wealthy from stock market 
gains, higher incomes and savings left over after refinancing homes 
continue to be in a buying mood. 
</P>
<P>
	The auto industry expects a record 16.8 million units of cars  
and light trucks to be sold this year, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The transportation sector is often volatile from month to month  
because it includes such big-ticket purchases as airplanes. 
Excluding transportation, orders for durable goods would have 
fallen 0.2 percent in August, the fifth decrease in the last eight 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists expect foreign demand for U.S. durable goods to  
continue to improve as economies in Asia and Latin America recover 
from the global crisis. That crisis had cut sharply into American 
manufacturers' overseas sales and also opened them up to stiffer 
competition from cheaper imports. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in overall durable-goods orders in August came  
despite decreases in other areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Orders for industrial machinery, including computers and machine  
tools, fell 2 percent in August, following a hefty 10.5 percent 
gain in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Electronic and other electrical equipment, which includes  
everything from semiconductors, circuit boards and 
telecommunications equipment to home appliances, fell 0.1 percent 
after a strong 7.1 percent gain in July. 
</P>
<P>
	And orders for primary metals, the category that includes steel,  
fell 1.7 percent in August, down for the first time since March. In 
July, orders for primary metals rose a solid 2.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Shipments of durable goods, a good sign of current demand, went  
up by 1.3 percent in August. This was the 13th increase in the last 
15 months. Jerry Jasinowski, president of the National Association 
of Manufacturers, said he expects healthy demand in coming months. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
